<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     12-07 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Beef Trade Undergoing Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's beef trade is undergoing rapid
changes as production declines in 1989 and production falters in
some major countries.
   One result, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday, is that
the United States is edging ahead of New Zealand as a world-class
beef exporter.
   U.S. exports are estimated at 450,000 metric tons, up from
313,000 tons in 1988, the department's Foreign Agricultural Service
reported. Exports are expected to rise to about 508,000 tons in
1990.
   Most of the increase is the result of larger sales to Japan
under last year's trade liberalization by Tokyo to open the door to
more beef and citrus.
   New Zealand's total beef and veal exports, meanwhile, are
estimated at 439,000 tons in 1989 and 368,000 tons in 1990.
Production rose this year as drought forced more cattle to
slaughter.
   U.S. imports of beef, which reached 1.1 million tons in 1988,
are expected to decline this year to around 990,000 tons, the
report said. The decrease is the result of smaller shipments from
Australia, where production is down and more meat was diverted to
the lucrative Japanese market.
   The report said U.S. beef imports in 1990 are likely to decline
slightly, to around 970,000 tons, as Australia continues exporting
to Japan.
   ``U.S. beef exports grew at a faster rate than those of the
other five countries during the 1980s, rising from sixth to fourth
position by 1988,'' the report said. ``In 1989, it is expected that
the United States will surpass New Zealand to become the third
largest beef exporter in the world.''
   The top six beef exporters in 1989 are: Australia, 823,000 tons;
the 12-nation European Economic Community, 759,000; United States,
450,000; New Zealand, 439,000; Brazil, 370,000; and Argentina,
350,000.
   Overall, global beef and veal production is expected to decline
this year to about 45.2 million metric tons from 45.3 million tons
in 1988, the report said. Much of the decease occurred in the EEC,
Argentina, Brazil and Australia.
   The situation in the major beef producing countries is watched
closely by USDA trade analysts and livestock producers,
particularly conditions in Australia and New Zealand.
   Cattle herds are expected to increase in Australia to about 25.3
million head by 1991 from 24.3 million at the beginning of 1989,
the report said.
   ``Dampening a more rapid increase in the herd size is an
attractive wool market and expansion in the sheep industry,'' the
report said. ``Without this competition for resources, total cattle
numbers could increase more rapidly.''
   In New Zealand, drought forced cattle slaughter to about 3.3
million head this year from 3.1 million in 1988. But slaughter may
decline to around 2.8 million head in 1990, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says it will soon
pay wheat and barley producers about $175 million in ``deficiency''
payments for participating in the government's 1989 acreage program.
   Keith Bjerke, executive vice president of the department's
Commodity Credit Corp., said Wednesday that the payments to wheat
and barley farmers will be made in cash through local offices of
the Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service.
   Wheat payments will total about $168 million and barley $7
million. No payments will be made for 1989 oats. The payments will
include a deduction for advance payments earlier this year.
   Deficiency payments are made to help make up the difference
between a target price and the higher of the price support loan
rate or a five-month market price average.
   For example, the target price for wheat this year is $4.10 per
bushel and the basic loan rate is $2.57 per bushel. The market
price average for five months was $3.78 per bushel.
   Thus, the deficiency payment rate would be 32 cents per bushel,
the difference between the target and the market price. An advance
of 25 cents per bushel was made, so farmers will get 7 cents per
bushel at final settlement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reduction in the use of wheat as animal feed
is partly responsible for a sharp jump in global corn trade, says
the Agriculture Department.
   In the last four years, world corn shipments have increased an
estimated 28 percent, the largest increase since the late 1970s,
the department's Foreign Agricultural Service said Wednesday in a
report.
   ``There has been some worldwide step-up in animal feeding,
particularly in the (Soviet Union) and major East Asian markets,''
the report said. ``But, in the last two years, an additional reason
for the sharp expansion ... is the reduced use of wheat for feed,
caused by relatively low global wheat supplies.''
   As a result, wheat has become more expensive in relation to the
livestock feeding value of corn.
   Further, the report said, U.S. corn exports have nearly doubled
in the last few years, while exports of other foreign suppliers
have dropped by one-third, due to ``shifts to more profitable crops
like oilseeds, increased domestic utilization'' and poor crops.
   ``The net result is that the U.S. now provides nearly 80 percent
of the world's corn export needs, up dramatically from just a few
years ago,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
