<FIRST>r a PM-People-Coleman     12-07 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Coleman,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor Says Mother's Attempt to Control His Estate is Vindictive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Coleman called his mother's attempt to
wrest control of his estate vindictive, and his lawyer said
allegations in her court request may damage the actor's career.
   Coleman, 21, and attorney Charles Wake responded Wednesday to
Edmonia Sue Coleman's statements in court documents asserting her
son was incapable of handling his $6 million fortune.
   ``My mother's latest legal action obviously stems from her
frustration at not being able to control my life,'' said Coleman,
star of the old ``Diff'rent Strokes'' TV series.
   Mrs. Coleman's conservatorship petition, filed Monday, said his
deteriorating physical and mental condition puts him at
``significant risk of financial exploitation.''
   ``The allegations upon which Sue Coleman's petition is based are
simply not true,'' said Wake. ``This sort of tactic will only
backfire because it will expose Gary's parents to additional
liability for malicious prosecution.
   ``The potential damage to Gary's career is enormous, and this
sort of accusation can be extremely harmful even though it has no
foundation whatsoever.''
   Mrs. Coleman asked that a conservator be appointed for her son
and that U.S. Trust Co. of California be placed in control of
assets that include $6 million in property and annual income of
$750,000.
   A Superior Court hearing on the request was scheduled for Jan. 3.
   It was latest action in the continuing legal wrangle between
Coleman and his parents.
   In February, Coleman filed suit in Santa Monica against his
parents and former business adviser Anita DeThomas, alleging they
improperly profited from his financial success.
   The lawsuit alleges the Colemans and DeThomas diverted his
profits and assets to themselves. Coleman said in his suit that he
felt his parents were unduly influenced by DeThomas.
   ``I was very hurt by the vindictive response it caused,''
Coleman said Wednesday.
   Coleman was born with an atrophied right kidney and has
undergone two transplants during a childhood that required frequent
dialysis and medications, the court documents said.
   Mrs. Coleman said she was concerned about her son's business
manager, Dion Mial, whom she described as a 25-year-old unemployed
Michael Jackson impersonator.
   Coleman was 10 when ``Diff'rent Strokes'' made it debut in
November 1978 and his character Arnold Jackson, opposite co-star
Todd Bridges, became a hit with young viewers. His twinkling eyes,
pudgy cheeks and flawless timing helped make the TV situation
comedy a ratings winner.
</TEXT>
