<FIRST>r a PM-MillionaireBenefactor     12-07 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Millionaire Benefactor,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Benefactor `Out of Money,' But Appeals for Help Still Roll in</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   T. David Franklin wants the world know
he's broke. But appeals for money, like the one containing pieces
of the Berlin Wall, keep streaming in.
   The package was delivered even though it was addressed to ``The
Millionaire David Franklin'' in ``Portland, Maine U.S.A.''
   It came from a young West Berlin woman who had read news reports
about the 32-year-old benefactor's efforts to help residents in his
adopted city of Portland start their own businesses.
   ``As a sign that a new time begins, I send you a little part of
the original Berlin Wall _ a sign that people should come together
and help each other in peace, love and harmony,'' the woman wrote
in asking Franklin to finance her health-related studies.
   Appeals have poured in by the thousands, said Franklin. He says
his life has changed dramatically in the six weeks since he placed
a classified ad in local newspapers offering to bankroll first-time
entrepreneurs and provide them with office space and business
advice.
   Enthusiasm and hard work were the traits the community college
dropout from a blue-collar Baltimore suburb sought in examining the
flood of applicants before selecting 15 beneficiaries of his
interest-free loans.
   ``These were people who didn't need a push,'' he said. ``They
had the enthusiasm. They just needed the guidance.''
   After writing checks totaling more than $220,000 and wondering
aloud how he will pay his next mortgage payment on the apartment
house where he lives and works, Franklin has a standard reply to
the unending pleas:
   ``I'm broke. I'm out of money.''
   Undaunted, applicants often ask Franklin to put their names on a
waiting list for any future largesse.
   Franklin acknowledged that, though he may be strapped for cash,
he probably remains a millionaire on paper. That's because of the
appreciation in value of real estate he accumulated in Baltimore,
New Hampshire and Maine as his career as a computer salesman
blossomed.
   He resigned his lucrative sales job last spring out of boredom
and invested in a computer company in Portland. He then looked at
job possibilities in the area, found nothing of interest, and
decided to use his business talents to help others.
   Franklin insists he was ``just an average guy'' before his
newspaper ad made him an international celebrity and propelled him
into 16-hour workdays.
   Recipients of Franklin's seed money include several welfare
recipients, a recently discharged serviceman and an ex-convict
trying to earn a living as an artist.
   The start-up money has ranged from as little as $200 for
supplies and equipment to help a young woman begin a cleaning
business to $100,000 to publish the comic book artist's work.
   Form months, 23-year-old Bonnie Robinson wanted to open the
cleaning business to get off welfare, but couldn't afford a vacuum
cleaner or other supplies.
   So she answered Franklin's ad and he helped her buy the
equipment.
   But she admits to being leery after first reading the ad: ``I
thought maybe it was a guy who wanted to kidnap people and sell
children, so I made sure not to bring my daughter.''
   Franklin, who embarked on the project three months after his
arrival in Portland, said the role of benefactor is a weighty
burden.
   ``A lot of people don't realize this but it's a big
responsibility when you're dealing with people's dreams,'' he said.
``They're looking up to you as an answer. It's frightening.''
   Diane Branscomb, associate director of the Small Business
Development Center at the University of Southern Maine, said people
applying to Franklin should be cautious because they are vulnerable
when they start a business, even if it is with someone else's money.
   ``They could put in the time and effort and blood, sweat and
tears and lose the whole kit and caboodle,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
