<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Frank     12-07 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Frank,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prostitute Testifies in Barney Frank Ethics Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A male prostitute who testified before the
House ethics committee on his relationship with Rep. Barney Frank
remains under subpoena and may be called back for additional
testimony, the panel's chairman says.
   Steven Gobie, who claims to have run a male prostitution ring
out of Frank's Capitol Hill apartment, testified for four hours
Wednesday at a closed meeting of the ethics committee.
   In past comments, Gobie had suggested that he had information
embarrassing to other members of Congress besides Frank, D-Mass.
But after the hearing, the ethics panel's chairman, Rep. Julian
Dixon, D-Calif., said Gobie's testimony did not expand the scope of
the investigation.
   Dixon said Gobie may be called back for additional testimony,
but that the investigation ``isn't any broader'' as a result of the
information he provided Wednesday.
   Frank has said he had a brief sexual relationship with Gobie
after meeting him and paying him $80 for sex in 1985. He said he
later hired Gobie with personal funds to serve as a housekeeper and
driver from July 1985 through August 1987.
   Frank has acknowledged that he intervened with Virginia
probation authorities on Gobie's behalf. But he denies other
allegations by Gobie, including that he knew Gobie was running a
prostitution ring from his apartment, and that Gobie evidently took
advantage of him.
   Frank had acknowledged his homosexuality before Gobie's
allegations were made.
   Leaving the session, Gobie said he was not out to destroy
Frank's reputation and career.
   ``I think he's a very fine person. I always have and I always
will. I think he's one of the best people up on the hill,'' Gobie
said.
   Frank has not yet testified to the committee. Neither Frank nor
his attorney, Stephen Sachs, attended Wednesday's session.
   Dixon said the committee will continue its investigation through
the current congressional recess, which is scheduled to end Jan. 23.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
