<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-RighttoDie     12-07 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Right to Die,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Considers `Right to Die' Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Cruzan has watched with anguish for nearly
seven years as his daughter lies unconscious in a Missouri hospital
and he says listening to the Supreme Court consider her fate was
yet another sad event.
   It ``certainly was a very painful thing to sit through,'' Cruzan
said after the the justices heard arguments on whether his
daughter's feeding tube should be removed.
   ``I would like to be able to express my feelings to them why we
are very comfortable with our decision, why we feel that we are
doing what Nancy would want us to do,'' he said.
   Cruzan, a 55-year-old sheet metal worker from southwestern
Missouri, and his wife, want the nation's highest court to grant
their request for removal of a feeding tube sustaining their
brain-damaged daughter, Nancy.
   On Wednesday, justices for the first time took up the
``right-to-die'' issue as they heard oral arguments by attorneys in
the case of the 32-year-old woman, who has been in what doctors
call a persistent vegetative state since a 1983 automobile
accident. The Missouri Supreme Court has ruled that doctors cannot
remove the tube that supplies food and water keeping Ms. Cruzan
alive.
   The family's attorney, William Colby, told the justices that if
Ms. Cruzan were ``lucid for a moment and could come before this
court,'' she would ``choose liberty'' and ask for removal of the
feeding tube. But she will never recover to do that, he said.
   Assistant Attorney General Robert Presson of Missouri maintained
that Ms. Cruzan's parents have no right to permit their daughter's
death, especially without ``clear and convincing evidence'' she
would choose to die.
   Letting her die ``goes against the state's interest in
preventing suicide,'' he said.
   Solicitor General Kenneth Starr, the Bush administration's top
courtroom lawyer, supported the state's position.
   A ruling by the court is expected by July. The justices recently
have been reluctant to expand individual rights, but they gave no
clear sign on the outcome of the case as they questioned the
lawyers during arguments.
   Colby said after the case that he didn't expect the court to
issue a broad ruling on the the right-to-die question. An estimated
10,000 people in this country are being kept alive in a manner
similar to that used for Ms. Cruzan. Legal and medical officials
say the court's ruling could set a precedent in determining the
limits of life-sustaining care.
   Doctors say Ms. Cruzan could live for 30 years or more in her
current condition unless the feeding tube is removed. Her body is
rigid, her hands and feet constricted and bent into claw shapes.
She can breathe on her own and at times her eyes are open and move
randomly.
   Cruzan and his wife, Joyce, an older daughter and two
grandchildren watched the Supreme Court proceedings.
   Afterward, he expressed concerns about the possible effects on
other families if the high court denies his daughter a right to
die. He contended it would force people to consider initially not
ordering life-sustaining treatment for fear that it could not later
be stopped.
   ``This puts families in a terrible situation of being faced with
making a decision about life support when there is still hope, when
it still might do some good,'' he said.
   Asked how he thought the oral arguments played out to the
justices, Cruzan replied, ``I have no idea. I'm not an attorney.
I'm just a spectator.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
