<FIRST>r w PM-DrugVerdict     12-07 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Verdict,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeal Planned in Big D.C. Drug Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for a man convicted of operating a
drug ring that took in $2 million a week in the nation's capital
say they will appeal the verdict, while U.S. Attorney Jay B.
Stephens says the convicted dealer will now face other charges.
   Rayful Edmond III, 24, was convicted Wednesday of operating a
cocaine distribution network that prosecutors said was responsible
for up to 30 percent of the cocaine sold in the District of
Columbia.
   A 12-member U.S. District Court jury found Edmond guilty of all
seven charges against him after more than four days of
deliberations, capping a 12-week trial held amid extremely tight
security. The verdict means Edmond faces a mandatory life prison
sentence. Ten other defendants were convicted of assisting him.
   ``Everyone on the defense team is upset by the verdict,'' said
William Murphy, one of Edmond's attorneys. ``We had the cards
stacked against us from the beginning ... and we are going to
appeal.''
   U.S. District Court Judge Charles Richey has not yet set a
sentencing date for Edmond or his associates.
   Edmond faces additional charges, including three counts of
first-degree murder and conspiracy. Stephens said he plans to try
Edmond on those charges, despite the mandatory life sentence in the
drug distribution case.
   ``Our immediate plan is to proceed,'' Stephens said. ``The
primary goal ... is to bring this organization to a halt.''
   Prosecutors had described Edmond's drug network as a blend of
family members and close friends who conducted their operations
with a sophisticated _ and deadly _ entrepreneurial flare.
   The charges against Edmond included conspiracy to violate drug
laws, employing minors to possess and distribute cocaine, traveling
across state lines to sell drugs and using a telephone to set up
illegal drug deals.
   Convictions on those counts satisfy a definition of a continuing
criminal enterprise, a crime that carries a mandatory life sentence.
   Edmond's 10 co-defendants, including an aunt, a sister, a
brother and several close friends, were found guilty of conspiracy
to deal drugs. That crime carries a penalty of 10 years to life in
prison.
   At its peak last summer, the prosecutors charged, the Edmond
network was pumping up to 440 pounds of cocaine per week into the
streets of Washington.
   ``The message should be clear _ if you deal death and
destruction, you will pay with your life,'' Stephens said. After
noting that Edmond had been perceived by some friends and neighbors
as a hero for his ability to make money, the prosecutor said Edmond
should be seen instead as a ``purveyor of human destruction.''
   The trial featured extremely strict security measures. At the
outset, Richey ruled that jurors' names be kept secret even from
himself and lawyers to protect the jury from reprisals. The home of
one witness' mother was firebombed during the trial and an
informant was shot after his name was accidentally divulged by the
prosecution.
   Defense lawyer James Robertson suggested that the unusual
security provisions _ including a 1{-inch bullet-proof shield
around the courtroom _ made it impossible for the defendants to
receive a fair trial.
   ``No matter what happened in that courtroom, it was going to
make it very difficult to give Mr. Edmond the benefit of the
doubt,'' he said.
</TEXT>
