<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-07 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Stocks Hit Another New High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen in Tokyo
Thursday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange set
another new high.
   The dollar closed at 144.13 yen, up 0.38 yen from Wednesday's
close of 143.75 yen. After opening at 143.95 yen, the U.S. currency
ranged between 143.94 and 144.33 yen.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which rose 160.12 points for a record closing of 37,654.29
Wednesday, added another 203.82 points, or 0.54 percent, to close
at 37,858.11, another new high.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's bullish opening in Tokyo was
largely due to the currency's gains on overseas markets overnight.
   The dollar-buying was triggered by warnings issued by the East
German military that it would not tolerate attempts by citizens to
seize munitions from security installations, according to dealers.
A fleeting fear that the military might take action to block the
country's reform movement led some to sell the West German currency
for dollars, they said.
   The dollar's decline against the mark in New York was
accelerated overnight by comments from U.S. Undersecretary of the
Treasury David Mulford, who said the United States was ``not
alarmed'' about the dollar's recent steep 10 percent decline
against the mark.
   He also noted the dollar has only slipped 2 percent against the
yen.
   The New York market took Mulford's comments to mean that the
U.S. central bank has not been intervening to shore up the sagging
dollar, as many had thought.
   Securities dealers said the Nikkei index rose as market players
were reassured by an Economic Planning Agency announcement of 2.9
percent growth in Japan's real gross national product in the
July-September quarter over the previous quarter.
   The rise in inflation-adjusted GNP was equivalent to an annual
12.2 percent growth, the largest since 1973, according to the
agency.
   ``Trading is becoming more active and broader,'' said a dealer
at Nikko Securities Co., requesting anonymity. ``I expect the
bullish trend to continue for some time.''
</TEXT>
