<FIRST>r a PM-BusCrashTrial     12-07 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Crash Trial,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anguished Father Speaks of Losing His Family in Bus Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Testimony to resume at 11 a.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father whose entire family was among
the 27 people killed in a fiery bus crash cast a stern gaze from
the witness stand at the man accused in the nation's deadliest
alcohol-related traffic accident.
   ``I just wanted to see if the man sitting over there being tried
for the murder of my three girls would have enough compassion to
look my way as I looked his way,'' Army 1st Sgt. Lee Williams said
after testifying Wednesday in Larry Mahoney's murder and
drunken-driving trial.
   ``And I didn't see it.''
   From the witness stand in Carroll Circuit Court, Williams glared
at Mahoney as he told of losing his wife, Marilyn Joy, 34, and
daughters Kristen, 14 and Robin, 10.
   Williams was the last in a series of parents and spouses who
testified about the 24 youths and three adults who died in the May
14, 1988, crash.
   Authorities said the crash occurred when Mahoney drove his
pickup truck in the wrong lanes of Interstate 71 south of this Ohio
River town and plowed into the bus owned by the First Assembly of
God Church in Radcliff.
   In July, Williams married the widow of another crash victim,
Dotty Pearman Williams, who also testified about her loss.
   Her husband, bus driver John Pearman, and a niece were killed.
Her daughter, Christy, survived with severe burns.
   ``Christy returned and was severely injured,'' Mrs. Williams
said. ``John was brought back in a cold, black body bag.''
   In other testimony, two witnesses said Mahoney was drunk the
night of the crash.
   Kerry Cantrell, a laboratory supervisor from Humana
Hospital-University of Louisville, testified a blood sample drawn
from Mahoney after the crash showed a blood alcohol level of 0.24.
   Terry Comstock, a state police chemist, said he tested the same
blood sample drawn four days after the crash. His tests showed
blood alcohol levels of 0.18 and 0.20.
   In Kentucky, a person is considered intoxicated if their blood
alcohol level is at least 0.10.
   Defense attorney Russell Baldani attacked the discrepancy among
the three tests.
   Mahoney, 36, is charged with 27 counts of murder, 42 counts of
wanton endangerment, 12 counts of assault and a count of drunken
driving.
   Testimony of the parents and spouses was brief because a
Kentucky Supreme Court decision limits questioning of homicide
victims' family members to basic biographical information about the
deceased, said Assistant Attorney General Paul Richwalsky Jr.
   But Williams said even a short time on the stand was painful.
   ``When the lawyer says, `When was the last time you saw your
family?' ... for a second or two, I honestly saw Kristen walk down
the hall to the bedroom, and I remember putting my arms around her
and I remember kissing her goodbye and telling her I loved her,''
Williams told reporters later.
   He spoke at length and in heart-breaking detail about his
experiences during the trial.
   ``This is the second Christmas I'm going without my two
daughters,'' Williams said. ``And I miss them every day.''
   Williams viewed Mahoney's three emotional outbursts in court
last month as an expression of guilt but not sorrow.
   ``But for his three times, I have broken down three thousand
times,'' Williams said.
</TEXT>
