<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SovietCarrier     12-07 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Carrier,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy: Soviets Launch Aircraft From New Carrier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union can now launch ground-attack
jets from its first full-scale aircraft carrier, a naval aviation
advance that the U.S. Navy says holds the potential for offensive
use.
   The development came only days before Mikhail S. Gorbachev
pressed President Bush on naval arms control issues at the Malta
summit.
   The U.S. Navy confirmed on Wednesday that the 65,000-ton Tbilisi
aircraft carrier had launched and recovered three fighter jets
during trials in the Black Sea _ the MiG-29 Fulcrum, a SU-27
Flanker and the SU-25 Frogfoot ground attack aircraft.
   The Tbilisi's capabilities are a marked advance over the much
smaller Kiev-class carrier, which is capable of transporting only
helicopters and jump-jets.
   While the Tbilisi's sea trials are not unexpected, Navy
officials pointed to the type of aircraft used on the carrier as
interesting _ as well as the timing of the event.
   ``They are way ahead of schedule,'' said one Navy officer, who
spoke on condition he not be identified by name.
   Use of an aircraft carrier vastly improves Soviet tactical
aviation capabilities, allowing fighter jets to be launched far
beyond the range of Soviet borders.
   The Tbilisi is the first of its class, while two others are
under construction.
   The ship uses a ``ski jump'' bow to launch aircraft and not the
high-powered catapults that hurl jets from U.S. carriers. But the
Soviets do use the arresting wires that stop planes as they land on
the deck, just as the American carriers do.
   The Navy, in a statement pointing to the ship's offensive
capabilities, said:
   ``The Soviets have insisted that the Tbilisi ... (is) intended
for defensive purposes only. ... Nonetheless, the demonstrated
capability of the Tbilisi to accommodate a variant of one of the
Soviet Union's principal ground-attack aircraft, the Frogfoot,
shows a potential for offensive operations.''
   While Pentagon officials said the trials took place in
mid-November, the Navy confirmed them several days after Gorbachev
sought to ban short-range nuclear weapons aboard the superpowers'
ships, according to White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Gorbachev illustrated his concern over the wide-ranging U.S.
Navy, giving Bush a map of U.S. naval bases, deployments and
maneuvers around the Soviet Union.
   In rejecting Gorbachev's argument, said Fitzwater, Bush
maintained that
   ``the Soviet Union is a land-based power. But the navy is
crucial to us in terms of maintaining all of our commitments around
the world, maintaining open sea lanes and commercial lanes around
the world.''
   Another defense official said the definition of the Soviet
warship as an aircraft carrier is of some importance to the region.
   ``The Soviets continue to tell Turkey that this is not an
aircraft carrier,'' he said, adding that the Soviets contend it is
a ``heavy aircraft-carrying cruiser.''
   Under the 1936 Montreux Convention, Turkey could bar the
movement of such a warship through the Dardanelles, which is the
passage between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean, the official
said.
   The convention put the control of the water passage in Turkish
hands, and it allows the nation to close the straits to warships of
other nations in time of war.
   The Soviets have stated that the Tbilisi will join the Northern
Fleet and operate out of the Kola Peninsula, the Navy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
