<DOCNO> AP891207-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Mideast     12-07 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Clears First Hurdle to Mideast Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III still
faces tough problems in getting Mideast peace talks started, even
with the conditional acceptance by the Palestine Liberation
Organization of a first round of negotiations.
   Baker will be able to convene talks in Washington early next
year with the foreign ministers of Egypt and Israel. However, going
beyond that stage will take slick maneuvering by Baker as well as
concessions from all sides.
   The PLO, speaking through Egypt, agreed Wednesday to the
session. The Israeli Cabinet agreed last month.
   But U.S. officials made it clear that the PLO and Israel still
have reservations about what happens next, and Baker will have to
find a way to ease their concerns to keep going.
   Basically, Yasser Arafat's group is clinging to its claim to
represent Palestinians everywhere. It wants to play a role in
selecting the Palestinian delegation that would meet with Israel in
Cairo as the next step in a drawn-out peace process.
   Israel, on the other hand, wants to exclude the PLO even from a
behind-the-scenes role. Baker's five-point program guarantees that
Israel will go to Cairo only ``after a satisfactory list of
Palestinians has been worked out.''
   But another provision of the Baker plan specifies that Egypt
cannot substitute itself for the Palestinians and that it ``will
consult with Palestinians on all aspects of the dialogue.''
   That could mean the PLO will be able to play an influential role
even if it's not at the table.
   Despite the problems, though, Baker achieved a breakthrough of
sorts after three months of dickering with Foreign Ministers Moshe
Arens of Israel and Esmat Abdel Meguid of Egypt.
   They will continue the bargaining at the Washington meeting,
which State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said would be
held in January, at the earliest.
   The U.S. goal is to carry out a proposal by Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir for elections among the 1.4 million
Palestinians who live on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   The elected Palestinians would negotiate with Israel an
arrangement for limited self-rule. After the five-year experiment,
Israel, Jordan, Egypt and Palestinians would hold talks on an
overall settlement.
   The PLO has repeatedly denounced the Israeli scenario as a
scheme to undercut Palestinian aspirations for statehood.
   Baker telephoned Arens with the news of the PLO's conditional
acceptance. Arens told him the Israeli government would study the
response, said Ruth Yaron, spokeswoman for the Israeli Embassy.
   A senior U.S. official, declining to be identified, said that
now that Baker has qualified acceptance from the PLO and Israel
``he can get down to work on dealing with their views.''
   Baker three months ago began an arduous diplomatic effort to
bridge the gap between the PLO and Israel. His plan includes the
Washington meeting with Arens and Meguid.
   Another provision of his five-point program, released by Ms.
Tutwiler, is that ``the United States understands that Israel will
attend the dialogue only after a satisfactory list of Palestinians
has been worked out.''
   A third provision guarantees that Egypt will consult with
Palestinians ``on all aspects of the dialogue.''
   A fourth assures the Palestinians that those who meet with
Israel ``would be free to raise issues that relate to their
opinions on how to make elections and the negotiating process
succeed.''
   This could be a vehicle for Palestinians to assert statehood
aspirations and also to register demands extending beyond the
limited self-rule Shamir envisions for five years on the West Bank
and in Gaza.
   For the past two years, Palestinians in the territories have
clashed with Israeli authorities. At least 626 have died in the
process, while 155 other Palestinians were killed by Arabs on
suspicion of cooperating with Israel. Also, 43 Israeli soldiers and
civilians died in the rebellion.
   The Baker formula makes no direct reference to the PLO, with
which the United States opened talks a year ago after Arafat
publicly renounced terrorism and said he accepted the existence of
Israel.
   Robert Pelletreau Jr., the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, has been
meeting with PLO officials while Baker conducted negotiations
through Meguid.
   Ms. Tutwiler called the Egyptian reply a ``step forward'' for
the peace process. Last week, in Baker's behalf, she had ruled out
any U.S. action on the PLO's reservations until it first accepted
his formula.
   ``We have now received from the government of Egypt a positive
response to Secretary Baker's five-point framework,'' Ms. Tutwiler
said.
   ``We will be working with the parties on steps needed to get to
a trilateral meeting in Washington as part of a process for
launching an Israeli-Palestinian dialogue.''
</TEXT>
