<FIRST>r w PM-Quayle     12-07 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Foreigners Like Gorbachev Better Than Soviets Do</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle says the United
States should not get too hung up on Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's charming manner, while pointing out that foreigners
like him more than his own countrymen do.
   ``The personality can help bring about these reforms and we
should encourage that,'' Quayle said in a televised interview
Wednesday on the Cable News Network's ``Larry King Live'' show.
   ``The president wants to encourage that and he wants to offer
help to Chairman Gorbachev to have these reforms,'' the vice
president said. ``But instead of getting caught up in the magnetic
personality of Chairman Gorbachev, we've got to look beyond that
and see if there are true lasting reforms taking place.''
   Following President Bush's meetings at Malta with Gorbachev last
week, Quayle expressed skepticism about Soviet foreign policy,
saying in a published interview Monday that the Kremlin still wants
to ``create instability'' in other nations.
   While that view seemed to contrast with the friendly nature of
the talks between Bush and Gorbachev, White House officials moved
quickly to say there was no disagreement between the president and
the vice president.
   Before the vice president's televised remarks Wednesday, Soviet
spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said Quayle's views on Soviet
foreign policy ``sounded strange.''
   Quayle has consistently taken a tougher view of the Soviet Union
than other administration officials, and while he spoke well of
Gorbachev during Wednesday's interview, he said relations should
not be based on one man.
   ``We want him to succeed in perestroika, we want him to succeed
in glasnost,'' Quayle said.
   ``But sometime, Gorbachev will not, sometime down the road, will
not be the leader of the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   ``His popularity is probably greater outside the Soviet Union
than in the Soviet Union,'' Quayle said.
   Recent polls in the United States, West Germany and the Soviet
Union support Quayle's observations on Gorbachev's popularity, the
first time a high U.S. official has said such things.
   A survey for the West German magazine Der Spiegel last summer
found 82 percent of 2,000 voters polled were convinced that
Gorbachev's reform policies in the Soviet Union will succeed. A
parallel survey of 1,000 Moscow citizens conducted for the magazine
by the Soviet Academy of Sciences found that 59 percent thought
perestroika will succeed.
   In sheer popularity, Der Spiegel found that Gorbachev rated
higher than West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. In the United
States, a Media General-Associated Press poll last month found that
Bush and Gorbachev have roughly equal popularity in this country.
</TEXT>
