<DOCNO> AP891207-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ArmsControl     12-07 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Control,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former U.S. Negotiator Urges Deep Cuts In Strategic Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should press for additional
cuts in strategic nuclear weapons once it finishes negotiating a
pact to reduce those weapons by as much as half, a former U.S. arms
negotiator says.
   ``Certainly we can afford to be more ambitious in our arms
control proposals,'' former arms negotiator Paul Warnke said
Wednesday in a speech to the Arms Control Association, a private
research group.
   Under the START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) agreement now
being negotiated, U.S. and Soviet long-range bombers, missiles and
submarines would be cut by 30 percent to 50 percent.
   Warnke said that agreement could be completed and signed at the
summit President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
plan to hold in Washington next June, a meeting the two leaders
agreed to at the Malta Summit last week.
   ``There is no reason at all we can't go ahead with a START 2
treaty,'' Warnke said.
   Such a second treaty should aim at banning missiles with
multiple warheads, Warnke said.
   Warnke argued that Soviet troop withdrawals from Eastern Europe
and the political changes sweeping the Warsaw Pact countries mean
fewer nuclear weapons are needed to defend the West.
   He said the major obstacle in the strategic arms reduction talks
in Geneva was the U.S. program to devise a space shield against
ballistic missile attack.
   ``But that idea left town with Mr. Reagan,'' Warnke said of the
U.S. Strategic Defense Initiative championed by the former
president but viewed with skepticism by many in Congress and most
arms control experts.
   A ban on missiles with multiple warheads would eliminate the
threat of a nuclear first strike by either side, Warnke suggested.
   Such an attack would require so many single-warhead missiles the
aggressor would be unable to defend against nuclear retaliation _
and therefore would not launch an attack, he argued.
   But Warnke, who was former President Carter's chief negotiator,
stressed the two sides should complete the current START treaty
first before making deeper cuts in their strategic weapons.
   Congress has approved a Bush administration plan to extend the
U.S. arsenal of land-based missiles armed with multiple warheads
that could reach all targets within the Soviet Union by putting
some on rail cars that could move around in a crisis, making them
harder for the Soviets to destroy.
   Warnke said that ``probably was a lousy idea'' and would
escalate nuclear tensions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
