<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Price     12-07 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Price,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Bear Man of Pack Creek' Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stan Price, who became a symbol of
peaceful coexistence between humans and brown bears, has died of
cancer. He was 90.
   Price, known as the ``bear man of Pack Creek,'' died Tuesday at
the home of his great-nephew, Gary Lingle of Juneau, where he had
been living since October.
   He lived for 40 years along the shores of Pack Creek on
Admiralty Island, which attracts thousands of visitors to see the
world's largest concentration of brown bears.
   But Price himself also was an attraction _ a small, white-haired
man who casually strolled among the fearsome-looking bruins, which
can weigh more than 1,000 pounds, with nothing more than a walking
stick for protection.
   A native of Missouri, Price arrived in southeast Alaska in 1927
in a sailboat he had built in Seattle. In 1928, he set up a mining
and logging operation at Windham Bay not far from Pack Creek, 30
miles south of Juneau. He also worked as a mechanic, fisherman and
fox farmer.
   In the 20 years that he regularly visited his great-uncle,
Lingle said he always felt safe walking with Price because of the
special relationship he had with the bears.
   ``He always said if you're friends with the bears, the bears
will be friends with you,'' Lingle said. ``He had a mutual respect
with the bears and the proof is that he lived there for 40 years
with only one incident.''
   That occurred on a narrow path between Price's woodshed and his
house on a beach. Price and a brown bear surprised each other and a
face off began with neither backing down. The big brownie finally
swatted Price, breaking his collarbone.
   Despite living in close quarters with about 25 brown bears that
roam the Pack Creek area, Price never carried a rifle. A quick bop
on the nose with his walking stick was usually sufficient if a bear
got testy.
   As word of Price's special relationship with the bears spread,
films, television shows and magazines told his story. During the
1980s, the number of visitors to Pack Creek increased dramatically.
   ``He had a gentleness and a special way of communicating with
the bears,'' said Joel Bennett, a Juneau wildlife filmmaker and
Alaska Board of Game member. ``He didn't subscribe to the theory
that they were marauding killers lurking behind every tree.''
   Bennett said Price would walk to within 6 feet of the animals
and talk to them.
   ``This is the passing of a grand old man that represents a
unique part of the heritage of Alaska,'' Bennett said. ``His legacy
is that people can coexist with wildlife peacefully if we try. He
taught that by example.''
   Survivors include Price's second wife, Esther, who lives in
Arkansas and has Alzheimer's disease, Lingle said. His first wife
died of cancer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
