<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-PeoplePower     12-07 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-People Power,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Citizens Now Guarding Secret Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSTOCK, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hanko Dewitz raced up on his
bicycle for his four-hour watch at secret police headquarters. His
mission: prevent Communist officials from destroying evidence in a
widening weapons scandal.
   The excited young supporter of the opposition New Forum group
had to wait until classes were out Wednesday before he pedaled
through this Baltic port to take up watch.
   Across East Germany, there are similar strange scenes. Angry
citizens have this week surrounded and, in some cases, stormed
local headquarters of the once-dreaded secret police.
   ``We check all material coming in and going out of this
building. We are here to make sure the police don't burn the
papers. We control this building,'' said Dewitz, a 24-year-old
medical student.
   Supporters of New Forum, the largest opposition group in East
Germany, occupied the building Monday upon hearing reports that
Communist officials were involved in illegal weapons export from a
nearby factory.
   There were also reports of the burning of documents.
   The focus of anger is the IMES factory at Kavelstorf, a village
on a rolling plain about 10 miles south of Rostock. New Forum says
it discovered cases of weapons among piles of household goods that
the plant normally produces.
   The plant is now occupied by police, and a representative of New
Forum is present at all times.
   A hand-lettered sign on the fence says ``New Forum Kavelstorf,''
and an East German flag with a white dove stitched on calls for
demilitarization.
   The group charges that the weapons were exported for hard
currency. The head of the firm has been arrested and Alexander
Schalck-Golodkowski, the government official who oversaw the
operation, has turned himself to authorities in West Germany, where
he had fled.
   A secretary in the mayor's office of Kavelstorf had this comment
on the affair: ``Disgusting!''
   Said a local mechanic: ``Everybody from the top party boss to
the little local party leader was corrupt.''
   The case has been turned over to the state prosecutor's office,
which has put five lawyers on it. The people are being represented
by New Forum.
   The scandal is the talk of the town, and by afternoon the local
OstZee Zeitung newspaper is now sold out. Once a Communist party
mouthpiece, the daily now prints full reports of opposition
activities and even lists planned demonstrations.
   Throughout East Germany, the opposition has set itself a tall
order to make sure that 40 years of incriminating documents do not
vanish.
   In addition to its 24-hour guard inside the secret police
building, New Forum has taken over a garage that serviced cars
belonging to the police.
   The activists are allowing no information to be radioed out, and
they say they have halted the burning of documents likely to
incriminate secret police.
</TEXT>
