<FIRST>r a PM-Boeing-Honeywell     12-07 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing-Honeywell,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness: Defense Contractor Employees Swapped Classified Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The swapping of classified Pentagon
budget documents by employees of nine major defense contractors was
``endemic,'' according to a witness at the federal trial of a
former Boeing Co. employee.
   The informal network of document trading existed in the late
1970s and early 1980s, government witnesses said Wednesday. It was
the third day of the trial of Richard Lee Fowler, a former Boeing
worker accused of illegally obtaining secret Defense Department
documents.
   Fowler has pleaded innocent to 39 counts, including conspiracy,
illegal conveyance of classified documents and mail fraud. Boeing
earlier pleaded guilty to receiving classified documents and will
pay a $5.2 million fine.
   Among the companies implicated in the document trading network
besides Boeing were Honeywell, Bendix, IBM, RCA, Grumman, Raytheon,
Rockwell and Martin Marietta.
   ``I would describe it as endemic,'' Linda Coutre, a Bendix
employee from 1972 to 1984, said of the document swaps.
   Ms. Coutre said everyone seemed to have the so-called
``planning, programming and budget system'' documents and she
exchanged documents with Fowler and employees of other defense
companies.
   The documents were never entered in Bendix's classified document
log, Ms. Coutre said, adding that she kept the documents in a file
cabinet or a safe and when they became outdated she would shred
them or burn them in her fireplace.
   Ms. Coutre said she never asked Fowler or others where they got
the documents.
   ``It was an unspoken agreement that no one asked that
question,'' she said. ``We didn't want to get people in trouble.''
   Ms. Coutre, who was granted immunity from prosecution by U.S.
attorneys, said the documents gave defense contractors some
indication of how serious the Pentagon was about pursuing various
projects.
   ``They were used primarily to support business decisions,'' she
said. ``We had to look at the opportunities from the Department of
Defense and make decisions on whether to invest money. We wanted to
make sure the government was serious about the opportunities before
we went forward.''
   Philip Jackson, an RCA employee from 1979 to 1984, said he also
swapped documents, but the top source of supply was Fowler.
   Jackson said Fowler's supply of documents ``seemed to be
continuous and quick'' and on at least two occasions Fowler handed
him documents from the trunk of his car parked in the garage at
Boeing's Rosslyn, Va., office.
   ``It was my sense that every major contractor had them,''
Jackson said.
   Jackson, who was also granted immunity from prosecution, said he
``never asked anyone what their source was. It was just not done.
It was not the gentlemanly way to do things.''
   But Jackson said he had the ``distinct impression'' that Fowler
got the documents from the Pentagon and he thought Fowler was
encouraging others in the network to develop Pentagon sources.
   Max Franklin, who worked both for Martin Marietta and IBM, said
that he too swapped documents with Fowler and others.
   Franklin, who was called as a defense witness, said he didn't
feel that exchanging the classified documents was illegal and that
defense contractors had a legitimate right to know what was in the
documents.
   Franklin said Fowler was described by others as the ``best in
the business'' in terms of getting the documents, but denied that
he had heard Fowler described as the ``mother lode.''
   In earlier testimony Wednesday, a retired Honeywell employee
said he and other company employees were under pressure to get the
secret budget documents.
   Frank Lozito said when he was asked by his supervisor to get
classified Air Force budget documents he turned to Fowler, an old
friend, for help.
   Lozito, who also was granted immunity, said he got documents
from Fowler five or 10 times a year, from 1979 to early 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
