<FIRST>r a PM-GreenhouseDebate     12-07 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greenhouse Debate,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debate Rages on Prospects for Global Warming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite popular opinion that global warming
will disrupt Earth's climate, scientists are still debating whether
the ``greenhouse effect'' has started and how bad it will get.
   ``The scientific community is by no means unanimous,''
Massachusetts Institute of Technology meteorologist Dick Lindzen
said Wednesday.
   Because of uncertainty that automobile and industrial pollutants
are heating up Earth's climate, ``I would be loathe to tell Detroit
they can't build big cars any more or tell Exxon to cut oil
production,'' said climate researcher Tim Barnett, of the Scripps
Institution of Oceanography in La Jolla.
   Debate over global warming took place at the American
Geophysical Union's fall meeting.
   The ``greenhouse effect'' theory says that carbon dioxide and
other gases emitted by burning industrial and automobile fuel is
accumulating in Earth's atmosphere, acting like greenhouse glass to
trap heat from sunlight.
   Computer simulations suggest that by the middle of the next
century, Earth's average temperature may rise 4 to 9 degrees
Fahrenheit, possibly altering storm patterns, triggering droughts
and crop failures and raising sea levels to flood low-lying coastal
areas.
   If humans keep burning fossil fuels at present rates, adding
more carbon dioxide to the atmosphere, ``by the year 2050 we're
going to have tremendous climate changes far outside what man has
ever experienced,'' said James Hansen, director of NASA's Goddard
Institute for Space Studies.
   Lindzen countered: ``It's equally easy to support scenarios
where nothing happens.''
   He argued that a warming of Earth's surface spurs creation of
more cumulus clouds and makes them rise higher, which in turn
blocks enough sunlight to counteract greenhouse heating.
   Barnett said the greenhouse effect's ``potential consequences
are scary as hell.'' But he and others question whether computer
forecasts of climatological doom are valid.
   That's because so far they have been unable to find evidence to
link greenhouse gases to the one-half-degree warming observed
during the past century.
   Analysis of warming since 1881 shows that most of that increase
in global temperature happened before 1919 _ before the more
recent, sharp rise in the amount of carbon dioxide in the
atmosphere, said Thomas Karl, of the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration's National Climatic Data Center in
Asheville, N.C.
   While global climate warmed overall since 1881, it actually
cooled during the period from 1921 to 1979 before warming again,
Karl said.
   ``In spite of all the well-publicized concern about global
warming, you must understand that there is still considerable
uncertainty among scientific experts about a number of critical
factors which determine global warming,'' NOAA administrator John
Knauss said in a statement.
   The researchers agreed they need to stop arguing and do better
research to learn if the greenhouse effect is under way and will be
as severe as Hansen and others believe.
   Hansen spurred controversy when he told a U.S. Senate committee
hearing during the hot, dry summer of 1988 that he was almost
certain greenhouse warming already had begun.
   Other scientists at Wednesday's news conference said that if
that's true, they can't detect such warming since it is so small
compared to temperature variations caused by changes in solar heat
output and other natural factors.
   Hansen said that to reduce the prospects for radical climate
change, there many things that can be done without great cost.
   Such steps include phasing out chlorofluorocarbon gases _ which
harm Earth's protective ozone shield and warm the atmosphere _
improving energy efficiency to reduce fuel burning, and recycling
newspapers to save trees that consume carbon dioxide, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NorthwestQuakes     12-07 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest Quakes,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Northwest Due for Giant Quake, Studies Suggest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growing evidence shows a monstrous
earthquake could wallop the woefully unprepared Pacific Northwest,
followed by tidal waves that would swamp coastal areas of Oregon
and Washington, scientists say.
   ``The chances are very high that a great earthquake will occur,
yet seismic building codes are notoriously out of date,'' said
University of Oregon geophysicist Paul Vincent.
   Craig Weaver, a U.S. Geological Survey geophysicist in Seattle,
called the region's ability to prevent death and damage from
earthquakes ``abysmal.''
   ``We're not prepared in the Pacific Northwest,'' he said.
   While some scientists remain skeptical, evidence accumulated
during the last five years indicates six quakes with magnitudes of
8 to 9 rocked the region during the past 3,500 years, making
coastal areas suddenly drop so that tsunamis, or seismic tidal
waves, inundated the shoreline. The last such quake was about 300
years ago.
   More studies showing such quakes have occurred and are likely to
strike again were released Wednesday during the American
Geophysical Union's fall meeting.
   Residents of the Northwest ``should be ready for an earthquake
at any time,'' although no one knows how soon, Weaver said.
   One study found the Oregon coast near Tillamook has been rising
and tilting eastward much more quickly during the past 50 years
than it has on average in 80,000 to 100,000 years.
   That indicates that stress is building underground, and will be
released in a quake measuring 8 to 9 on the Richter scale any time
within the next 150 years, according to scientists from the
University of California, Berkeley.
   The study was conducted by Vincent and Ray Weldon at the
University of Oregon, and Mark Richards at Berkeley.
   Dozens of dead western cedar trees along Washington's southern
coast were studied by David Yamaguchi, a forester at the University
of Colorado at Boulder. Yamaguchi said that by dating the trees'
rings, he determined they all died suddenly about 300 years ago,
when coastal land suddenly dropped during a major quake and
tsunamis submerged the trees.
   Yamaguchi said the trees were found along a 60-mile coastal
stretch, suggesting the quake measured 8 on the Richter scale.
   Mary Reinhart of the University of Washington presented a study
showing 300-year-old peat buried by sand has been found along at
least a 120-mile stretch of the Oregon-Washington coast. She said
it indicates a 40-foot-high tsunami dumped sand on coastal
estuaries in a big quake three centuries ago.
   Richards said Oregon is severely unprepared for the ``great
seismic hazard.'' The lack of recent big quakes lulled Oregonians
into a false sense of security, and the state has made little
progress updating building codes to take large quakes into account,
he added.
   Weaver said Washington state is slightly better prepared because
building standards were improved after a magnitude-7.1 quake in
Olympia in 1949 and a magnitude-6.5 quake near Seattle in 1965. The
two quakes killed 17 people.
   Geological Survey geologist Bob Buckham found new evidence that
one and possibly two quakes measuring about 7 rocked Seattle at
least 1,200 years ago.
   He found that land on Bainbridge Island west of Seattle was
suddenly uplifted by as much as 23 feet at the time. A
magnitude-7.3 quake in Algeria several years ago raised land there
by about 16 feet.
   Two large plates of Earth's crust collide off the Pacific
Northwest. The Juan de Fuca plate, which is under the seafloor, is
diving eastward under the North American plate beneath Oregon and
Washington in a process is called subduction.
   Quakes can happen in subduction zones when one plate sticks to
the other until so much stress builds up they snap apart in a giant
temblor.
   That caused the 1985 Mexico earthquakes, which killed about
10,000 people, and the two largest quakes ever recorded: the 1960
Chile quake that killed about 5,000 people and measured 9.5, and
the 1964 Alaska quake that claimed 131 lives and measured 9.2.
   Lynn Sykes, of Columbia University's Lamont Doherty Geological
Observatory, said other scientists ``have too quickly jumped on the
big earthquake scenario'' for the Northwest.
   He believes the Juan de Fuca plate is warmer and softer than the
plates off Alaska, Mexico and Chile. In that case, the plate could
dive smoothly under North America without sticking and snapping.
   But Richards said if that were true, the Northwest would have
``the only major subduction zone which does not cause substantial
earthquakes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0043 </DOCNO>
