<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     12-07 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Members Want Some Health Benefits Revived</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two House members are trying to save some of
the Medicare catastrophic health insurance benefits that Congress
recently voted to repeal.
   Reps. Fortney ``Pete'' Stark, D-Calif., and Willis Gradison,
R-Ohio, on Wednesday asked fellow lawmakers to back legislation
that would provide limited Medicare coverage of mammography
screening, expanded home health services, respite care and hospice
care.
   The four benefits were lesser provisions included in the
year-old Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act, which Congress last
month voted to repeal in response to senior citizens' complaints
that the program was too expensive.
   President Bush is expected to sign the repeal legislation.
   The catastrophic package was designed to protect 33 million
elderly and disabled people against financial ruin from prolonged
illnesses.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Move to Hold Hearing on Texas Bus Crash Rejected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board will
complete its investigation of Texas' worst school bus accident
without a public hearing that had been sought by the lead on-site
investigator.
   NTSB member Lee V. Dickinson said a hearing would call attention
to several national safety issues involved in the September
accident near Alton that killed 21 teen-agers, but the move failed
on a 2-2 vote.
   Dickinson said a hearing would spotlight such issues as
continued problems with deficient brakes in the trucking industry,
whether school buses have adequate escape hatches and whether
students are sufficiently drilled on emergency escape routes.
   Nineteen students aboard the bus drowned when it collided with a
soft-drink delivery truck, careened into a water-filled pit and
quickly submerged. Two others died later.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Contaminated Eye Wash Recalled by Florida Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nonprescription eye wash is being recalled
by a Florida company because of a bacterial contamination that
could cause serious infection, according to the Food and Drug
Administration.
   The FDA said Wednesday the product, made by the Dansol Division
of Ocumed Inc. in Sarasota, Fla., is Valumed brand irrigating eye
wash sterile solution in four-ounce plastic bottles carrying lot
number N4209.
   The lot number is stamped in ink on the bottom of the bottle.
The eye wash is labeled as being manufactured for Moore Medical
Corp. of New Britain, Conn.
   About 1,400 bottles were distributed, the FDA said.
   The contaminated solutions could cause infection in a scratched
or damaged eye. But the FDA said no injuries have been reported.
</TEXT>
