<FIRST>r p PM-LelandSeat     12-07 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leland Seat,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Allies Now Foes in Election for Leland's Congressional Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former allies on Mickey Leland's ``People's
Five'' slate of young, black legislative candidates have become
political foes in the race to succeed the congressman who died in a
plane crash.
   State Sen. Craig Washington and City Councilman Anthony Hall
face eachother in Saturday's non-partisan runoff election for
Leland's 18th Congressional District seat. Leland was killed Aug. 7
during a famine relief mission to Ethiopia.
   In the early 1970s, all three men worked for civil rights, fair
housing, health care for the poor, food for the hungry and other
social concerns. They were the only successful candidates from the
Democratic ``People's Five'' slate, who sought to represent Houston
in the state House.
   Now Washington and Hall have spent weeks trying to establish
their political differences and prove their interest in
representing a district said to be among the nation's poorest.
   ``My campaign is a movement,'' said Washington. ``It's an
opportunity for people to get involved in politics again.''
   An attorney and a former law school instructor, Washington, 48,
has been state senator since 1983 after serving 10 years in the
House.
   He captured 41 percent of the vote in the Nov. 7 election,
compared with 34 percent for Hall. The two topped a field of 11
candidates seeking to succeed Leland.
   The term expires in 1990.
   ``I won in the black community and the white community and the
Hispanic community,'' Washington said. ``And I intend to do exactly
the same thing on Dec. 9.''
   A poll published Monday by KPRC-TV showed the race is nearly
deadlocked. The KPRC poll said 41 percent of voters favor Hall,
while 38 percent were for Washington. Twenty-one percent said they
were undecided, and the poll had a 5 point margin of error.
   Hall, 45, has a more buttoned-down style. Also an attorney, he
gained early notice as a decorated Vietnam veteran who returned to
Houston questioning discriminatory practices in housing and
employment. More recently, he has worked to set up 50 ``Just Say
No'' anti-drug programs for 1,300 students.
   ``I have a vision that indeed we can do better than we do now at
solving the problems that we face as a community,'' said Hall, a
three-term legislator who has served as councilman since 1979.
   Hall, who had been a high school friend of Leland's, lost a
bitter battle to him for the congressional seat in 1978, when the
two fought to succeed Barbara Jordan.
   Hall had to give up his re-election bid for the council to run
for Congress. Mayor Kathy Whitmire has endorsed his bid for
Congress and helped him raise money.
   Washington and Hall agree many issues: both favor increased
funding to battle drug trafficking and abuse, and for health care
to the poor and elderly and military cutbacks in Central America.
   ``What differences there are largely is a matter of style,''
says Franklin Jones, a political scientist at Texas Southern
University. ``Washington comes off as the more grassroots kinds of
campaigner _ more of the people's candidate. While Hall has the
more polished image, as the sort of professional candidate. But
both of them are extremely professional and long-term political
people.''
</TEXT>
