<HEAD>Snow, Cold And Wind Predicted In Midwest, Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow, wind and continued frigid temperatures were expected in
the Midwest and Northeast today as arctic high pressure from Canada
works its way southeast, and low pressure over the Plains states
moves southeast along the Rockies.
   The colder air was predicted to circulate into eastern New York
and Vermont this morning, powered by winds of up to 25 mph and
accompanied by flurries.
   Tonight's lows may dip to 10 below zero in northeast New York
state.
   A snow advisory has been posted over northern upper Michigan
along the shore of Lake Superior.
   Highs in the teens and 20s were predicted today and Friday in
the Plains states. Parts of South Dakota and western Nebraska
expected several inches of snow today. Some light snow may develop
in western parts of Minnesota and Iowa.
   A snow advisory was in effect late Wednesday over the Sangre de
Cristo mountains and the northern mountains of Colorado. Snow
continued to fall across southeast Colorado. At 2 p.m. Wednesday
there was 5 inches of new snow at West Cliff, Colo.
   Snow was scattered overnight through northern Maine, northwest
New York state and Pennsylvania, northern Indiana, Michigan,
northwest Wisconsin, and parts of the Dakotas, Colorado, Wyoming
and Montana.
   Rain extended over southeast Colorado, Ohio, northeast Kentucky,
northern West Virginia, much of the rest of Pennsylvania and New
York state and southern New England.
   Rain and thunderstorms reached from the upper Texas Gulf Coast
across southern Louisiana and Mississippi and southwest through
central Alabama.
   Wednesday's record high temperatures included 69 degrees in
Huntsville, Ala.; 71 in Mountain View, Calif.; and 70 in
Sacramento, Cal.
   The nation's high temperature Wednesday was 87 degrees at
Borrego Springs, Cal.
