<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearSecurity 1stLd-Writethru a0449 12-07 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Security, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indications of Widespread Security Lapses at Nuclear Arms Plants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf, `Security questions ...,' to INSERT first
reference to Dingell; picks up final graf, `Also, a ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional investigators are turning up
evidence of possibly widespread security problems at the Energy
Department's nuclear weapons plants, which already are under the
gun for extensive safety and environmental flaws.
   Little has been documented of security lapses, mainly because
details about protection of plutonium and other nuclear materials
are classified. As a result of congressional inquiries, however,
once-secret information is trickling out.
   Some members of Congress and private experts say the emerging
evidence points to an unnerving vulnerability to diversion of
bomb-grade plutonium to terrorists.
   ``The questions of diversion and the pathways of diversion are
extremely numerous,'' said Milton Hoenig, scientific director of
the Nuclear Control Institute, a private group that advocates
measures to control the spread of nuclear weapons.
   Despite the government's devotion to secrecy in matters of
nuclear weapon production, it appears some federal nuclear
facilities have run the risk in recent years of allowing the theft
of enough plutonium to build a nuclear bomb.
   Government documents also suggest that some Energy Department
officials have played down protection problems. Other officials
complain that budget constraints have prevented the department from
filling security posts with adequately trained people.
   Among security slips disclosed this week by a House
investigations subcommittee:
   _Argonne National Laboratory-West, near Idaho Falls, Idaho,
violated rules last year on controlling access to portable
plutonium at a nuclear reactor site at the lab.
   Details of the incident are classified, but a senior Energy
Department official told a closed hearing of the House Energy
investigations subcommittee that the violation ``revealed a
deficiency and vulnerability'' to diversion of bomb materials to
terrorists.
   Portions of the hearing transcript were declassified earlier
this week.
   The official, Hilary J. Rauch, manager of the regional Energy
Department office that manages the Idaho facility, did not dispute
a suggestion by Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., that the incident
meant ``people could be carting plutonium out of the place.'' Rauch
stressed that the problem has since been corrected.
   _Quantities of plutonium large enough to make a nuclear bomb
were left unattended in rooms without alarms at Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory in California last spring.
   A previously secret inspection report on Livermore also said
large quantities of plutonium ``were often left, between process
steps, with only one person or unattended'' during normal business
hours. Department officials acknowledged to the House subcommittee
that this was a serious lapse of security.
   _A senior department official, Brig. Gen. Paul F. Kavanaugh,
expressed concern in an internal memorandum last April at the
frequency of ``marginal and unsatisfactory ratings'' of nuclear
material security by federal inspectors of weapons plants.
   ``If, within the DOE, we cannot articulate and enforce effective
security practices at our most sensitive facilities, we will
deserve the comments of our most vocal critics,'' wrote Kavanaugh,
who left the department shortly after sending his memo.
   Kavanaugh also drafted a tough-worded message that he suggested
be sent to managers of key weapons plants requiring immediate
action to improve nuclear materials security. A few weeks later, a
brief version of his proposed message was sent offering thanks for
previous efforts but making scant mention of the problems.
   The subcommittee is investigating why the draft Kavanaugh
message was watered down by his superiors.
   Security questions also have arisen at the Oak Ridge weapons
complex in Tennessee. Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., expressed alarm
that responsibility for granting security clearances was taken away
from Oak Ridge's security officials and given to the personnel
office.
   Also, a laboratory at Oak Ridge was unsure for more than a year,
starting in August 1988, whether a substantial amount of tritium _
a gas used to make nuclear warheads _ had been stolen from a
loading facility. The department said last week that it was
confident that none had been lost, but some members of Congress say
doubts remain about Oak Ridge's ability to protect tritium supplies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
