<DOCNO> AP891207-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     12-07 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Cuts Mandatory Military Service Period In Half</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DAVID CRARY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President F.W. de Klerk
announced a major defense cutback today, including a reduction from
two years to one year of the mandatory period of initial military
service for white men.
   He said certain military units would be eliminated and
facilities closed, with details to be disclosed next year.
   The announcement came two weeks after South Africa completed the
withdrawal of its troops from Namibia, where since 1966 they had
fought a bush war against pro-independence guerrillas.
   A year ago, South Africa signed a treaty that cleared the way
for Namibia's independence and also halted South African
involvement in the civil war in Angola, Namibia's northern neighbor.
   These diplomatic developments have prompted speculation that a
major cut in military spending is imminent.
   De Klerk, opening a new headquarters for the state arms
manufacturing corporation, indicated that conscripts already in the
military would have their terms of service shortened.
   He said details about this would be disclosed Friday.
   The president said it was possible that career military
personnel and employees of Armscor, the weapons company, might lose
their jobs as part of the cutback. He said efforts would be made to
find new jobs for these people.
   It was the second time in 10 days that the president had
announced steps which reduce the scope of military operations and
influence. On Nov. 28, he scrapped a nationwide security network
which critics had denounced as an unaccountable shadow government.
   De Klerk's predecessor, P.W. Botha, had been criticized for
giving the security forces too large a role in policy-making. Botha
quit in August after losing a power struggle with de Klerk.
   Under the current conscription system, all able-bodied white
males in South African are required to serve two years of initial
military duty and then are eligible for call-up camps that could
amount to two more years of service spread out over 20 or more
years. Military service for blacks, Asians and people of mixed-race
is voluntary.
   In September, 780 white men vowed not to perform military
service, the largest defiance ever of conscription laws.
   Draft resisters face prison terms of up to six years, or 1{
times the amount of unfulfilled service. Three men currently are
serving six-year terms _ the youngest, 19-year-old Charles Bester,
completed a full year of his sentence on Tuesday.
   The government does not release information on the manpower of
the armed forces. However, at any given time in recent years, there
have been as estimated 68,000 conscripts on active duty and about
325,000 men in the reserves out of the roughly 2.4 million white
males of all ages in South Africa.
</TEXT>
