<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos-Slayings     12-07 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos-Slayings,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Testimony: At Least Four Intelligence Agencies Operated In
U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
said in videotaped testimony that his government collected
information on dissident activities in America.
   Marcos, who died in Hawaii Sept. 28, said in a video deposition
he became fearful of anti-Marcos protests in the United States by
1984, when ``massive, black propaganda'' was mounted against his
regime.
   Asked whether four Philippine agencies, including the military
and the Presidential Security Command, would have been involved in
collecting intelligence in the United States, Marcos replied:
``Among other things, most probably, yes.''
   Shown in U.S. District Court on Wednesday, the videotape was
made in Hawaii in July 1986, five months after Marcos was
overthrown in a popular revolt.
   The late Marcos, his widow, Imelda, and others are being sued
for $30 million by the families of Silme Domingo and Gene Viernes,
union reformers and anti-Marcos activists who were fatally shot in
June 1981 in the Seattle offices of the Alaska Cannery Workers
Union.
   The suit claims Marcos' government ordered the killings based on
an intelligence network in the United States that monitored
anti-Marcos activists, including Domingo and Viernes.
   Local prosecutors contended the killings involved an internal
union dispute. Three men were convicted of the murders in a 1981
criminal trial.
   Philippine intelligence in the United States would have been the
same as any other country's, Marcos said in the video.
   ``Every embassy, including the American embassy ... have reports
of this nature of those who are against the government in either a
benign way or a vicious way,'' he said. ``I never heard of any
serious effort of infiltrating any anti-Marcos organizations in the
United States.''
   Shortly before their deaths, Viernes had carried money to the
Philippines and met with anti-Marcos labor union officials there,
and he and Domingo supported a resolution at a labor convention in
Hawaii calling for an investigation of labor conditions in the
Philippines.
   But Marcos said he wasn't very concerned about opponents in the
United States until years after the killings.
   ``This fear probably reached ... what you would call an
attention level about '84, not before that, because of the massive,
black propaganda directed at me personally,'' Marcos said.
   He said he doubted a U.S. Senate committee report of the late
1970s that said Philippine agents had operated in the United States
since 1973, keeping track of Marcos opponents.
   ``That's a surprise to me,'' Marcos said.
   Among the documents taken out of the Philippines after Marcos'
overthrow was one that plaintiffs claim shows a ``slush fund''
account in San Francisco that was used to funnel money to the
United States for intelligence work.
   Plaintiffs claim one $15,000 entry on that account was used to
pay for the murders of Domingo and Viernes.
   Marcos was not asked about that document in the video shown
Wednesday. But he said the Philippines intelligence apparatus
contained ``funds that are considered held at the discretion of
some of the officers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
