<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-India     12-07 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singh Makes Tries to Ease Sikh Tensions With Punjab Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Prime Minister V.P. Singh visited
Sikhism's holiest shrine today and told an estimated 20,000 Sikhs
to help him stop the sectarian violence that has cost thousands of
lives.
   ``Too much bloodshed has taken place in Punjab,'' Singh told the
Sikhs gathered inside the sacred Golden Temple.
   Singh's visit to Punjab was the first by a prime minister since
Indira Gandhi traveled to Amritsar in June 1984, when she ordered a
bloody crackdown on Sikh extremists.
   Four months later, she was assassinated by two of her Sikh
guards.
   Singh's visit is part of his new government's initiative to
solve the Sikh separatist campaign.
   More than 7,500 people have died in the 8-year-old campaign for
the homeland that Sikh extremists propose to carve out of Punjab, a
rich farming state bordering Pakistan.
   Singh, a Hindu, traveled in an open jeep. ``Your love to me is
my security,'' he told the Sikhs who lined up the 2-mile route and
cheered him. He gave autographs to Sikh children and shook hands.
   ``My government will move fast to bring peace and prosperity in
Punjab,'' Singh, 58, told the Sikhs gathered in the 14th century
Golden Temple.
   ``I have not come here for any political or governmental
purposes,'' Singh said. ``I have come to perform prayer in the holy
shrine so that peace and normalcy can be restored in the state once
again.''
   The shrine was the scene of a fierce battle when it was attacked
by Indian troops to flush out Sikh militants entrenched inside.
More than 1,200 people, mostly Sikhs, were killed in the 1984 army
operation that precipitated the revenge slaying of Mrs. Gandhi.
   Sikhs, whose religion is rooted in both Islam and Hinduism,
comprise just 2 percent of India's 880 million people but have a
slight majority in Punjab. Sikh militants claim the government in
the predominantly Hindu nation discriminates against them socially
and politically.
   Hindus make up 82 percent of the population.
   Sikh took office last month after elections that ended the
tenure of Rajiv Gandhi, Mrs. Gandhi's son and immediate successor.
   The new government issued formal orders Dec. 2 to free top Sikh
leaders from jails, including a new member of Parliament who was
accused of plotting the 1984 assassination of Mrs. Gandhi.
   Simranjit Singh Mann, a former police officer accused of
conspiracy, was released from jail after the government withdrew
cases against him. Mann was elected to the lower house of
Parliament from Punjab by an overwhelming majority in last month's
national elections.
   Other leaders released were Gurcharan Singh Tohra, chief of the
Sikh temple management committee, and Prakash Singh Badal, a former
chief minister of Punjab.
   Mann, 44, who has been jailed for the past five years on
sedition charges, was charged with conspiracy when the
assassination case was re-opened in April.
</TEXT>
