<DOCNO> AP891207-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Comoros     12-07 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Comoros,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Threatens Aid Cutoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORONI, Comoro Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France has cut off aid to the
Comorro Republic until a French mercenary who led a successful coup
that claimed the president's life leaves the Indian Ocean
archipelago.
   In the capital today, soldiers used tear gas and clubs to
disperse about 1,000 high school students who marched through the
streets to demand that he and the other mercenaries involved in the
Nov. 26 takeover leave.
   The students, carrying placards reading ``mercenaries out'' and
``assassins, assassins,'' gathered in front of the French Embassy.
   They marched to the beachfront, where they were confronted by
dozens of members of the Comoran presidential guard, founded by
French mercenary Bob Denard and led by about 30 French and Belgian
soldiers of fortune.
   The guardsmen were supported by vehicles equipped with heavy
machine-guns. Many students threw themselves into the water when
the troops arrived. Others fled. Most later regrouped before the
Ministry of the Interior in the city center, where the guardsmen
launched tear-gas grenades and charged with clubs.
   There were no immediate reports of injuries.
   Several photographers and journalists covering the march had
their film and notebooks seized.
   The demonstration came as France cut off its $25 million in
annual aid to the Comoro Republic over the coup.
   French government sources in Paris said Wednesday that the aid
will not be renewed until Denard leaves the islands.
   Various diplomatic sources have said President Ahmed Abdallah
Abderrahmane died in an attack carried out or directed by Denard,
commander of the 500-man guard that diplomats say now controls the
island. The guard has reportedly disarmed the 500-man regular army.
   Denard, who ousted and later returned Abdallah to the presidency
in coups during the 1970s, has denied involvement in the
assassination.
   Students jeered the 60-year-old Frenchman, a convert to Islam
married to a Comoro woman, on Tuesday with taunts of ``assassin''
after he left a mosque after saying prayers.
   France and South Africa are the main sources of foreign
investment in the archipelago, located midway between Mozambique
and Madagascar.
   South Africa demanded an end to the mercenary presence Monday,
and both countries are reported to be trying to make a deal with
Denard and his men to leave. Denard said Tuesday he has not been
approached by French officials with such an offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
