<FIRST>r a PM-NAACPOfficialJailed     12-07 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NAACP Official Jailed,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alabama NAACP President Begins Four-Year Prison Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Alabama NAACP has
begun serving a four-year sentence for a federal bribery conviction.
   Thomas Reed, 61, a former Alabama House member, surrendered at
11:30 a.m. Wednesday to a minimum-security prison in Pensacola, Fla.
   Donna Stratman, assistant superintendent at the 300-inmate
Staufley Field prison, said Reed was fingerprinted, photographed
and assigned a standard prison uniform.
   She said the prison, which has no fences, is located on Navy
property and inmates have work assignments in the facility or on
the Navy base.
   Reed, who in 1970 became one of the first two blacks to serve in
the Alabama Legislature since Reconstruction, was ousted from his
seat after he was convicted in September 1988 of accepting $10,000
as a bribe to help obtain an early release for a convicted
murderer, Anthony Chesser.
   The parole board denied the parole after Reed's involvement
became known. Chesser was released earlier this year.
   Reed was re-elected president of the Alabama chapter of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in
August, and said last week he has no plans to resign.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta recently
upheld the conviction, but Reed's attorneys plan to take the case
to the Supreme Court.
   His attorneys say Reed, who predicts he will be vindicated,
should get a new trial because a jury heard about his attempts to
remove the Confederate flag from the Alabama Capitol.
</TEXT>
