<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Consent 1stLd-Writethru a0499 12-07 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Consent, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0499,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan House Approves Parental Consent for Teen-age Abortions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Under the...', to CORRECT that one parent's
permission is required, sted parents'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA ZAGAROLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state House has passed a bill
requiring parental consent for unmarried girls under age 18 to have
an abortion in Michigan.
   The bill passed 65-39 Wednesday after the house rejected nearly
50 amendments, including one to require boys to wear condoms to
prevent teen-age pregnancy.
   It now goes to the Senate, which has passed a similar measure
and is expected to take action before lawmakers leave for the
winter holidays next week.
   That sets up a promised veto by Gov. James Blanchard, who has
pledged to strike down any measure restricting abortion rights.
   Opponents of the bill say it is merely intended to make it more
difficult for girls to get an abortion. Planned Parenthood
officials said at least 70 percent of pregnant minors in Michigan
already bring at least one parent to an abortion clinic with them.
   ``This bill is meant to put the squeeze on teen-agers with no
regard to the horrible alternatives they may seek,'' said Rep.
Maxine Berman, a Democrat. ``Can any of you live with yourself if a
woman resorts to a back-alley abortion, or to crack cocaine to
induce abortion, or to suicide? I don't want any more young people
to die.''
   Under the legislation, a pregnant girl could petition a probate
court to have an abortion if she believes she can't tell a parent
or if the parent refuses to let her have an abortion. Permission
would be required from just one of the parents.
   ``We're talking about the very bedrock of our society _
family,'' said Democratic Rep. Michael Griffin, the bill's sponsor.
``We recognize there are families in trouble, that's why we put the
judicial bypass in there.''
   William Kandler, spokesman for Blanchard, said the Democratic
governor wouldn't change his mind despite a poll by The Detroit
News that said 68 percent of state residents favor a parental
consent requirement.
   ``I'm hopeful the governor will think about parents and not his
own personal beliefs,'' said Barbara Listing, president of Right to
Life of Michigan.
   Margy Long, spokeswoman for Planned Parenthood of Michigan, said
she was encouraged by at least 40 signatures collected on the House
floor asking the governor to veto the bill.
   That is more than enough to sustain a veto in the 109-member
House, although supporters of the bill say they have enough votes
for an override in the Senate.
   Meanwhile, the state Department of Public Health reported
Wednesday that the number of abortions in Michigan during the third
quarter of 1989 fell 23 percent from the same period last year.
   The drop comes on the heels of similar declines reported
beginning in late 1988 with the implementation of a ban on
state-funded Medicaid abortions for poor women.
   The 8,696 abortions between July 1 and Sept. 30 compared with
11,358 in the same months in 1988.
</TEXT>
