<FIRST>r i PM-QuakeAnniversary     12-07 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake Anniversary,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Year After Quake, Armenians Mourn The Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINAKAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bells tolled and mournful chants
filled the streets today as Armenia marked the one-year anniversary
of the earthquake that killed at least 25,000 people.
   In this mountain city hit hardest by the quake, officials
stopped the big town clock forever at 11:41, the minute disaster
struck Dec. 7, 1988.
   ``If only it could all have been a dream, and we could wake up
and have everyone here again,'' Armenian poet Maro Marzarian told a
crowd of several hundred gathered to dedicate a memorial to
Leninakan's victims.
   In a cemetery just outside town, hundreds of families gathered
at gravesites, some openly sobbing, others in stony silence. Among
the many graves of the earthquake victims were plots for the
remains of unidentifiable corpses, with markers reading only ``238
woman'' or ``453 child.''
   ``Your soul hurts so much you just can't express it,'' said
Lilia Stepanian, 25, whose brother, Zillik, and his family were
crushed to death in their Leninakan apartment.
   ``You remember that on this day, at this time, they were already
gone,'' she said. ``At this time one year ago I was standing by our
house, only it wasn't a house any more.''
   She said Zillik's 3-year-old daughter could be heard crying from
the ruins of the house but rescuers could not reach her.
   ``And the people left alive have such a hard time,'' Ms.
Stepanian said. She and her mother have moved to the Armenian
capital, Yerevan, until Leninakan housing can be built for them.
They don't expect that anytime soon.
   The earthquake measuring 6.9 on the Richter scale killed at
least 25,000 people and left 500,000 people homeless.
   A year after the earthquake, 20,000 people are still missing,
according to the relief agency Search.
   The destruction was massive. The town of Spitak was leveled.
Kirovakan and some 300 villages were shattered.
   In Leninakan alone _ then Armenia's second-largest city with
235,000 people _ the quake destroyed 99 nine-story apartment
buildings, 10 schools, and every factory, officials said.
   The Soviet leadership promised after the quake that Leninakan
and the other demolished communities would be rebuilt within two
years.
</TEXT>
