<DOCNO> AP891207-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DeputiesCharged     12-07 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deputies Charged,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>2 Top Sheriff's Officials Charged With Obstructing Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two deputies have been charged with
conspiring to delay the court-ordered seizure of property from a
financially troubled company, after Mayor W. Wilson Goode called
the sheriff on behalf of the company's owner.
   The delay last January gave the businessman time to avoid the
seizure by declaring bankruptcy.
   Goode says he did nothing wrong by referring the businessman to
the sheriff and said the grand jury report describing the man as a
friend of his was wrong.
   The two deputies surrendered Wednesday to face charges they
conspired to delay the seizure of $160,000 worth of machinery from
Elijah Medley's business.
   A grand jury presentment released Wednesday said Medley faced
the seizure after defaulting on about $500,000 in loans. The grand
jury also raised questions about the involvement of city officials.
   In Pennsylvania, grand juries may issue a presentment
recommending that a prosecutor charge someone, instead of issuing
an indictment bringing the charge itself.
   ``We are concerned that city officials knowingly abused the
power of their office to unfairly benefit one citizen at the
expense of other citizens to impede the orderly administration of
justice,'' the presentment said.
   ``We will continue our investigation to determine if there was a
systemic abuse of power and to determine whether any other public
officials were involved in such conduct.''
   The prosecutor is District Attorney Ronald Castille, a
Republican considered to be a mayoral prospect in 1991.
   Goode and Sheriff John Green, both Democrats, denied any
wrongdoing.
   ``I did not intervene,'' the mayor told reporters. ``I simply
referred a businessman, who is not my friend, to someone who could
help him. ... I can assure you that Ron Castille knows deep down in
his soul that I did nothing wrong.''
   ``I don't do wrong things, and I resent anyone implying that.''
   Green also denied wrongdoing, and said he was confident that
Chief Deputy Joseph Graves Jr., 56, and Lt. Robert Armstrong, 41,
would be exonerated of what he called ``weak charges that have
obvious political implications.''
   The defendants are accused of ``purposely failing to execute a
court-ordered seizure of equipment from Medley Tool and Model
Co.,'' Castille said. The seizure was supposed to have been made
Jan. 30, but it was delayed and the company filed for bankruptcy
Feb. 1.
   Charges against Graves and Armstrong include criminal conspiracy
and tampering with public records or official information, each a
felony punishable by up to seven years in prison.
   Neither Goode nor Green denied the mayor had made a telephone
call on behalf of Medley shortly before the seizure was to have
been made.
   Goode said Medley called him _ the grand jury presentment
described the businessman as the mayor's friend, which Goode said
was inaccurate _ and asked for help about a ``sheriff's sale''
problem for which he needed more time. Goode said he then called
Green at home.
   The sheriff declined to discuss details of the case, but said he
felt it was political. He also said parts of the presentment were
inaccurate.
   Castille, just elected to a second term, said both the mayor and
sheriff appeared to have ``played an integral part'' in the case.
   The presentment said that after the writ was delayed ``Sheriff
Green asked Chief Graves, `Has the mayor's job been taken care of?'
(and) Graves said that it had.''
   The mayor summoned reporters to his City Hall office and denied
he had done anything wrong, insisting the phone call from a
businessman was normal and that all he did was refer it to the
sheriff.
   Medley couldn't be reached by telephone for reaction. His
company, though in bankruptcy, is still in business, but telephone
calls are taken by an answering service.
</TEXT>
