<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Wall     12-07 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Wall,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Accepts Wall's `Unselfish' Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in a letter released today,
accepted the resignation of M. Danny Wall as overseer of the
nation's savings and loan institutions and praised the embattled
regulator for his ``unselfish'' decision to quit.
   ``As the first director of the Office of Thrift Supervision, you
served during the important organizational phase of the new
agency,'' Bush told Wall in a four-paragraph letter dated Wednesday.
   ``I thank you for your hard work in that position, and for your
unselfish recognition that the job of revitalizing the industry
demands the complete and undistracted attention of the agency's
entire leadership and staff,'' the president wrote.
   Wall announced his resignation on Monday, bowing to demands in
Congress that he quit because of his handling of the S&amp;L crisis.
   Wall took over as chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board
in July 1987. Last August, he became director of the thrift office
when the bank board was dismantled under S&amp;L bailout legislation.
   Wall was the focus of six weeks of hearings by the House Banking
Committee, which was investigating his handling of the failure of
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association, Irvine, Calif. It is expected
to be the nation's biggest thrift failure at a cost to taxpayers of
$2 billion.
   Wall told reporters Monday that he was resigning because
continuing the fight with the committee would distract the agency
from conducting its work.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah, accused the administration of
``not having any guts'' for failing to support Wall. Garn, who
brought Wall to Washington in 1975 as his chief aide, made his
remarks in an interview with the Deseret News of Salt Lake City.
   Wall is continuing to serve as thrift office director for an
unspecified transitional period. His successor has not been
selected.
</TEXT>
