<FIRST>u w PM-Poindexter 1stLd-Writethru a0470 12-07 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poindexter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Fights Poindexter Subpoena</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new, recasting; picks up 4th graf pvs, The subpoena.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan is trying to quash a
subpoena for his notes and diaries by onetime national security
adviser John Poindexter, saying it encroaches on the office of the
presidency.
   Poindexter, facing trial Jan. 22, contends that notes and
diaries compiled by Reagan will show the ex-president authorized
the activities for which Poindexter has been accused of crimes.
   In a court filing Wednesday, Reagan said Poindexter's subpoena
was a ``broad-gauge discovery device masquerading as a trial
subpoena'' and that it seeks a ``laundry list'' of documents on 67
different subjects.
   The subpoena raises constitutional concerns about the
president's prerogative to ``maintain a purely personal and private
record of his thoughts and reflections,'' said Reagan's lawyers.
   ``Nothing could be closer to the core of the presidency and more
private than the intimate and confidential communications by the
president with himself,'' the lawyers argued.
   Reagan and the Justice Department suggested in separate filings
that President Bush might become involved in the battle over the
records from Reagan's presidency.
   Reagan suggested a review of a limited number of diary excerpts
by U.S. District Court Judge Harold Greene, who is handling the
Poindexter case.
   ``Only then should the former president and, if appropriate, the
incumbent president be forced to assert or waive executive
privilege,'' Reagan said in the court papers.
   The Justice Department urged the court to consider Bush's views
before taking the ``extremely serious step'' of forcing public
disclosure of Reagan's diaries.
   The Justice Department proposed a procedure under which it would
review a sealed filing that Poindexter made to the court outlining
``what he believes are in the diaries and why he needs them.''
   The department noted that this procedure would not compromise
the secrecy of Poindexter's defense because the office of
independent counsel Lawrence Walsh, not the Justice Department, is
prosecuting the case.
   After reviewing Poindexter's filing, the Justice Department said
it would prepare a response. The court could then inspect excerpts
of the diaries, the Justice Department said.
   The department moved to quash a similar subpoena for Reagan
papers served by Poindexter on the National Archives and Records
Administration. The material sought from the Archives has already
been turned over to Iran-Contra prosecutors, the Justice Department
said.
   Reagan's lawyers said any diary entry must be found by the judge
to be ``central'' to Poindexter's case and ``essential to justice''
before it can be disclosed.
   Earlier Wednesday, the judge rejected a request by Poindexter to
subpoena records from 65 U.S. senators and representatives.
   Greene also denied as overly broad Poindexter's request to issue
subpoenas to a number of congressional committees, the office of
White House counsel and the National Security Agency. The judge did
not disclose how many committees Poindexter wanted to subpoena.
   The judge said the only apparent basis for the proposed
subpoenas to the members of Congress is that they ``at one time or
other met with Oliver North.''
   North, a former National Security Council staff member, was
involved in the secret Contra resupply network and the
administration's arms sales to Iran. He was convicted of three
felonies in the Iran-Contra affair and is appealing.
   Poindexter has said that Reagan ``formulated'' or tacitly
approved ``the administration's position'' on matters for which
Poindexter now faces trial.
   He has said his communications with Reagan included discussion
of a White House chronology that falsely said no one in the U.S.
government knew at the time that a 1985 shipment to Iran contained
Hawk missiles.
   Another subject Poindexter says he discussed with Reagan is the
administration's view of a proposed House resolution of inquiry
into North's secret Contra resupply network. Poindexter is accused
of obstructing Congress by endorsing earlier denials that the
National Security Council staff was soliciting funds or
coordinating military efforts for the Contras.
</TEXT>
