<FIRST>r a PM-BoysKilled     12-07 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boys Killed,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth Found in Contempt for Not Testifying to Grand Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-year-old who was with two boys shot
to death by a police officer after a car chase has been found in
contempt of court for refusing to testify before a grand jury.
   The boy, whose name has not been released because he is a
juvenile, was sentenced Wednesday by Dakota County District Judge
George Hoey to 90 days in the Ramsey County Juvenile Detention
Center. Hoey said he would release the boy if he decides to testify
before the grand jury adjourns, which is expected Friday.
   The grand jury is investigating the Nov. 15 shooting.
   According to court documents, three boys ran from a stolen car
they had driven into a ditch as police chased them. The 14-year-old
ran in a different direction from Thai Yang and Ba See Lor, both
13. Lor and Yang were killed by a shotgun blast to their backs
fired by Kenneth Murphy, an Inver Grove Heights police officer,
according to court documents.
   Murphy said one of the boys pointed a screwdriver, and he
mistook it for a gun.
   The boy refused to testify Wednesday even after a special state
prosecutor assured the boy's attorney he would not be indicted.
   Villaume maintained that the grand jury is independent of the
prosecutor and it could indict the boy on a charge of murder.
People can be charged with murder when deaths occur during the
commission of a felony, in this case the car theft.
   The killings angered Minnesota's substantial community of
Southeast Asian refugees. The boys' parents, who live in St. Paul,
are Hmong immigrants.
</TEXT>
