<FIRST>r a PM-AMA-AIDS     12-07 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AMA-AIDS,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMA Supports AIDS Notification; Attacks Tobacco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Medical Association policymakers have
recommended that communities set up systems to find and notify
unsuspecting sexual or needle-sharing partners of people infected
with the AIDS virus.
   The AMA's House of Delegates on Wednesday also broadened its
attack on drug abuse to include tobacco-related diseases.
   The delegates approved the AIDS notification policy by voice
vote as part of a resolution that encourages state legislatures to
establish laws for reporting and following up on serious
communicable diseases including AIDS.
   The resolution says communities and prisons should have systems
to notify people who are at risk of AIDS because they have sexual
partners or share drug needles with infected people.
   Dr. David Johnson of Arkansas said concern for patient privacy
should be secondary in light of the number of AIDS deaths in the
United States. As of the end of October, the federal health
authorities had recorded 112,241 cases of AIDS in the United
States, with 66,493 deaths.
   However, former military physician J. William Cox of San Diego
protested, saying devising a system to keep track of sexual or
drug-use partners would ``waste incredible amounts of money'' and
drive people infected with the AIDS virus underground.
   In other business, the association resisted an attempt to remove
tobacco from a resolution naming substance abuse its top health
priority.
   The resolution included the endorsement of a routine screening
program for all pregnant women and those of childbearing age for
evidence of substance abuse.
   Before ending its three-day meeting Wednesday, the AMA delegates
also ordered the restructuring of the group's internal organization
and restricted the authority of its executive vice president.
   That action came after AMA Executive Vice President James H.
Sammons approved two financial deals with executives that failed
and caused thousands of dollars in losses.
   Sammons accepted full responsibility for the deals and a call
for his immediate resignation failed, with more than two-thirds of
the 435 delegates supporting him. Sammons is due to retire at the
end of next year.
   The organization's 280,000 members account for about half the
doctors in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
