<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls-Bush     12-07 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Bush,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Wall but Garn Raps White House for Lack of Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Keating Money Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush praised savings and loan
regulator M. Danny Wall in a letter released Thursday, but a
prominent Republican senator criticized the administration for not
defending Wall who announced his resignation Monday under fire.
   While Bush saluted Wall for ``unselfish recognition'' that he
could best help the industry by quitting, Sen. Jake Garn of Utah,
the senior Republican on the Senate Banking Committee, accused the
administration of ``not having any guts'' and failing to support
the regulator.
   Wall was a focus of six weeks of hearings by the House Banking
Committee, which was investigating his handling of the failure of
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, Calif. Lincoln is
expected to be the nation's biggest thrift failure at a cost to
taxpayers of $2 billion.
   ``I am disappointed'' in the administration's dealing with Wall,
Garn said in an interview with the Deseret News in Salt Lake City,
Utah. ``If it had been their nominee, their appointment, they
would'' have supported Wall, who earlier served 12 years as the
senator's top aide, he said.
   Garn said, ``Dan was a Reagan appointee and they certainly in no
way came to his defense.''
   Bush, in a ``Dear Danny'' letter dated Wednesday, commended Wall
for hard work as director of the Office of Thrift Supervision and
for his ``unselfish recognition that the job of revitalizing the
industry demands the complete and undistracted attention of the
agency's entire leadership and staff.''
   Calls for Wall's resignation had come from Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine; Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,
chairman of the House Banking Committee; several major newspapers
and citizens groups. White House Counsel C. Boyden Gray was also
reported to be seeking his oustr, and Bush and Treasury Secretary
Nicholas F. Brady failed to come to his defense in public.
   Wall took over as chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board
in July 1987. In August of this year, he became director of the
thrift office when the bank board was dismantled under S&amp;L bailout
legislation.
   He told a news conference he was resigning because continuing
the fight with the committee would distract the agency from
conducting its work. He is continuing to serve as thrift office
director for an unspecified transitional period.
</TEXT>
