<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru   12-07 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0545,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Renew Attacks on Several San Salvador Neighborhoods</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with new attacks. Changes byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas renewed
their assault on the Salvadoran capital today, setting up positions
in at least seven neighborhoods and battling government soldiers.
   The rebels claimed they shot down a military helicopter, but the
government said it suffered a mechanical problem and crashed.
   A statement by the armed forces press office said columns of
rebels infiltrated the metropolitan area from the north, east and
west during the night, including the upper-class Escalon and San
Benito districts.
   There were no immediate reports of casualties, a military
spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity for security
reasons.
   Planes and helicopter gunships flew over the city during the
night, dropping flares and strafing suspected rebel positions,
while troops on the ground opened up with automatic weapons fire.
   But the new outbreak was much smaller than the fighting that
began when guerrillas launched an urban offensive on Nov. 11 as
part of their decade-old struggle for power against a succession of
U.S.-backed governments.
   Fighting had subsided to a few scarce shots since Friday after
the rebels withdrew from an incursion in Escalon and San Benito.
   Also reported under attack were the working-class neighborhoods
of Aytuxtepeque, San Ramon and Soyapango, north and east of the
city, and the small town of Apopa, to the north, the military said.
   The military spokesman said a U.S.-made helicopter crashed
during the night because ``of mechanical failure,'' but the rebels'
clandestine Radio Venceremos claimed it was shot down by guerrilla
fire.
   In the broadcast, the guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front also announced they were renewing their sabotage
campaign against electric power installations and other economic
targets.
   Rebel groups destroyed two city buses, and five private
automobiles were destroyed by guerrillas in Santa Ana, 25 miles
west of the capital, and a burlap bag factory in San Miguel, 85
miles east of San Salvador.
   The rebels also were reported to have dynamited a bridge on the
Litoral Highway near the city of Usulutan, 70 miles east of the
capital.
   In an unrelated development, the government allowed three U.S.
Episcopalian bishops to enter the country to check on several
Episcopalians who were imprisoned during the recent offensive by
leftist guerrillas.
   Bishops William Frey of the diocese of Colorado, David Reed of
Kentucky, and William Swing of California arrived Wednesday on a
commercial flight from Miami and went through immigration
proceedings with no problems.
   The first two had come on Tuesday and were told by immigration
authorities their visas were invalid. They were put on a flight
back to Miami, where they spent the night before making the second
attempt to enter.
   Frey said President Alfredo Cristiani sent a letter by telefax
apologizing for the previous day's problems.
</TEXT>
