<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Bavier 1stLd-Writethru a0498 12-07 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Bavier, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frances Bavier, Mayberry's `Aunt Bee,' Dead at Age 86</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Griffith via
his manager. Picks up 4th graf, `Actor-singer Jim...'. SUBS 9th graf pvs,
`She became...', to delete now-redundant first reference to Griffith. `Bee'
is cq.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SILER CITY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frances Bavier, the Emmy Award-winning
actress remembered by millions of TV viewers as the lovable Aunt
Bee on ``The Andy Griffith Show'' in the 1960s, has died at age 86.
   Miss Bavier died at home Wednesday, said Leslie Fletcher of
Smith and Buckner Funeral Home.
   She had been released Monday from a hospital, where she had been
treated for almost two weeks in the coronary care unit.
   Dick Linke, manager for Andy Griffith, who played Sheriff Andy
Taylor in the series, said Griffith wanted people to know that Miss
Bavier ``was a fine woman, a wonderful actress and most of all, a
brilliant character actress. Even though she was from New York
City, she played Aunt Bee so perfectly that everyone believed she
was Aunt Bee and from North Carolina.
   ``We who knew her and worked with her will always remember her.
We say goodbye with a great deal of sadness,'' said Linke.
   Actor-singer Jim Nabors, when notified of her death at his
Hawaii home, recalled that Miss Bavier ``was very, very good to me
when I first started out and I was totally inexperienced in the
business.''
   ``She was always one of my favorite people,'' said Nabors, who
played gas station attendant Gomer Pyle in the series. ``I am a
better person for having known her.''
   He said she taught him a lot about ``personal kindness,''
adding: ``During my free time she taught me about antique
shopping.''
   Miss Bavier, a New York City native who would have turned 87
this month, attended Columbia University and was a graduate of the
American Academy of the Arts.
   She had more than 20 years of stage experience, including stints
in vaudeville and on Broadway, where she appeared in such
productions as ``Kiss and Tell,'' ``Point of No Return'' and ``The
Lady Says No.''
   She became famous for her role in the popular show starring
Griffith as a North Carolina sheriff. She portrayed the devoted
aunt, who was known for her Southern cooking and who helped raise
the widower Taylor's son, Opie, portrayed by Ron Howard.
   She continued in the role in the short-lived series ``Mayberry
RFD.'' She won an Emmy for the role in 1967.
   ``The Andy Griffith Show'' was in the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings
top 10 during its entire run, from October 1960 to September 1968,
culminating in a No. 1 ranking in its final season.
   ``Many episodes focused on her and she was essential to the
success of the show,'' said John Meroney, founder of the Andy
Griffith Show Appreciation Society. ``When she started on the show
she was 57 and had more experience going in than any of the other
cast members.
   ``She was the only one from a large city and the fact that she
could portray Aunt Bee showed the depth of her talent.''
   Although she was born in New York and lived in Hollywood during
her acting days, Miss Bavier, as Aunt Bee, often spoke of ``going
shopping in Siler City.''
   She had visited the mill town of 5,000 in 1963 while dieting at
Duke Medical Center. She retired here in 1972 when she left
Hollywood. She made a cameo appearance in the 1974 movie ``Benji.''
   ``I fell in love with North Carolina,'' she said in a 1981
interview. ``All the pretty roads and the trees. I, like a child,
came here looking for a fairyland.''
   It wasn't quite like the ficticious Mayberry _ fans continually
rang her door bell _ but she adjusted to her new home and never
left Siler City.
   ``Sometimes people just gawk and gape,'' she said in a 1972
interview, ``and sometimes they're utterly charming and sweet.''
   In the 1981 interview, she said: ``I know how people saw me as
Aunt Bee. I'm still a compassionate person. That's how I want them
to remember me.''
   During her recent hospital stay, Miss Bavier received many
cards, letters and flowers from fans.
   She had refused media requests for interviews for some time.
</TEXT>
