<FIRST>u w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0460 12-07 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>For 3:10 p.m. EST release</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Trip Combines Drug-Bashing and Political Fund Raising</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Leads with 11 grafs on Bush text at drug rally; picks up 6th
graf pvs, bgng ``Bush's national...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, likening the U.S. war against
drugs to people's quest for freedom in Eastern Europe, today lauded
a poor black community that united to drive drug dealers out of a
public park.
   ``As with the new freedom in Eastern Europe, freedom from drugs
isn't something the government can give you,'' Bush said in remarks
prepared for an anti-drug rally at Winzer Park in his adopted
hometown.
   ``You've got to take a stand. You've got to take back the
streets,'' he urged.
   He lauded the tenants and community activists from the Acres
Homes War on Drugs Committee, who helped sweep drug dealers out of
Winzer Park last year and organized neighborhood crime-watches to
keep them out.
   He said that like those demanding freedom to travel and vote in
Eastern Europe, the Acres Homes residents ``have used `people
power' to fight for another kind of freedom: freedom from fear;
freedom from crime; freedom from drugs.''
   Bush said Acres Home was once ``the embodiment of the American
dream,'' the largest unincorporated black community in the South.
   ``But in recent years, the dream on Main Street has become the
nightmare on Elm Street, a twisted, backwards world where our
children and our playgrounds are taken away by an evil menace
called cocaine, often in broad daylight,'' he said.
   By 1987, 25 to 30 drug dealers were operating in Winzer Park,
and a circular drive was so clogged with cars of drug-buyers ``that
police called it `crack-in-the-box,''' Bush said.
   But since 1,000 community activists joined with police to drive
the dealers out on April 9, 1988, ``they haven't come back. And
they better not.'' He said the local residents had taken a stand
against ``evil.''
   ``Efforts like yours are a critical part of America's
battleplan'' against drugs, said Bush, who unveiled his $8 billion
strategy three months ago. He said parents, teachers and other
community leaders must teach children right from wrong and instill
a sense of personal accountability.
   ``Only you can cultivate character and a sense of value in our
kids. It is not a federal problem for which there is a simple
federal solution,'' he said. ``We can't do it by looking to the
government alone.''
   He named the Acres Home War On Drugs group as a recipient of one
of his Presidential Points of Light _ a daily honor highlighting
outstanding volunteers.
   Bush was attending a fund-raiser dinner in the Astrodome tonight
for Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, before journeying to Colorado and
Iowa on Friday.
   He will spend the night in Houston, his adoptive home, before
heading to Denver for another anti-drug rally and a campaign
luncheon for Rep. Hank Brown, R-Colo., a U.S. Senate candidate.
   Bush's national drug policy coordinator, William Bennett, also
visited Winzer Park recently.
   On Friday, Bush will take part in an anti-drug rally with
members of the Denver Broncos football team, then fly to Des Moines
to address a fund-raising dinner for Rep. Tom Tauke, R-Iowa. Tauke
plans to run for the Senate seat of Democratic Sen. Tom Harkin.
   Bush's trip on behalf of domestic anti-drug efforts comes a day
after more violence rocked the drug-producing nation of Colombia. A
truck bomb exploded outside police headquarters in Bogota, killing
dozens and wounding hundreds during morning rush hour.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Colombia is
still being considered as a site for the February drug summit that
Bush will attend with the leaders of Peru, Colombia and Bolivia,
the chief drug-producing nations.
   However, he said, other sites outside of Colombia are also being
considered.
   ``Wherever we hold it, we will do so with the assurance that we
can provide security for the president,'' he told reporters.
   Speaking about another Latin American trouble spot, Fitzwater
said the Nicaraguan Contra rebels had ``no alternative'' but to
stay intact as a fighting force despite a regional peace accord
requiring them to disband Dec. 5.
   Fitzwater contended that Nicaragua's ruling Sandinista
government has not lived up to its commitments under the August
agreement to promote democratic reforms and encourage repatriation
of the Contras.
</TEXT>
