<FIRST>u w PM-Summit-Economy 1stLd-Writethru a0471 12-07 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Skeptical About Gorbachev's Attempt to Fix Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs with Fitzwater reax after 5th graf, The official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is voicing deep
skepticism about Mikhail S. Gorbachev's efforts to repair the
Soviet Union's ailing economy, saying his ideas are simplistic and
``just far from the real world.''
   The gloomy assessment arises from Gorbachev's weekend talks with
President Bush during a two-day summit off the Mediterranean island
of Malta.
   A senior administration official, intimately acquainted with the
two leaders' discussions, said Gorbachev demonstrated he has ``less
than a realistic economic notion of how to deal with his economic
problems.''
   Referring to Gorbachev's ideas, the official said, ``They're
simplistic.''
   The official discussed the summit with a small group of
reporters at the White House under assurances of remaining
anonymous.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, speaking with reporters
today aboard Air Force One as Bush flew to Houston, said, ``We
wouldn't use that word.''
   Fitzwater said that the Soviets do have ``a lack of knowledge
about how free enterprise systems work and how market economies
work. And that was reflected in the conversation'' between Bush and
Gorbachev at Malta.
   He said ``simplistic'' was ``not a very good word to use. But
there is going to be a problem in introducing free market economies
to these (Marxist) countries.''
   The Soviet Union is suffering from widespread shortages of food,
fuel and consumer goods despite Gorbachev's program of economic
reform, known as perestroika.
   The problems are expected to worsen during the bitter Soviet
winter, raising fears of civil unrest.
   ``A lot of his economic definitions and ideas and so on come out
of a kind of Marxist mold and they're just far from the real
world,'' the official said.
   In particular, the official mentioned Gorbachev's views on
converting the ruble to a hard currency, his lack of information
about the benefits of a central bank comparable to the U.S. Federal
Reserve and his ideas about long-term leasing of land and factories
to Soviet farmers and workers.
   ``The other side of it was, here is a man of great
self-confidence,'' the official said. ``There was no hint of
self-doubt given the immensity of the problems he faces, which he
acknowledges, but (he was) very, very self-assured.''
   Bush and Gorbachev held eight hours of talks in their first
superpower summit.
   The official said Gorbachev was ``more self-controlled'' than in
his five earlier summit meetings with President Reagan.
   ``Clearly he wanted to establish a relationship with the
president, and wanted this to be good,'' the official said.
   During the summit, Bush offered an array of economic concessions
to help Gorbachev deal with his economic problems.
   The president proposed completion of a U.S.-Soviet trade
agreement by June 1990, granting ``most favored nation'' status to
Moscow, giving it the lowest possible tariffs for its exports.
   The most favored nation status would be linked with the waiver
of a 1974 law that imposed trade sanctions against Moscow in
retaliation for restrictions on emigration by Soviet Jews.
   Bush also proposed giving Moscow observer status at a world
organization that sets international trading rules, the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. Until now, the United States had
strongly opposed Soviet participation.
   ``I think he needs a lot more sophistiction,'' the official said
about Gorbachev. ``One of the things that will help him get the
sophistication is something like observer status at GATT, so he can
have a look at how the world economy really works.
   ``I'm not sure where he wants to go with economic reforms,'' the
official added.
   While welcoming Bush's economic package, Gorbachev ``was not at
all in a posture of saying, `We want your help,''' the official
said.
   ``What they don't want is the notion that the United States is
going to come in to bail them out. We're not going to do it,
anyway.''
   On another subject, the official said Gorbachev suggested some
flexibility toward ethnic unrest in the Baltic states.
   The official said the Soviet leader said he was prepared ``to
look on all kinds of autonomy,'' but that he would ``draw the line
at independence.'' The official quoted Gorbachev as saying, ```We
need to look for new structures to meet new circumstances.'''
   The official added, ``He seemed quite open to experimentation.''
</TEXT>
