<FIRST>u i AM-Czech-Statue     12-07 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Statue,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>Villagers Want to Sell Their Statue of Stalin</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOMAROV, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A banner on the outskirts says,
``With Soviet Union Forever,'' but the people of this Bohemian
village want to sell their 20-foot statue of Josef Stalin for
Western currency.
   ``Everyone in town is with the revolution against the Communists
except one guy, and he's in the secret police,'' said butcher
Vaclav Jicha.
   ``Well, maybe 10 percent of Komarov opposes these changes, but
all of the rest are happy,'' said elementary school teacher, Jiri
Beran.
   Whatever the numbers, a glance outside Prague shows that the
students' November revolution is firmly implanted in smaller cities
and rural areas.
   In Plzen, an industrial city 50 miles west of Prague,
anti-Communist posters are less evident than in the capital. But
attitudes are clear. During last week's strike, even the fabled
Urquell Pilsener beer stopped flowing.
   ``No one hesitated when we asked them to stop,'' said Jan
Kylbergr, strike organizer at Prazdroj Brewery. Workers left even
before he got a chance to read his manifesto.
   ``We won't have to disband Communist groups here,'' added
Kylbergr, 27. ``They'll destroy themselves.''
   If any place in Czechoslovakia exemplifies the new mood, it is
Komarov, a village of 2,200 people about 30 miles southwest of
Prague.
   Komarov makes machine parts _ no one likes to be more specific _
and the factory put up an immense stone statue of Stalin in the
1950s. It's still there on the square, one of the last Stalin
monuments left in Europe.
   Reformers were about to smash it into gravel when a visiting
professor mentioned someone in Britain collected Stalin
memorabilia. Komarov townsfolk, in need of an old-age home, figured
Stalin might be of some use to them after all.
   That was a few days ago. The plan, in its earliest stages, has
not yet reached the proper channels for approval.
   At first glance, Komarov looks like a party town. Walls are
festooned with red stars, the odd hammer and sickle, and
standard-issue Marxist-Leninist poster art.
   A bulletin board announced a party youth march. And there was
Stalin's statue, identifying him as, ``The Greater Teacher of
Working People, Liberator of our Country.''
   Asked about it, Beran advised: ``Don't pay any attention to that
garbage. Look over there.'' He pointed to glass double doors to the
little shopping mall, plastered with leaflets from the opposition
Civic Forum.
   Inside, in a well-stocked store offering everything from bidets
to bicycles, saleswoman Iva Bartipanova explained how the pamphlets
got there.
   ``We didn't know anything about what was happening in Prague
until these things appeared on the doors,'' she said. ``During the
night, someone ripped them off. But then they appeared again.''
   When demonstrations began in Prague, volunteer taxi drivers took
students and actors from town to town to spread the word. They
found willing ears in Komarov.
   ``Anyone who lived through the 1968 invasion must support what
the Civic Forum is doing,'' Mrs. Bartipanova said. In 1968, she was
just bringing her infant son home from the hospital when she ran
into Soviet troops headquartered just up the road.
   Down a country road from Komarov, Josef Prochazka, 65, lives
alone on isolated farm the state decided to return to him last year
after keeping it for four decades. He knows all about the uprising.
   Prochazka could hardly believe it. Back in the 1950s, he watched
the Communist militia shoot two men who mocked the idea of
collective farms. He spent years in a forced labor camp because his
father would not join a collective. He suffered later when a nephew
defected.
   Now he makes a meager living sawing logs in the farm's small
mill, which the state still owns.
   Despite it all, he has swung right back into political
kibitzing, in Czechoslovakia's democratic tradition.
   ``The opposition is doing the wrong thing,'' he said. ``We need
two strong parties, the Peoples Party and the Socialists.''
   In sharp contrast to the immediate past, almost everyone was
happy to talk. Mothers pushing babies in prams carefully spelled
out their names. Young soldiers described their enthusiasm, and
their officers' misgivings.
   For Frantisek Sojka, a 85-year-old pensioner in a moth-eaten fur
hat, the biggest surprise of the revolution was seeing an American
reporter and English photographer wandering around loose.
   Sojka would just as soon keep the Stalin statue _ it is art, he
says, _ but he wants to see it accompanied by a monument to Tomas
Masaryk, Czechoslovakia's first president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
