<FIRST>u a PM-IowaReturn 1stLd-Writethru a0536 12-07 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa Return, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0536,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Returning Home to Continuing Controversy Over Cause Of April
Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with arrival, reporters kept from
interviewing families. Picks up 2nd graf, `Adm. J.D....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battleship USS Iowa, its No. 2 turret
still sealed after an April explosion that killed 47 sailors,
arrived today to cheers from the crew's family and friends after a
six-month deployment in the Mediterranean.
   The crew lined the rail, bundled in pea coats to protect against
cold, blustery winds, as the Iowa docked at its home port shortly
after 1 p.m.
   A cheer went up from more than 1,000 family members and friends
when the ship appeared on the horizon, then they waited patiently
for it to dock.
   Navy officials kept reporters about 500 yards away from the
crowd. During normal homecomings, the crew, families and media
representatives are free to mix after the ship ties up.
   ``We're doing this to protect the privacy of the crewmen and
their families,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Steve Burnett, a Navy spokesman.
   Adm. J.D. Williams, the 6th Fleet commander in the
Mediterranean, laid the groundwork for a festive welcome by telling
crew families in a letter, ``Pull out all the stops for the Iowa's
homecoming.''
   In contrast, the Iowa's return to Norfolk Naval Base four days
after the April 19 gun turret explosion was somber and silent.
   Then, the 1,500 crewmen in their white uniforms lined the
battleship's rails. Each crewman wore a black armband. As tugs
nudged the 887-foot warship was nudged toward the pier, the several
thousand people on shore stood silent.
   The Navy's controversial report on the explosion was released in
September while the Iowa was at sea. It found the blast most likely
was caused by a disgruntled gunner's mate who sabotaged the huge
gun and died in the explosion.
   That report is being challenged by many of the families of the
47 victims who believe the Navy is covering up equipment and
training failures aboard the World War II-era battleship.
   Congressional committees will hear testimony next week from Navy
officials and FBI experts. Navy investigators found that sabotage
was the only explanation for the explosion, but the FBI has
declined to endorse that conclusion because its tests and
investigation failed to duplicate the Navy's findings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Philippines 3rdLd-Writethru a0596 12-07 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Philippines, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0596,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Says Mrs. Aquino in Precarious Position</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs of State Dept. comment after 9th graf, Asked
about; deletes last 4 grafs pvs to shorten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional leaders expressed concern today
about the depth of opposition to Philippine President Corazon
Aquino, despite her apparent success in quelling the latest coup
against her government.
   ``It appears that the immediate threat to Mrs. Aquino's
government has been removed, but it's troubling that some of the
rebel military elements (are) among the most professional and
proficient Philippine military,'' House Speaker Thomas S. Foley
told reporters outside the White House after a meeting with
President Bush.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., said the coup raises concerns about
U.S. aid for the Philippines, especially as the two nations enter
negotiations for the future of the major U.S. bases there.
   ``We're obviously concerned about what that money's going to be
spent on, what the government's going to be there,'' said Leahy.
   Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., said this was the best organized coup
to date. ``Our intelligence shows us if they keep stepping it up
grade by grade, she will be in deep trouble,'' he said.
   Simpson noted that Congress has been considering aid of up to
$1.6 billion, including benefits for Philippine war veterans, as
part of the price of renewing base leases.
   A senior adminstration official said Wedneday that despite
putting down the coup, Mrs. Aquino's political future appears
uncertain.
   ``She's been hurt, there's no question about it,'' said the
official, adding that Mrs. Aquino should ``take seriously what
happened.''
   Asked about those comments today, White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said, ``On the record, we would not speculate on'' Mrs.
Aquino's future. He acknowledged that the United States has
concerns about the situation and certain Philippine policies, ``but
that does not diminish the fact that we support her and her
government and we hope that they're successful.''
   At the State Department, spokesman Richard Boucher said ``Mrs.
Aquino's government has shown incredible resilience in this
situation,'' and he restated ``our very strong support for her.''
   Setting a more optimistic tone than the senior official, Boucher
said pessimism surrounded a coup attempt in 1987, but that the
Phillipines rebounded rapidly and continued its economic growth.
   The United States now expects ``that the Philippine people can
pull together under President Aquino's leadership'' to achieve a
similar recovery from the latest unrest, he said.
   The official, briefing a small group of reporters Wednesday on
the condition that he not be identified further, apparently was
seeking to send a clear message to Mrs. Aquino's U.S.-backed
government to become more responsive to criticism within her
country.
   Mrs. Aquino's future may depend on her ability to ``eliminate
the sources of discontent,'' the official said.
   Uneasiness among the Philippine population in general, and
within the military in particular, is a sure sign of trouble ``and
as a political leader she has to deal with it,'' the official said.
   Asked if Mrs. Aquino could survive politically, the official
said: ``That's a tough one.''
   He spoke as the coup attempt _ the sixth since she took office
in 1986 _ seemed to be running out of steam. Rebel forces who had
fortified themselves in Manila's Makati business district returned
voluntarily to their barracks Thursday.
   However, it remained unclear whether the announcement marked the
end of the coup.
   At least 79 people have been killed and more than 570 wounded
since Friday.
   Earlier, U.S. officials praised as ``careful and effective'' a
Philippine evacuation that freed 280 Americans and other foreign
citizens from the Manila hotels where they had been trapped by
gunfire in the 7-day-old rebellion.
   ``We commend the Aquino government for organizing and carrying
out this operation,'' said State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler, applauding the ``careful and effective manner in which it
dealt with the situation in the Makati commercial district and the
efforts it took to safeguard American citizens and others who were
in the area.''
   The senior administration official said that, with U.S. military
help, Mrs. Aquino had appeared to survive ``an almost-successful
coup,'' correcting himself to say ``a serious attempted coup.''
   In any event, he said, ``I think that if she takes seriously
what happened and tries to eliminate the sources of discontent
which helped lead to the coup, it may come out'' all right for her.
   ``We really have to reassess what all this means.''
   Asked to elaborate, he said: ``We have to assess what this has
done and the American assistance in terms of the situation. People
will use the fact that she called on America against her.''
   President Bush heeded Mrs. Aquino's plea for help last Friday,
sending F-4 fighter jets from Clark Air Base screaming over two air
fields held by rebels, preventing the insurgents from using those
fields to launch additional attacks.
   The United States gave $650 million to the Aquino government
this year, the third largest foreign aid package, behind only
Israel and Egypt. The United States maintains two bases in the
Philippines, Clark and the sprawling Subic Bay naval base.
   U.S. leases on both bases expire in 1991, and the attempted coup
seriously complicates efforts to renegotiate those leases. For the
time being, lease talks have been put on hold.
</TEXT>
