<DOCNO> AP891207-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India     12-07 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Visits Sikh Temple in Campaign to End Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DEL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister V.P. Singh visited
Sikhism's holiest shrine, the Golden Temple, on Thursday in a major
initiative by his government to end the lingering secessionist
campaign by Sikh militants.
   It was the first visit by a prime minister to the Golden Temple
in more than five years, since shortly after a bloody army raid
that led to the assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi.
   ``Too much bloodshed has taken place,'' the Hindu prime minister
told about 20,000 Sikhs inside the 14th century shrine. ``The time
has come to win the hearts of the people.''
   In New Delhi, a judge formally dropped charges against four
Sikhs accused of participating in the Oct. 31, 1984, assassination
of Mrs. Gandhi.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot and killed by two Sikh bodyguards angered
by the army attack she ordered on the Golden Temple in June 1984 to
drive out Sikh militants using it as a base.
   One assassin was shot and killed by security men. The other was
convicted along with an accomplice and both were hanged in January.
   Conspiracy charges were later filed against four other Sikhs.
Last week, the government said it would withdraw the charges in a
conciliatory move toward the Sikh community.
   ``One does wonder why the move was not made earlier,'' said
Judge Jaspal Singh, himself a Sikh, in ordering the charges dropped.
   All Sikhs and many Hindus use the name Singh, which means lion.
   Two of the Sikhs accused of conspiracy were elected to
Parliament in last month's general elections, in which V.P. Singh
and his National Front coalition prevented Rajiv Gandhi, Mrs.
Gandhi's son and successor, from returning to power.
   Singh was sworn in as prime minister Saturday and said solving
the Sikh dispute in the northern state of Punjab would be one of
his top priorities.
   On Wednesday, he made an effort to heal rifts between Hindus and
Moslems by by appointing a Moslem, Mufti Mohammad Sayeed, to the
key job of minister of home affairs. Religious riots this fall left
at least 300 people dead.
   His visit to the Golden Temple was noticeable for the almost
total lack of bodyguards, who surrounded Gandhi during his public
appearances. Singh traveled in an open jeep from Amritsar's Raja
Sansi airport to the temple after refusing to sit in a bulletproof
sedan.
   ``Your love to me is my security,'' the prime minister told the
gathering at the gold-domed temple. ``I have not come here for any
political or governmental purposes. I have come to perform prayers
in the holy shrine so that peace and normalcy can be restored.''
   Mrs. Gandhi was the last prime minister to visit the temple. She
came a week after the army raid.
   The Sikh secessionist campaign was launched by a small group of
radicals in 1982 and exacerbated by the raid on the Golden Temple
and by anti-Sikh riots in northern India after Mrs. Gandhi's
assassination.
   At least 1,200 people died in the army raid, and the temple
suffered heavy damage, turning even moderate Sikhs against the
government. At least 3,000 Sikhs were killed in ensuing riots.
   Sikhs, easily identifiable by the their long hair, flowing
beards and colorful turbans, form only 2 percent of India's 880
million people but are a majority in Punjab. Sikh militants say
their community is discriminated against by the Hindus, who make up
about 80 percent of the population.
   Officials say at least 7,500 people have been killed in Punjab
since the Sikh campaign began.
   Punjab Governor Sidhartha Shankar Ray resigned Thursday and was
replaced by Nirmal Kumar Mukarji, an appointee of the new
government. The state is ruled by the federal government in the
absence of an elected legislative assembly, and the governor is the
top administrator.
</TEXT>
