<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Legislators-Insurance     12-07 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Legislators-Insurance,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taxpayers Pay Insurance for Lawmakers Considering Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A safe driving record and living in a
low-crime area are two ways to get lower auto insurance rates, but
being elected to the Legislature might be more effective.
   Pennsylvania and California are the only two states that
reimburse legislators for the lease and insurance on their cars.
   A vote on a compromise insurance reform bill is expected next
week in the Pennsylvania Legislature, where the Senate in June
voted down a proposal that would have cut rates by about 25 percent.
   Philadelphia's rates are among the highest in the nation, fueled
in part, The Philadelphia Inquirer said, by legislation that was
drafted by lobbyists for the insurance industry and trial lawyers,
who benefit from personal-injury lawsuits.
   Two state senators are not reimbursed for car insurance. One
doesn't have a driver's license or car and the other is Sen. James
C. Greenwood. All 48 other senators have the taxpayers cover most
of their insurance premiums.
   ``I think to the extent that every time my insurance goes up I
feel the pain too _ that makes me like the people I represent,''
Greenwood said.
   Sen. Chakka Fattah, who paid $184 to insure his 1989 Lincoln
Continental last year, said it is unfair to say that legislators
don't care about the insurance issue because their car insurance is
paid by the state.
   ``That's just like saying because we have jobs we wouldn't be
concerned about unemployment,'' Fattah said.
   State Insurance Commissioner Constance B. Foster said the
state's reimbursement policy could make it more difficult for
legislators to adopt reform legislation.
   ``If a person is isolated from the problem, it's very easy to
minimize it _ even if they have teen-age sons and daughters,'' she
said. Foster was one of the key proponents of the insurance-reform
bill defeated by the Senate in June.
   Foster has the use of a state-owned and -insured 1989 Buick
Century.
   State records show that many Pennsylvania lawmakers lease
late-model Cadillacs, Lincolns and other luxury cars. The insurance
on those cars runs from several hundred dollars a year for rural
legislators to thousands for Philadelphia lawmakers.
   Under House rules, representatives can be reimbursed for up to
100 percent for their car insurance. Senators can be reimbursed up
to 95 percent.
   Many legislators said that such a benefit is normal in business
and that it helps them perform their jobs better. They also
disputed that the practice insulates them from the high cost of
insurance because they still have to pay for insurance on personal
and family cars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
