<DOCNO> AP891207-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Corruption     12-07 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Corruption,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scandal Figure Vows to Fight Extradition, Says Fair Trial Unlikely</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jailed East German official accused of
embezzling will fight extradition back to the Communist country,
saying the growing turmoil makes a fair trial unlikely, his lawyer
said Thursday.
   Alexander Schalck-Golodkowski fled the country after prosecutors
disclosed he was operating a weapons ring selling arms to countries
in South America, Africa and the Middle East.
   The growing scandal already has led to one suicide and the
arrest of Schalck-Golodkowski's deputy for allegedly taking $110
million in West German marks out of East Germany.
   Such allegations are particularly embarrassing for East Germany,
which for years has claimed that it needs more Western currency to
support its economy.
   Schalck-Golodkowski had supervised the various government-owned
businesses that brought in the badly needed Western money.
   He disappeared while on an official visit to West Germany on
Saturday, quickly becoming the target of an international manhunt
that added even more damaging publicity to the deeply troubled
nation.
   East Germany's Christian Democrats, a small party that recently
broke with the Communists, said the allegations made the country
look like a ``banana republic.''
   Schalck-Golodkowski turned himself in to West Berlin authorities
Wednesday night and immediately promised to repay $31 million to
East Germany from Swiss bank accounts. That is only a small part of
what East Germany's official news media claim he embezzled.
   In an interview with a West Berlin TV station, the former
official's lawyer, Peter Danckert, said his client would resist
being returned to East Germany for trial.
   Danckert said that ``the uncertainty that we have seen
everywhere in East Berlin'' made a fair trial unlikely. The
national frenzy aimed at punishing past corruption has led Lutheran
Church officials to warn that calls for ``revenge against the
guilty'' were sparking widespread fears.
   Danckert said Schalck-Golodkowski would appeal to the West
German Supreme Court if necessary to avoid an extradition.
   On Thursday, West Berlin prosecutor Dietrich Schultz said
Schalck-Golodkowski would stay in jail indefinitely and that the
former East German official ``feels that he is not guilty.''
   The West Berlin prosecutor added that an extradition to East
Germany is still possible based on the Communist nation's arrest
warrant for embezzlement. The charge carries a maximum of 10 years
in prison.
   However, Schultz said his office had not turned over anyone to
East Germany for prosecution in 20 years and that it was possible
he would be set free.
   Schultz said that Schalck-Golodkowski could be tried on the
allegations in West Germany, if the East Germans can prove he
committed the crimes.
   On Wednesday, the official East German news agency ADN reported
the suicide of an official caught two days earlier trying to leave
a government building with two suitcases stuffed with East German
and West German money. ADN did not give his name, but said he was
connected to the Schalck-Golodkowski case.
   Manfred Seidel, who served as Schalck-Golodkowski's deputy, was
arrested on suspicion of having smuggled $110 million in West
Germank marks out of the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
