<FIRST>r a PM-PearlHarbor 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 12-07 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pearl Harbor, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0548,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceremonies Commemorate Pearl Harbor Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with detail from ceremonies. Picks
up penultimate graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEARL HARBOR, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thousand people gathered at two
sites today to remember the ``day of infamy'' that killed more than
2,000 servicemen and brought the United States into World War II.
   Ceremonies on the 48th anniversary of the Dec. 7, 1941, Japanese
attack on Pearl Harbor included a moment of silence and a 21-gun
salute.
   Simultaneous ceremonies were held by the U.S. Navy aboard the
aboard the USS Arizona Memorial, where about 100 guests attended,
and onshore at the Arizona Memorial Visitors Center.
   The shore ceremony, open to the public and sponsored by the
National Park Service, which runs the center, attracted about 900
people.
   Adm. Huntington Hardisty, commander of U.S. forces in the
Pacific, spoke at the Navy ceremony, alluding to the new peace
initiatives between the East and West blocs.
   ``As the opportunity arises to reduce tensions and the potential
for open conflict, we should seize it and support it,'' he said.
But he said Americans also ``must continue to speak out'' against
perceived threats to the nation's security.
   The speaker at the public ceremony was retired Rear Adm. Victor
Dybdal, who was a gunnery officer aboard the USS Helm during the
attack.
   In all, 19 ships were sunk or damaged and some 2,300 men died on
the day President Franklin Roosevelt said would ``live in infamy.''
The sunken Arizona is the final resting place for 1,102 Navy men
and Marines.
   The memorial spans the hull of the Ariozona battleship, which
still flies the U.S. flag. It is the only Navy ship not in
commission that is allowed to do so.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
