<DOCNO> AP891207-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Rocket     12-07 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Rocket,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims Long-Range Missiles, Rocket With Satellite Capability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq claimed Thursday it has test-fired
two long-range missiles and successfully launched a rocket able to
carry satellites into space, developments that could affect the
Middle East's military balance.
   Hussein Kamel, minister of industry and military
industrialization, said the three-stage rocket was launched Tuesday
from the Al-Anbar space research center 50 miles west of Baghdad.
   He also claimed in a statement broadcast by state-run Baghdad
Radio that Iraq has test-fired two surface-to-surface missiles with
a range of 1,240 miles.
   That is enough to reach Cairo to the west, Athens and Istanbul
to the northwest, all of Iran to the east, and the southern Soviet
Union to the north.
   Iraq's other main foes, Israel and Syria, are already within
range of missiles reported in Iraq's armory.
   If the Iraqi claims are true, the developments will heighten
Soviet and U.S. fears of a new arms race in the Middle East.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said he had heard
reports Iraq had developed intercontinental ballistic missile but
knew nothing about their validity.
   Kamel gave no details of the surface-to-surface missiles and did
not say when the test-firings occurred.
   The heaviest missile the Iraqis are believed to have developed
is the al-Hussain, with a range of about 560 miles.
   There was no independent confirmation of Tuesday's reported
rocket launch, but Iraqi TV showed what it said was footage of it.
   Kamel said the rocket weighed 48 tons, bigger than anything the
Iraqis were believed to possess.
   The U.S. Polaris nuclear missile weighs only 13 tons.
   ``It's a big leap,'' said Hans-Heino Kopietz, a Middle East
analyst with London's International Institute for Strategic
Studies. ``The Iraqis are known to have been working on some big
projects and we must assume this was one of them.''
   ``What we must anticipate now, if this report proves to be
correct, is how Iraq's neighbors will react.''
   Israeli officials refused comment and there was no immediate
reaction from other Middle East capitals.
   Kamel said the rocket will be used to launch a satellite for
scientific research at an unspecified date.
   He said the launch was the first stage of an Iraqi space
research program and called it ``the springboard for further
achievements in space technology.''
   But it also would enable Baghdad to spy on Israel and Iraq's
main rivals in the region, Syria and Iran.
   Iraq fought an eight-year war with Iran that was halted by a
cease-fire last year. Syria, Iraq's archrival in the Arab world,
was allied with Iran during the war.
   Iraq is the only Arab country to claim the capability of
launching satellites. Israel is the only Middle East country known
to have satellite capability.
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein has been driving to develop an
aerospace industry for some time and has spent billions of dollars
on missile development.
   The most ambitious part of the program was development of a
two-stage ballistic missile with Egypt and Argentina based on
Argentina's Condor missile.
   Intelligence sources have said Iraq is negotiating with Brazil's
space agency and the French to help it acquire a surveillance
satellite.
   Israel launched the Ofek-1 satellite Sept. 19, 1988. It said
Ofek-1 was designed for scientific research, but Arab governments
fear it will be used as a spy satellite.
   Israel has said it is working on an Ofek-2 satellite. The
official Soviet news agency Tass reported the Israelis launched a
ballistic missile Sept. 14.
   The Israelis denied it, but Western intelligence believes the
reported firing could have been an abortive effort to launch Ofek-2.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
