<DOCNO> AP891207-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     12-07 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Militias Battle in West Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite militias fought in Moslem
west Beirut on Thursday during a general strike to protest alleged
attempts by Michel Aoun, the rebellious Christian general, to
partition Lebanon.
   Police said no casualty reports were available on the battle
between the the pro-Iranian Hezbollah and Amal, a more moderate
militia supported by Syria.
   ``Luckily this clash broke out on a day of general strike, which
decreases casualties among civilians,'' said a police spokesman,
whose name was withheld in keeping with regulations.
   Amal and Hezbollah fighters started shooting at midday in the
densely populated Basta and Khandaq al-Ghamiq districts of the
Moslem sector, which is patrolled by Syrian soldiers, the spokesman
reported.
   He said tension was ``gradually spreading'' despite efforts by
the Syrians to contain the trouble. The Syrian command sent
hundreds of its soldiers to districts bordering Basta and Khandaq
al-Ghamiq.
   Automatic weapons fire and the thud of exploding
rocket-propelled grenades could be heard across west Beirut, and
radio stations interrupted regular programming with reports on the
violence.
   The police spokesman said the confrontation ``could spread
quickly.''
   Fighting broke out in Beirut two days after Hezbollah drove Amal
from the western part of the Syrian-occupied Bekaa Valley in east
Beirut, destroying the five major Amal bases in Sohmor, Yohmor and
Mashgara villages.
   Police gave casualties in the Bekaa confrontation as 17
combatants killed _ 16 from Amal and one from Hezbollah _ and 42
wounded.
   The two factions have fought since May 1987 for supremacy among
the 1.2 million Shiites, Lebanon's largest sect. Police say 552
people have been killed and 1,532 wounded.
   Leaders of the National Front alliance of pro-Syrian leftist and
Moslem groups called the strike in Moslem areas to ``denounce
attempts to partition the nation.''
   President Elias Hrawi, a Christian like Aoun, presided over a
meeting of his government at an army barracks in Syrian-policed
east Lebanon, and issued a statement saying ``several decisions
were adopted regarding ways of ending the partition scheme.'' No
details were given.
   The government urged ``all concerned to join the unifying policy
of the legal authority to abort the partition scheme.''
   Moderate Christian leaders have joined Moslems in supporting
Hrawi, who was elected by Parliament on Nov. 23 with a mandate to
implement a peace agreement designed to end the 14-year-old civil
war.
   Aoun rejected Hrawi's election and opposes the peace accord
because it does not include a timetable for withdrawal of Syria's
40,000 troops from Lebanon. He commands 20,000 Christian troops
from a bunker beneath the presidential palace in the Christian
suburb of Baabda, and refuses to leave.
   Syria has ringed the 310-square-mile Christian enclave east and
north of Beirut with tanks, artillery and thousands of soldiers.
Hrawi has given mediators two weeks to convince Aoun to leave the
palace peacefully.
</TEXT>
