<HEAD>Officer Lozano Guilty On Both Counts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Lozano showed...', to UPDATE with Lozano statement.
Picks up 4th graf, `Prosecutors say...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MHH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury today found a Hispanic police officer guilty
of manslaughter in the deaths of two black men that led to three
days of inner-city rioting.
   Miami officer William Lozano, 31, was charged with two counts of
manslaughter in the Jan. 16 deaths Clement Lloyd,
23, and his passenger, Allan Blanchard, 24. The two counts carry a
total maximum sentence of 45 years.
   Lozof motorcyclist ano showed no emotion as the verdicts were read
and the
jurors were polled. Later, he issued a statement promising to
appeal and saying: ``I was not given a fair trial from the
beginning. There was a lot of evidence denied and quashed.''
   Prosecutors say Lozano fired unnecessarily as Lloyd's motorcycle
fled a squad car after a traffic violation. Lloyd died of gunshot
wounds while Blanchard died of injuries suffered in the resulting
crash.
   Lozano said he fired in self-defense when the motorcyclist tried
to run him down.
   The January riot left one man dead and 11 others wounded with
gunshots. Thirteen buildings were set afire, others were looted,
and 372 persons were arrested.
   Announcement of the verdic the verdict.''
   The sequestered jury began deliberations Wednesday after seven
weeks of testimony and hearings. They worked for about six hours
Wednesday and reconvened this morning, deliberating for an
additional 1{ hours before notifing the judge they were finished.
   Circuit Judge Joseph Farina did not formally endorse the verdict
today, but defense attorney Ray Black said that was just a
technicality. The judge ordered the parties to return Jan. 24, but
did not indicate whether sentencing would take place at that time.
Lozano remained free on $10,000 bond.
   He faces up to 30 years in the death of Lloyd, where the charge
was manslaughter using a firearm, and 15 years in the death of
Blanchard, where the charge was manslaughter not using a firearm.
   Lozano's wife left the court in tears.
   Officials had prepared for violence if the Colombian-born Lozano
had been acquitted, but also stressed their hopes for calm in the
hours before the verdict was announced.
   ``We're really concerned about the media coverage and
implications that this is something that would be almost expected
from a community,'' Mayor Xavier Suarez said today on ``CBS This
Morning.''
   ``I think the community is ready to accept the verdict. All the
leaders have called for tranquility and serenity in all the
communities in our city. I'm very pleased to see that approach
being taken.''
   The Dade County Community Relations Board called a last-minute
conference with social workers before they were sent out speak with
residents, said assistant director Lloyd Major.
   Forty-five police cars had formed a perimeter around Overtown,
Liberty City and black sections of Coconut Grove, and officers have
been issued riot equipment as a precautionary measure.
   ``We don't want to have storm troopers out there and have 400
policemen running around the city,'' police spokesman David Rivero
said Wednesday. ``We have just our normal patrols out there in the
city right now, but as soon as anything starts, we are going to go
in and arrest people.''
   Anderson, who is black, on Wednesday walked the streets of
Overtown, the neighborhood where the shooting occurred.
   ``Will we have justice this time?'' one resident asked the chief.
   ``I think so,'' Anderson replied, patting the man on the
shoulder.
   The rumors of a verdict had grown so strong Wednesday afternoon
that downtown workers reportedly left their jobs early, and Dade
County's Chief Circuit Judge Gerald Wetherington went on the air to
assure the public that the jury had reached no decision.
</TEXT>
