<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Legislation     12-07 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Legislation,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Bill Expanding Federal Damage Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislation Thursday
giving the attorney general the authority to settle claims of up to
$50,000 for injuries or damage caused by FBI agents executing their
duties.
   The measure amends a 1936 statute that had limited such damage
payments to $500.
   It also expands the settlement authority to cover other federal
law enforcement agencies, including the Drug Enforcement
Administration, the Immigration and Naturalization Service, the
U.S. Marshals Service and the Bureau of Prisons.
   The expanded settlement authority is intended to cover incidents
ranging from broken walls and doors to personal injury or deaths
resulting from properly executed law enforcement activities by the
FBI and other federal agencies.
   If negligence were involved, the victims already had a right to
sue the government for much larger damages than $500 under the
Federal Tort Claims Act.
   Bush also signed legislation allowing disabled Vietnam veterans
to receive Agent Orange settlement payments without jeopardizing
their eligibility for other federal disability or welfare aid.
   That measure excludes the Agent Orange payments from
consideration of the veterans' assets for means-tested federal
programs.
   Veterans who suffered health problems linked to the herbicide
sprayed as a defoliant during the Vietnam War can receive up to
$12,800 from a $180 million Agent Orange settlement fund.
   Bush signed a raft of other measures before departing the White
House on a two-day trip to Houston, Denver and Des Moines.
   Among them were:
   _A new four-year authorization for ACTION, the 25-year-old
domestic version of the Peace Corps. It includes a $15 increase in
the $75-a-month stipend for the 2,600 volunteers, who have not a
raise since 1976. The stipend will also go from $90 to $95 in
fiscal 1991. It also boosts the hourly stipend for foster
grandparents to $2.35 from $2.20.
   _Authorization levels in 1990 of $1.2 billion for the U.S.
Customs Service, $39 million for the International Trade Commission
and $21 million for the U.S. Trade Representative.
   _Allowing the Department of Agriculture to donate to charities
or public agencies confiscated meat and poultry, so long as the
products are wholesome and unadulterated, such as meat seized as
mislabeled.
   _Revising the terms under which the National Consumer
Cooperative Bank must begin repaying $184 million in loans from the
Treasury at the end of next year.
   _Designation of 1990 as the ``International Year of Bible
Reading,'' as proposed by Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., and 57 other
sponsors.
   _Creating a new post of president of the $20 million James
Madison Memorial Fellowship Foundation, which will award
fellowships of up to $12,000 a year to study the Constitution.
   _Appointment of Robert James Woolsey Jr., the U.S. ambassador to
conventional arms talks in Europe, and physics educator Homer
Alfred Neal to the board of regents of the Smithsonian Institution.
   _Permission for the U.S. Information Agency to distribute within
the United States a film, ``A Tribute to Mickey Leland,'' honoring
the efforts of the late Houston congressman to alleviate world
hunger. Leland was killed Aug. 7 in the crash of a mercy mission
flight in Ethiopia.
   _A green light for the Agriculture Department to pay food stamp
benefits in cash to families participating in the Minnesota Family
Investment Plan, a welfare experiment.
   _Renaming a post office on Hylan Boulevard in New York's Staten
Island as the Walter Edward Grady U.S. Post Office Building in
memory of a letter carrier who worked the same route in Staten
Island for 25 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
