<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0622 12-07 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Sandinistas Trying to Intimidate Election Foes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf pvs, Bolton also, to CORRECT spelling of Elliot.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior State Department official said
Thursday that Nicaragua's government has embarked on ``a clear
pattern of abuses'' designed to intimidate opposition political
activists and voters before February's national elections.
   John Bolton, assistant secretary of state for international
organization affairs, said the political opposition has grown to
represent a real threat to continued Sandinista power in Nicaragua,
and the government has responded with ``tactics designed to
discredit, confuse and intimidate the opposition and its
supporters.''
   Bolton also released a letter he had sent this week to Elliot
Richardson, the chief U.N. observer of Nicaragua's elections,
detailing more than a dozen attacks and threats aimed at opposition
political figures and their supporters in recent weeks.
   Bolton said the incidents would make it difficult for
Richardson, a former attorney general, to certify following the
Feb. 25 voting that the elections were free and fair in accordance
with a regional peace agreement signed by the leftist Sandinista
regime and its four Central American neighbors.
   In a speech at the State Department, Bolton said that Virgilio
Godoy, the vice presidential candidate of the opposition coalition
UNO, had been stopped by soldiers on Nov. 26 in the town of
Pantasma. When Godoy complained that two of his supporters had been
beaten and detained by the army, the soldiers responded that the
opposition had been throwing rocks and then threatened to fire on
the candidate and his party.
   That and other incidents ``present a clear pattern of abuses
designed to interfere with the open, free and fair electoral
process that the Sandinistas are pledged to uphold,'' Bolton said.
   Bolton, in a letter to Richardson, also cited the Nicaraguan
government's refusal to provide visas for a 20-member U.S.
congressional election observer group appointed by President Bush.
   In rejecting the visa requests last week, Nicaragua said the
United States could not claim objectivity because it was providing
$9 million in support to the electoral process to enhance UNO's
chances and was continuing to funnel support to the anti-Sandinista
Contra rebels, many of whom have re-infiltrated into Nicaragua.
   Bolton dismissed those arguments, noting that ``humanitarian''
aid to the rebels is permitted in the regional peace accord and
that Nicaraguan law permits outside financial aid to political
parties.
</TEXT>
