<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1639EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HumanRightsKillings     12-07 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Human Rights Killings,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>68 Human Rights Monitors Killed in Last Year, Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-eight human rights monitors were killed
worldwide in the last year, double the number in the previous 12
months, an international human rights monitoring organization said
Thursday.
   Human Rights Watch said 63 of the killings were in countries
usually considered to be democratic, but added in its annual report
that ``the danger in democratic countries ... is, of course, not an
argument in favor of dictatorships of the right or of the left.''
   The organization said it had little or no information on
persecutions of human rights monitors in Albania, Iran, Iraq, North
Korea, Romania or Saudi Arabia because it is virtually impossible
for citizens in those countries to monitor government activities.
   Nevertheless, the report said, ``the dangers that attend efforts
to monitor and defend human rights in some `democracies' should
give pause to those who have celebrated the democratic tide that
has swept across the world in the 1980s.''
   ``At least in a number of Latin American and East Asian
countries, the advent of electoral democracy has not meant great
advances in respect for human rights.''
   ``It is when a certain degree of openness prevails but when the
rule of law has not been established that the perils are
greatest,'' the organization said.
   In Colombia, where the group said a history of human rights
violations has been exacerbated by the violence associated with the
drug trade, 24 human rights monitors were killed, more than in any
other country.
   Brazil was second with 14 and ``many of the cases reflect the
intense struggle over land distribution in rural areas,'' Human
Rights Watch said.
   The 345-page report discussed 1,200 cases of persecution of
human rights monitors in 72 countries, including arrest,
imprisonment and torture of people who gather and disseminate
information on their own governments' human rights abuses.
   Aryeh Neier, executive director of Human Rights Watch, said
Czechoslovakia, where a new reformist government has come to power,
was second only to South Africa in the total number of cases. But
he said many of those listed had been released about two weeks
before the report was issued.
   ``Not all the people we care about in Czechoslovakia have yet
been released, so there is a way to go,'' Neier added.
   South Africa takes up 36 pages in the report and Czechoslovakia
23.
   The report devoted only six pages to China, but said some of the
thousands arrested after the June 3-4 disturbances in Tiananmen
Square were known to have been signers of statements and petitions
on human rights issues.
   In addition to the 68 killings, 10 more human rights monitors
``disappeared'' after being taken into custody, the organization
said.
   Human Rights Watch is made up of five regional committees:
Africa Watch, Americas Watch, Asia Watch, Helsinki Watch and Middle
East Watch. It is headquartered in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
