<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--BloodDisorder     12-07 0125</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Blood Disorder,0127</SECOND>
<HEAD>Now 730 Cases of Rare Blood Disorder, CDC Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reported cases of a rare blood disorder linked to
the nutritional supplement L-tryptophan have risen to 730, federal
officials said Thursday.
   The painful disorder, known as eosinophilia-myalgia syndrome,
has been reported in 48 states, the Centers for Disease Control
said. Earlier this week, the case count stood at 720.
   The CDC has reported a link between the syndrome and
L-tryptophan, an amino acid taken in pill form to treat
sleeplessness, depression and other ailments. The Food and Drug
Administration has issued a nationwide recall of L-tryptophan
tablets, capsules and caplets.
   One death has been linked to the substance, and three others are
being investigated.
</TEXT>
