<HEAD>Panama Establishes Trade Ties With Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's
government announced Thursday that Panama has established
commercial ties with the Soviet Union, under an agreement the two
countries signed earlier this year.
   Carlos Jimenez has been named Panama's trade representative in
Moscow, and the Soviet Embassy in Costa Rica will handle Soviet
relations with Panama for the time being, the announcement said.
   Noriega, chief of the Defense Forces and Panama's de facto
ruler, is wanted by U.S. authorities under indictments rendered by
federal grand juries in Florida in 1988 on charges of drug
trafficking and money laundering.
   The United States has imposed economic sanctions against Panama
and has been applying diplomatic pressure to oust Noriega, but so
far he has refused to budge.
