<HEAD>Authorities Arrest Two Suspected Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIEL, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police captured two suspected leftist
terrorists Thursday, but authorities declined to say whether the
arrests were connected to the bomb murder one week ago of top
banker Alfred Herrhausen.
   Authorities declined to provide any details except to confirm
that the two suspects were arrested in Husum, near this port city
on the Baltic coast.
   ``Because of the investigation, we can't say anything,'' said
Rolf Hannich, a spokesman for the federal prosecutor's office in
Karlsruhe.
   An officer at the Kiel police headquarters said the suspects
were a man and a woman. He said two police helicopters were
involved in the capture.
   Herrhausen, the powerful chairman of Deutsche Bank, was killed
one week ago when his armored car was blown up by a bomb in Bad
Homburg, near Frankfurt.
   The leftist Red Army Faction claimed responsibility for the
attack.
   Police launched a massive hunt for the suspects and offered a
reward of up to $2.2 million. Police have named three suspects in
Herrhausen's murder.
