<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1607EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;LRules     12-07 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Rules,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stricter Standards Take Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Keating Money, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strict new financial standards effective
Thursday will force more than a third of the nation's savings
institutions to shrink or shut down if they can't raise new capital.
   Only 1,800 of 2,900 S&amp;Ls have enough capital to satisfy the
requirement, prompting industry analysts to nickname the deadline
``Pearl Harbor Day'' because it coincides with the 48th anniversary
of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor.
   ``It's a good analogy, except in one respect,'' said economist
Robert Litan of the Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank.
``This wasn't a sneak attack. (S&amp;Ls) should have known this was
coming a long time ago.''
   The new rules were required under S&amp;L bailout legislation
enacted Aug. 9 and are considered the cornerstone reform of the
bill. The Office of Thrift Supervision published them Nov. 6.
   Advocates of forcing S&amp;L owners to back their lending with more
of their own money say the measure will encourage institutions to
avoid risky investments that could run up big losses for the
government deposit insurance fund.
   Of the 1,100 institutions falling short of the standard, about
300 are already insolvent and due to be transferred to the
Resolution Trust Corp. for liquidation.
   Of the 800 remaining, about 270 likely will be able to shrink or
raise capital on their own and about 230 likely won't be able to do
it before mandatory growth restrictions take effect on Jan. 1,
1991, M. Danny Wall, director of the thrift office, said Thursday.
   ``Then 300 in the middle are candidates for the matchmaker
program, blind dates, arranged marriages, however you want to put
it,'' Wall told the Association of Government Accountants Thursday
in a reference to a thrift office program aimed at matching weak
S&amp;Ls with merger partners.
   Private analysts, however, are skeptical about the prospects for
capital-deficient institutions.
   ``There are very good reasons to question whether the guys in
the middle will survive, certainly in their present form,'' Litan
said. ```The most likely strategy will be shrinkage because they
will not be successful in attracting new capital. There's a pall
hanging over the entire thrift industry, which makes investors
nervous.''
   Anticipating the rules, S&amp;Ls have been shrinking, shedding a
record $15.2 billion in assets in September and $13.3 billion in
August, according to the latest report available.
   Litan and another economist, Paul Getman of the Wefa Group in
Bala Cynwyd, Pa., said another provision in the thrift bill
requiring S&amp;Ls to concentrate 70 percent of their assets on housing
loans, up from 60 percent, is discouraging investors and virtually
forcing the shrinkage.
   ``Congress is saying to thrifts, `Put all your eggs in one
basket,' and that basket is looking real shaky,'' Getman said,
noting weakening real estate markets in the Northeast on top of
already soft markets in the Southwest.
   ``This is setting up the industry for what will be a knockout
punch in the early 1990s,'' he said, predicting that the Southeast
will be the next region with real estate problems.
   ``The right analogy to draw for these 800 thrifts is they are
like prisoners on death row. They have another 15 years to live,''
Getman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
