<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1940EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Lenin     12-07 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Lenin,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Monument Demonstrations Cannot Be Tolerated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Solidarity-led government said
Thursday it won't tolerate more demonstrations at monument to Lenin
where anti-Soviet protesters trying to destroy the statue have
twice clashed with police.
   Protesters chanting ``Soviets go home!'' hurled paint, gasoline
and explosives at the monument and fueled the fire with park
benches in a demonstration that lasted until midnight Wednesday.
   Police used water cannon and tear gas to disperse the
demonstrators after they marched to a militia headquarters, pelted
officers with stones and tossed Molotov cocktails, the official PAP
news agency reported.
   Twenty people were injured _ 13 of them police, PAP said. Damage
was estimated at $6,000, including a jewelry store looted after its
windows were smashed.
   Another demonstration turned violent Nov. 29 at the statue to
the founder of the Soviet state that dominates a square in the
Krakow suburb of Nowa Huta, built in the 1950s as a model socialist
industrial city.
   ``The problem of the location of the monument should be decided
by inhabitants of this district of Krakow in legal forums,'' the
government statement said.
   ``Vandalism and hooliganism are something else. Such activities
cannot be tolerated,'' it continued. ``The forces of order, acting
in accordance with the law, will be forced to take firmer steps in
order to prevent such dangerous excesses.''
   The youthful demonstrators, gathered by a radical group known as
Movement for an Alternative Society, have been an embarrassment for
the government of Prime Minister Taduesz Mazowiecki, formed of
former opposition forces who now must maintain relations with the
Soviet Union.
   The police action Nov. 29 was apparently the first large-scale
use of force against demonstrators since Solidarity took over the
government in August.
   The Solidarity committee for the southern Poland region has
adopted a resolution asking local authorities to remove the Lenin
monument to prevent further disturbances, PAP reported Thursday.
   ``Our resolution is not dictated by political reasons but by
concern over security and order in the city,'' it said, according
to PAP.
   ``If a decision manifesting the will of society is not made
immediately, stability will be threatened and district and
municipal authorities will be to blame,'' it said.
   Not freely elected, the people's councils that form local
governments have yet not been subject to the reform sweeping
through the central government and are still dominated by communist
party members.
   Stanislaw Suchonski, a member of the Krakow council, told PAP
two possible solutions were being considered: ``Either to prevent
such further events or, having heard the opinion of Nowa Huta
inhabitants, to move the monument to a different place.''
   Edward Nowak, a Solidarity parliament deputy serving as a
mediator in the monument dispute, said Thursday that only removal
of the statue can end the demonstrations, PAP reported.
</TEXT>
