<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru a0651 12-07 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0651,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buying More Subsidized U.S. Wheat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf pvs, The sale, to CORRECT that wheat sale was
the second this year.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought 410,000 metric
tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices for delivery in 1989-90,
the seventh year of a long-term grain supply agreement, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   F. Paul Dickerson, general sales manager for the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service, said shipments are scheduled in
January and February.
   The wheat was sold under the department's Export Enhancement
Program, or EEP, which provides subsidies to exporters selling U.S.
commodities to designated foreign markets.
   Dickerson said only 14,200 tons of wheat remain in the Soviet
Union's current EEP allocation of 1.5 million tons announced May 2.
   It was the second U.S. wheat sale since the seventh year of the
long-term grain agreement began Oct. 1, although more than 10.3
million tons of corn have been sold for 1989-90 delivery, along
with soybeans and soybean meal. A sale of 215,000 tons was reported
on Monday.
   The pact runs through Dec. 31, 1990, and a new agreement is
currently being negotiated.
   In 1988-89, the sixth year of the current agreement, the Soviet
Union bought about 5.4 million tons of wheat and more than 16.3
million tons of corn, plus soybeans, soybean meal and grain
sorghums.
   A metric ton is 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of
wheat. The 410,000 tons are equal to more than 15 million bushels
worth around $57 million at recent U.S. farm prices.
   Dickerson reported the subsidies at an average of $16.81 per
ton, or about 46 cents per bushel.
   The EEP arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and
other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced
prices to meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free
government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or
subsidies.
   Dickerson said the wheat was sold by Alfred C. Toepfer
International Inc., 150,000 tons; Louis Dreyfus Corp., 135,000;
Cargill Inc., 50,000; Continental Grain Co., 25,000; J. Aron &amp; Co.,
25,000; and Mitsubishi International Corp., 25,000.
   Since EEP began in 1985, more than $2.6 billion in subsidies
have been paid to exporters to ship a variety of commodities to
overseas customers. As of Nov. 30, sales totaled 87.2 million tons
of grain, including 64.4 million tons of wheat.
   The Soviet Union, the largest EEP beneficiary, has bought more
than 17.5 million tons of wheat. China is second at 13.2 million
tons of wheat, plus 185 head of cattle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AileyTribute     12-07 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ailey Tribute,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Season-Opener Turns Into Tribute For Alvin Ailey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opening night of the Alvin Ailey American Dance
Theater's season became a tribute in words and dance to the founder
of the troupe.
   The program was changed to include only dances choreographed by
Ailey and ended with his early masterpiece, ``Revelations.'' The
evening concluded with dancers, former dancers and crew members
embracing on stage and piling flowers under a photograph of Ailey
in his dancing years.
   Ailey died Friday of a blood disorder. He was 58.
   Carmen De Lavallade, who danced with Ailey, said during
Wednesday's program that Ailey's dream may have started in high
school, or before.
   ``I have been privileged to watch that dream grow from a tiny
seed of a company at the 92nd Street Y to this wonderful,
incredible company you see here tonight,'' she said.
   ``For the Y, he composed a dance about a man who fell in love
with the moon and decided to catch it. Alvin was the man and I was
the moon. After I was carried around through the air and out, a
silver sliver of a moon slid down a wire from my side to the stage
to his. He caught the moon. That's what he caught _ his dream.''
   Ailey started his troupe with seven members in 1958, dedicating
it to the preservation and enrichment of the American modern dance
heritage and the uniqueness of black cultural expression. Today the
troupe numbers 28, many of them graduates of the Alvin Ailey
American Dance Center.
   First as a dancer, than as a choreographer, Ailey was known for
his jazz-oriented modern dance innovations that combined black and
contemporary American cultural themes including jazz, blues,
gospel, folk heroes and politics.
   Harold Levine, chairman of the dance company's board, said the
board will ``continue the great legacy of Alvin Ailey. We will
build on his 31 years of creativity and see that his dreams are
realized.
   ``Generations to come will be thrilled and inspired by the Alvin
Ailey American Dance Theater.''
   George Faison, a former Ailey dancer, now a choreographer, spoke
after Marilyn Banks danced to ``My Soul Is a Witness for My Lord.''
   He said, ``We have seen Alvin Ailey's glorification of the Lord
and we have all been witnesses of Alvin Ailey's human spirit.''
   The evening began with Roberta Flack singing ``Always.''
``Revelations,'' the audience's favorite Ailey creation, was danced
in its entirety, to hymns sung by Brother John Sellers, other
soloists and a choir.
   The evening ended with the audience leaving as Sellers sang
``Rocka My Soul in the Bosom of Abraham.''
</TEXT>
