<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-DrugNeighborhood     12-07 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Drug Neighborhood,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Revisits Houston Park Where Neighbors Routed Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of children and grownups jammed a park
where George Bush once coached girls' softball to show the
president Thursday how they reclaimed the playground from drug
dealers.
   Bush said he was proud of the neighborhood for joining together
on what they call Independence Day, April 9, 1988, when 1,000
people went out to take Andrew Winzer Park back from drug dealers.
   ``Thank you not only for standing up to greet me, but also for
standing up for Houston every day,'' said Bush, noting that at one
time the park had been so clogged with drug dealers even Houston
police called it ``Crack In The Box.''
   Bands, drill teams, cheerleaders, choirs, school mascots _ even
a few children skipping school _ lined up hours before the
president arrived in northeast Houston to review the results of the
Acres Homes War on Drugs.
   Joining Bush for the 20-minute ceremony were federal drug czar
William Bennett, who visited the park in July, and Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady. The visit was part of the president's
two-day trip to Texas, Iowa and Colorado to spotlight anti-drug
efforts and boost Republican candidates.
   In his remarks, Bush referred jocularly to the time he coached
softball at the park during his congressional service in the 1960s.
   ``It was a great bunch of girls. They almost won state,'' said
Bush. ``In fact, I think I see our third baseman over there,'' he
said, drawing a laugh from the crowd.
   The festive atmosphere Thursday was in stark contrast to the
situation in the area two years ago, when drug dealers dominated
the neighborhood.
   ``It was sad,'' said John Phillips, a former high school
football coach. ``I used to drive by here at lunch. There would be
25 cars lined up there for four or five guys selling whatever you
wanted. Families just stopped coming here. People were afraid.''
   The neighbors banded together, got their children involved, and
started an aggressive neighborhood watch program that included
writing down license numbers and turning alleged drug dealers into
police.
   Bush drew applause when he quoted Erma Scales, president of the
Acres Homes War on Drugs, as saying, ``We need to teach our system
of values, parents ... need to spend more time with their kids and
... go back to being parents, not just being buddies,'' he said.
   Kenneth Scott, 34, came out Thursday with his 3-year-old
daughter, Keandra.
   ``It's nice and peaceful now, but it was a lot of drug dealers
and drug addicts here. It was just in turmoil. I couldn't bring my
kid out here. They would run out to every passing car and ask every
passing car to buy drugs.
   ``But now that's all changed. I love it here.''
   But police said the job is not finished.
   As crews worked Wednesday to ready the park for the president's
visit, undercover police officers made three arrests in an hour for
the sale of crack cocaine within a mile of the park.
</TEXT>
