<HEAD>Salvation Army Commander Puts Bellringers on Quotas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POCATELLO, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The local Salvation Army commander has
put his holiday bellringers on a $60 quota on daily donations in
their Christmas kettles, contending he's just practicing good
business.
   ``Our business practice requires that our costs should not
exceed 50 percent of what we bring in,'' Capt. Ron Gilden said in
justifying recent written warnings sent to two minimum-wage
bellringers.
   The wife of one disgruntled bellringer, who said her husband was
told he would lose his job if his collections did not pick up,
claimed Gilden's policy has prompted some bellringers to quit.
   Gilden acknowledged that one person quit, but others have had no
trouble meeting the quota. He said the complaining worker, who was
not identified, takes too many breaks, leaving his station
unattended.
   ``I've placed him at various sites and his collections are
always less than what was taken in the day before or the day after
he was at the site,'' Gilden said.
   Gliden said this year's Christmas drive is targeted to raise
$30,000, about 10 percent more than last year. The money is used
throughout the year.
