<FIRST>r a AM-PearlHarbor     12-07 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pearl Harbor,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceremonies Mark 48th Anniversary of Pearl Harbor Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON STATON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEARL HARBOR, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America should seize and support
opportunities to reduce international tensions, the commander of
U.S. forces in the Pacific said Thursday in commemorating the 48th
anniversary of the Pearl Harbor attack. ``But when we perceive a
threat against the interests and security of the nation, we must
continue to speak out, even if the tide of public opinion is
running the other way,'' said Adm. Huntington Hardisty during a
Navy ceremony aboard the USS Arizona Memorial.
   Hardisty noted that an 18-year-old sailor lost in the Dec. 7,
1941, attack by Japan would now be 66.
   That sailor would be pleased to see that the Pacific command is
waging peace, Hardisty told about 100 invited guests.
   ``He would be pleased to see that our nation's security posture
in the Pacific is in good shape,'' Hardisty said. ``But I also
think the sailor would sound a warning that peace requires strong,
credible forces, and constant vigilence.''
   A minute of silence was observed at 7:55 a.m., the time the air
raid began. The minute ended with a flyover by Hawaii Air National
Guard jets in the ``missing man'' formation.
   Representatives of veterans, civic and patriotic organizations
presented wreaths during the ceremony, which also included prayers
and a 21-gun salute.
   Among those attending were U.S. Reps. Daniel Akaka, D-Hawaii,
Martin Lancaster, D-N.C., Marvin Leath, D-Texas, and David O'B.
Martin, R-N.Y.; Hawaii Gov. John Waihee; and other Pacific military
commanders.
   About 900 people attended a public service held simultaneously
at the Arizona Memorial Visitor Center.
   Retired Rear Adm. Victor A. Dybdal, who was a gunnery officer
aboard the USS Helm at the time of the Pearl Harbor attack, was the
keynote speaker.
   He gave a personal account, paid tribute to those who died, and
said America must remain strong, even with recent developments in
Europe and the Soviet Union.
   ``We should support the movements toward democracy and freedom,
but remember that the huge military strength of the Soviet Union is
still there,'' he said.
   The National Park Service ceremony included prayers by the World
Federation Japan Religious Committee.
   Some Pearl Harbor survivors scattered across the country
attended commemorations without returning to Hawaii.
   In Harrisburg, Pa., for example, Gov. Robert P. Casey told about
50 Pearl Harbor survivors they were in ``the front line'' of the
fight for freedom that is taking place in eastern Europe.
   ``You stand for peace and freedom, the peace and freedom that we
all enjoy, that others strive for and that can never be taken for
granted. You are living reminders of where we have been, of our
goals and of our aspirations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
