<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Protest     12-07 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Protest,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Rally Against Communists, Secret Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,500 East Germans marched through the
city center late Thursday shouting slogans against the Communist
Party and the country's once-feared secret police.
   Hundreds of the demonstators blew shrill, ear-piercing whistles
and shouted for the secret police to stop meddling in citizens'
affairs.
   ``Imprison the Communists!'' the marchers demanded, referring to
disgraced former leaders accused of having misused their offices or
made off with state funds during four decades of Communist rule in
East Germany.
   The rally, which started at East Berlin's sprawling
Alexanderplatz, followed the broad Marx-Engels-Forum Boulevard and
passed city hall, included demonstrators who hoisted signs calling
for free elections next year.
   ``We Demand Quick Free Elections'' and ``The Communists Must Now
Pay for the Mistakes of Misery,'' placards read. ``We Have Had
Enough of Election Fraud.''
   Former Communist Party chief Egon Krenz was forced to resign
from his posts as party leader and president this week following
accusations that he allowed approval of falsified April election
results.
   Two demonstrators carried a sign showing a caricature of a man
shredding polling records.
   Another sign denounced Krenz and West German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, who has offered a plan for German reunification.
   ``We need neither Krenz nor Kohl _ we'll only feel well when we
govern ourselves,'' the sign read.
   There had been reports the demonstrators would march on the
secret police headquarters in East Berlin, but the demonstrators
never passed the building.
   About 200 demonstrators broke off from the main column at the
Communist Party headquarters, where they shouted ``Come Out, Come
Out, We Are Peaceful!''
   Police presence as the march wound through the city was
negligible.
   At one point, a policeman using the megaphone of a patrol car
shouted, ``Attention, attention, this is the people's police,
please use the sidewalks, you are disrupting traffic.''
   The marchers ignored the order, booing and jeering. The police
did nothing.
   People in a hotel along the route cheered on the marchers, who
waved back.
   At about the same time, about 30 demonstrators from West Berlin
pushed their way to the front of the column of marchers and shouted
anti-Nazi slogans.
   Part of the procession marched by the Dietrich-Bonhoeffer
building, where negotiations between the Communists, other
recognized political parties and opposition groups were under way.
   The marchers joined a chorus of calls there for free elections
and other democratic reforms in a Communist nation under siege by
its own people.
   About 90 minutes later, the marchers dispersed peacefully.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
