<FIRST>r a AM-PorkRoundup     12-07 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pork Roundup,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garbage-Eating Pigs Trapped, Sent to Slaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANFORD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wild pig population feeding on garbage
at the Seminole County landfill had multiplied to about 1,500, and
the county decided it was time to do something.
   Enter Daniel Godwin, 23-year-old professional trapper.
   He pays the county $52 apiece to round up the hogs and truck
them away to sell to a slaughter house.
   ``People think catching hogs is fun, but it's a job,'' Godwin
said Tuesday after several days of trapping and muscling squealing
hogs _ which weighed up to 350 pounds _ into a truck.
   Godwin arrived at the 1,200-acre landfill early Saturday with
three helpers and began their routine: Set traps by day, sleep in
their vehicles at night while the hogs get trapped, and the next
day haul the hogs to Myakka City, a three-hour drive.
   It's tough work, he said.
   ``They get mean. They ain't no pets, you know. They'll catch you
if you let them,'' Godwin said.
   Now landfill workers say they will miss the porkers.
   ``They have gotten used to seeing them run around out there. You
look at the little ones, they're kind of cute,'' said Fred
Blakeley, the county's solid waste manager. ``But, you've got to do
what you've got to do.''
</TEXT>
