<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--HurricaneTrees     12-07 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hurricane Trees,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan Residents Send Christmas Cheer to Hurricane Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLEGAN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo victims will be getting
1,000 Christmas trees and the trimmings to go with them.
   Organizers said the trees, relatively expensive in the South
because they must be shipped from colder climates, might be a
luxury beyond the means of many victims of the hurricane that swept
through South Carolina in September.
   Allegan County residents, tree growers and two companies teamed
up to send two truckloads of trees to Charleston, S.C., on Sunday.
   ``Allegan County, being such a big Christmas tree county, they
planned to raise money to buy trees to send,'' Mayor Craig van
Melle said.
   But tree growers donated the trees, and Frito Lay and L. Perrigo
Co. offered to handle the trucking. So residents provided
decorations.
   Marine Corps Reserve members will coordinate distribution in
Charleston.
