<FIRST>r w AM-LincolnS&amp;L 1stLd-Writethru a0648 12-07 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lincoln S&amp;L, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Ask Judge to Throw Out Keating Suit</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS 3 grafs on related Cranston development</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Keating Money Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators asked a judge Thursday to
dismiss a suit against them by the former owner of Lincoln Savings
and Loan Association, saying they can show Phoenix millionaire
Charles H. Keating Jr. was operating the thrift in violation of the
law.
   Deals that the hearing is focusing on are ``literally just the
tip of the iceberg,'' James P. Murphy, an attorney for the Treasury
Department's Office of Thrift Supervision, told U.S. District Court
Judge Stanley Sporkin.
   Under an arrangement approved by attorneys for both sides, a
sample of four deals _ two land transactions, a tax-sharing
arrangement between Lincoln and its holding company and a deal
involving stock _ will occupy the two days of hearings that began
Thursday.
   ``I assume you picked the worst ones,'' Sporkin, a former chief
enforcement officer for the Securities and Exchange Commission,
said to Murphy. The judge ordered the hearing on the government's
motion to dismiss Keating's suit in what regulators say will end up
as the costliest S&amp;L collapse in history.
   Last May, a month after regulators seized Keating's Irvine,
Calif., thrift, he filed the suit seeking to nullify the
government's action. Regulators contended the S&amp;L had lost between
$1 billion and $2.5 billion in federally insured deposits through
fraud, risky investments and sham real estate transactions.
   The government has summoned Keating to appear as a witness.
   The target of a federal grand jury investigation in Los Angeles,
Keating invoked his Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination and refused to answer questions in a subpoenaed
appearance last month before the House Banking Committee.
   In his suit, Keating and his attorneys allege that Lincoln was
being operated soundly, met federal capital requirements and was
making a profit, and that its takeover by the government was
``capricious and arbitrary.''
   Before hearing testimony, Sporkin denied efforts by Keating's
attorneys to quash as evidence four letters from one of Lincoln's
attorneys prior to the takeover last April 14.
   Charles M. Stern, a Los Angeles attorney representing Keating,
said allowing the government to use the letters would violate his
client's attorney-client privilege. ``We should not be forced to
have our own lawyers used against us,'' he said.
   However, attorneys for the thrift regulators said the letters
effectively became government property once the government seized
Lincoln.
   Sporkin granted Keating's request for government records dating
back to 1985 on tax-sharing agreements between hundreds of thrifts
around the country and their holding companies.
   A key element of the government's case is its contention that
Lincoln and its holding company, American Continental Corp. of
Phoenix, abused a tax-sharing agreement to effectively siphon off
nearly $95 million in federally insured deposits.
   Keating is chairman of American Continental, which filed for a
Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization one day before the government
placed Lincoln into conservatorship.
   Government regulators in 1986 had approved the tax-sharing
arrangement, under which American was supposed to collect taxes
from Lincoln and forward the money to the Internal Revenue Service.
   But Murphy said Lincoln and American Continental fraudulently
misused the accord to effectively allow the holding company to use
the tax collections as a no-interest loan from Lincoln.
   Federal thrift regulations prohibit savings and loan
institutions from lending money to their holding companies.
   In a related development, Sen. Alan Cranston's complaint about a
leak of information that the FBI was investigating a voter
registration project operated by his son, Kim, was referred to the
Justice Department's Office of Professional Responsiblity.
   FBI Director William S. Sessions told reporters he referred the
matter to the Justice Department's internal investigations office.
Cranston, D-Calif., is one of five senators who intervened on
Keating's behalf with federal regulators.
   The FBI is investigating whether whether Cranston and the other
senators violated any laws by taking campaign donations from
Keating and lobbying federal regulators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1752EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-ArmeniaQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0659 12-07 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armenia Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Year After Quake, Armenians Mourn the Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs `And the...' with one graf to CORRECT spelling
of first name of Stepanian; pickup graf 10 `The earthquake...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINAKAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bells tolled, thousands wept in the
graveyards and plaintive chants filled the streets Thursday as
Armenia marked the first anniversary of the earthquake that killed
25,000 of its people.
   In this mountain city, officials stopped the town clock forever
at 11:41, the minute disaster struck, and held a moment of silence.
   Only muffled sobs broke the stillness.
   ``If only it could all have been a dream, and we could wake up
and have everyone here again,'' Armenian poet Maro Marzarian told a
crowd of several hundred gathered to dedicate a memorial to
Leninakan's thousands of dead.
   In a snowy cemetery just outside of town, women sobbed at the
gravesites, some of them caressing photographs etched on the
tombstones and men stood stony eyed and silent. Many graves held
unidentified corpses, with markers reading only ``238, woman'' or
``453, child.''
   ``Your soul hurts so much you just can't express it,'' said
Lilia Stepanian, 25, whose brother, Zillik, and his family were
crushed to death in their Leninakan apartment.
   ``You remember that on this day, at this time, they were already
gone,'' she said. ``At this time one year ago I was standing by our
house, only it wasn't a house any more.
   She said Zillik's 3-year-old daughter could be heard crying from
the ruins of the house but rescuers could not get to her in time.
Stepanian's mother, Rima, said Zillik's wife had been due to give
birth to a second child three weeks later.
   ``And the people left alive have such a hard time,'' Lilia
Stepanian said. She and her mother moved to Armenian capital of
Yerevan until Leninakan housing could be built for them _ which
they don't expect any time soon.
   The earthquake measuring 6.9 on the Richter scale killed at
least 25,000 people, left 20,000 missing and destroyed the homes of
500,000 more.
   In the nearby village of Spitak, where the quake destroyed
virtually every house, residents dedicated a new church of
galvanized steel. Standing above a hillside crowded with graves, it
shone in the sun under Thursday's bright blue sky.
   Armenians stopped work Thursday to honor the dead, and Armenian
TV broadcast a program on earthquake damage and reconstruction.
   After the quake rocked Armenia with such devastating force, the
Soviet Union opened its borders to foreign assistance for the first
time, accepting the help of thousands of experts, including rescue
teams, doctors and construction specialists.
   More than a half-billion dollars in assistance poured into the
disaster area from overseas, altering the course of East-West
relations as generosity and mercy overcame years of Soviet
propaganda depicting Westerners as greedy and hate-filled.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov said Thursday that
foreign assistance as of mid-October totaled $586 million. The most
generous donors were Italy with $95 million; West Germany with
$84.5 million; the United States with $42 million; Britain with $38
million; Czechoslovakia with $34.5 million; East Germany with $30
million; and France with $28 million.
   On Thursday, the Vatican announced Pope John Paul II sent
$100,000 to Armenian Christians, saying he wanted to give ``a new
sign of his affection for those peoples and of his active
participation in the difficult test they have been subjected to.''
   Vatican officials gave the gift to Vasken I, the chief leader of
the Armenian Church, which broke from the Roman Catholic Church in
the 6th century but maintains good ties with the Holy See.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
