<FIRST>r w AM-MeatRecall     12-07 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meat Recall,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lunch Meat Recalled For Possible Food Poisoning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sumter, S.C., processor is voluntarily
recalling a single 240-pound shipment of luncheon meat distributed
to nearby stores because some of the product may be contaminated by
food poisoning bacteria, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Harvin Choice Meats Inc. sold the product _ ``Harvin Sliced
Luncheon Meat'' packed in 6-ounce vacuum packages _ exclusively to
grocery and convenience stores in a 20-mile radius of Sumter,
officials said.
   The possible contamination involves Listeria monocytogenes,
bacteria that can cause severe illness, said Lester M. Crawford,
head of the department's Food Safety and Inspection Service.
Consumers should return the packages where purchased. No other
product of the company is involved in the recall. k
   Crawford said no illnesses have been reported as a result of
eating the suspected product. Cartons containing the packages carry
the production code, 0318. And each carton and package bears a USDA
inspection seal with ``Est. 6592'' inside the seal.
   Food contaminated with the bacteria can cause listeriosis,
described as a rare but potentially serious disease, particularly
for those with weakend immune systems _ infants, the elderly and
the chronically ill.
   Symptoms are flu-like and include fever chills, headache,
backache and sometimes abdominal pain and diarrhea.
   Consumers with questions about the recall can phone the
toll-free USDA meat and poultry hotline at 1-800-535-4555 from 10
a.m. to 4 p.m. EST, Monday through Friday. Callers in Washington,
D.C., metropolitan area lshould call 447-3333.
</TEXT>
