<FIRST>r w AM-Skinner-Drugs     12-07 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinner-Drugs,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Secretary Promises `Reasonable' Approach To Drug Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
assured private transportation operators Thursday that his
department will be ``reasonable and understanding'' in enforcing
drug testing rules that take effect this month.
   ``You don't have to be worried during the implementation stage
that enforcers will show up at your doorstep with subpoenas,''
Skinner told an industry seminar on the new program.
   Drug testing programs, including random testing, will have to go
into effect for mariners and transit and aviation workers this
month. Testing for railroad workers starts in January and for
pipeline workers in April. A federal court injunction has stalled
random and some post-accident testing in the trucking industry.
   Companies with fewer than 50 employees will have another year to
begin testing programs. Twenty-two court challenges have been filed
against the program by various transportation groups, but Skinner
said it will take effect on schedule except where courts intervene.
   ``While we want the rules enforced and expect them to be
implemented, we understand it will be an evolutionary process,''
Skinner said. ``Rest assured, we will be reasonable and
understanding.''
   Skinner said safety-related jobs must be drug-free for the
nation's transportation systems to remain safe. The department
eventually expects about half of the nation's 4 million
transportation employees to be tested at least once a year both as
a means of detecting drug use and as a deterent.
   Skinner noted that 25,349 random drug tests conducted on
department employees resulted in only 141 positive tests, a rate of
about 0.5 percent. But he told reporters earlier this week that he
expects the tests to show an ``alarming amount of drug usage'' in
mass transit and other private transportation industries.
</TEXT>
