<FIRST>u a AM-RiotTrial-Preparations     12-07 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riot Trial-Preparations,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>City, Police Officials Confident But Wary After Verdict</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and community leaders expected little
violent reaction Thursday to the guilty verdicts against a police
officer in the killing of two black men, but police stayed on alert
in the ethnically tense city.
   Police had made extraordinary preparations in case an inocent
verdict in the trial of Hispanic officer William Lozano set off
violence in black neighborhoods. Instead, the verdict left
bitterness among some Hispanics.
   ``We'll maintain a high visibility tonight and possibly
downscale our activities tomorrow,'' Police Chief Perry Anderson
said.
   The police department put all 1,100 officers on call, bought 700
gas masks and arranged for two armored personnel carriers to be
available for riot duty.
   The city has been wracked by riots four times this decade, most
recently in January when Lozano's fatal shooting of a black
motorcyclist triggered three days of violence in the week before
Miami held the Super Bowl. The motorcyclist's passenger also died.
   Near the shooting site in the impoverished, mostly black
Overtown section, some 100 blacks went ahead with a march Thursday
despite the verdict. But they said the event was turned from a
protest to a celebration.
   ``The verdict means relief, but there's still an element in the
police department that thinks justice lies at the end of your
arm,'' said march organizer Michael Umoja Imani.
   ``Everyone has been following this from day one,'' said
participant Judy Wallace, 22, who lives in an apartment building
across the street from the shooting site. ``When the verdict was
announced, everyone was relieved and very happy.''
   Some marchers criticized police officials' decision to post
riot-ready units in black neighborhoods and ignore mostly Hispanic
areas.
   Among Hispanics, who outnumber Dade County blacks more than
2-to-1, the mood seemed mostly concerned but not hostile.
   ``Yes, there will be people in the Hispanic community that will
think it's unfair, but that has to be settled,'' said Tere Gavalda
of the Spanish-American League Against Discrimination. ``It's
unfortunate the case turned out to be a black against Hispanic
issue. We have to put that to rest.''
   Mayor Xavier Suarez said he received nearly a dozen telephone
calls from people angered by the verdict, but there was no
indication of violence.
   Suarez, who last summer was denounced by some fellow
Cuban-Americans for supporting a black woman over a Cuban for a
city commission seat, said there was no way of knowing if the
verdict would raise tensions between blacks and Hispanics.
   ``I don't think the Hispanic community is going to respond in
any monolithic way,'' Suarez said.
   Suarez, who took office in 1985 with a promise to improve
Miami's inner-city neighborhoods, hoped the verdict might ease some
of the alienation among blacks there who feel the justice system is
against them.
   ``There has been a succession of cases that led to outcomes that
have not been successful to the black community,'' Suarez said.
``This was at least a departure from a trend.''
   Community leaders who had been ready to go into the streets to
talk against violence said they would try to ease any ethnic
reactions by Hispanics.
   ``We definitely have not reached Utopia,'' said Willie Sims of
the Dade County Community Relations Board. ``We're not going to
drop everything. We were focusing on a not guilty verdict (and
black reaction) and now the emphasis shifts on the Hispanic group.''
   At Spanish-language radio station WQBA, caller were shocked and
angry, said Fernando Checa, a technical director. ``Mostly, they
feel the judgment was done for the black community,'' Checa said.
   Some police advocates predicted the verdict would harm efforts
to recruit for Miami's police force.
   ``I hope this won't discourage people from being police
officers, but that's my concern. Being a cop in Miami is tough
enough,'' said David Nevel, attorney for a police group that
supports stronger penalties for criminals and also president of
Miami Beach Fraternal Order of Police Associates.
</TEXT>
