<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-07 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winter Storm Covers Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Plains got a blast of winter Thursday as a storm left more
than a foot of snow in places, while a second winter storm warning
was posted for the mid-Atlantic states.
   Snowfall was heaviest in the West. Colorado snow cover included
17 inches at Rye, with 8 inches at Beulah, West Cliff and
Walsenburg. Story, Wyo., had 11 inches of snow and 5 inches fell at
Sheridan, Wyo.
   Roads over the Texas Panhandle were ice-covered Thursday
morning. At least three inches of snow fell on Amarillo, Texas, and
up to two inches of snow accumulated in parts of Nebraska.
   Mild temperatures melted much of the snow and turned it into
freezing rain. ``It's melting about as fast as it's falling,'' said
Bill Wyatt, a spokesman for the city of Woodward, Okla., which
received about 3 inches of snow.
   During the day snow fell over the southwestern third of North
Dakota, much of South Dakota, north-central through western
Nebraska, northeast Colorado, much of Kansas into southwest
Missouri, northern and western Oklahoma, the Texas Panhandle and
northwest Texas.
   In the East, a winter storm warning was posted for Friday over
the southern and western half of Virginia, northeast Tennessee,
southeast Kentucky and much of western North Carolina.
   Snow showers fell Thursday across central and western New York
state, northwest Pennsylvania and northeast Ohio. Snow extended
over upper Michigan and western lower Michigan.
   Rain reached across Arkansas, eastern Louisiana, Mississippi,
Alabama, northern Georgia and South Carolina.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included an inch at Jackson, Miss., .72 of an inch at Lafayette,
La., and .70 of an inch at McComb, Miss.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from zero
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 85 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.The
low temperature for the nation Thursday morning was 15 degrees
below zero at Warroad, Minn.
</TEXT>
