<FIRST>u i AM-Comoros     12-07 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comoros,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Use Tear Gas on Anti-Coup Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORONI, Comoro Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Presidential Guard used tear
gas and clubs to disperse about 1,000 students Thursday during the
largest protest yet against European mercenaries who seized control
of this island nation.
   Witnesses said several of the high-school students were beaten.
   The violence came as France cut off its $18 million in annual
aid to the Comoros, off the east coast of Africa. Diplomatic
sources said the assistance would not be resumed until the head of
the new ruling group, French mercenary Bob Denard, leaves the
island.
   South Africa, another large donor to this impoverished nation
with a population of about 430,000, took the same action Monday. It
also cut off support for the Presidential Guard.
   President Ahmed Abdallah Abderrahmane died Nov. 26 in an attack
blamed by diplomatic sources on Denard, commander of the 500-member
Presidential Guard. That force disarmed the regular army and now
controls the four-island archipelago between Mozambique and the
island of Madagascar.
   The students shouted ``The mercenaries must go!'' and ``Denard
is an assassin!'' as they marched from the French Embassy to the
beachfront Thursday morning.
   They were confronted there by members of the guard, which is led
by about 30 French and Belgian mercenaries.
   The guardsmen, supported by jeeps equipped with heavy machine
guns, drove through the capital in the biggest show of force since
Abdallah was killed. Denard has denied involvement in the
assassination, but sources said Thursday the two men had quarreled
recently over several issues, including funding of the Presidential
Guard.
   Many students dashed into the water when the guardsmen arrived,
and others fled through side streets. Most later regrouped at the
Ministry of the Interior in the city center, where dozens of
guardsmen launched tear-gas grenades and charged with clubs.
   Youths forced a suspected spy for the Presidential Guard from
his civilian car, then overturned the vehicle and burned it on one
of the main streets of Moroni, the capital.
   Witnesses said several students were clubbed or otherwise
beaten, but there was no official injury toll.
   Guardsmen patrolled working-class areas of the city throughout
the day, dispersing smaller gatherings with tear gas and clubs, the
witnesses said.
   Throughout the day, hundreds of young men jeered and shouted at
Guard vehicles as they sped through the capital and outlying
villages.
   ``The people have always opposed the mercenaries, but they were
silent until the president was killed,'' said Abdul Mohammed, a
Moroni resident. ``Now the people are angry and say the mercenaries
must leave.''
   Several photographers and reporters had their film and notebooks
seized as they covered the morning demonstration. Ten journalists
were later ordered to leave the islands by Thursday evening, and
five other journalists were told to remain in their hotel.
   The French Foreign Ministry said the suspended aid includes
direct assistance, as well as 150 technical and 13 military
advisers. The islands gained independence from France in 1975.
   Denard, 60, ousted and later returned Abdallah to the presidency
in coups during the 1970s. Although Denard held no official title,
he maintained strong influence in security and political matters.

</TEXT>
