<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1911EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia     12-07 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombia Descends into Political Chaos Following Terrorism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia descended into political chaos
Thursday under threats from drug traffickers of further terrorism,
leading one newspaper to demand cancellation of next year's
presidential elections.
   All 10 presidential candidates for party nomination should
withdraw, the influential El Espectador newspaper said in an
editorial.
   The capital's half-dozen dailies all ran banner headlines about
Wednesday's 1,100-pound dynamite bomb explosion that destroyed a
block of downtown Bogota, killing 52 people and wounding about
1,000.
   The blast outside federal investigative police headquarters came
one day after a government report blamed terrorists for the Nov. 27
explosion of a Colombian jet that killed all 107 people aboard.
   ``Drug Traffickers Turn Bogota into Beirut,'' said El Tiempo's
headline.
   El Tiempo and El Espectador said the situation was so grave
President Virgilio Barco should ask all parties to forget their
differences and form a common front against traffickers.
   El Espectador said the crisis extends beyond the traffickers'
terrorist campaign to encompass a political system on the verge of
collapse.
   Barco told the nation late Wednesday traffickers were
endangering the country's democracy, but would fail.
   ``We are fighting and will continue to fight. The war is against
all Colombia, against democracy,'' he said in a speech transmitted
by satellite from Tokyo, where he is on a state visit.
   Barco is cutting his visit short by one day and returning to
Colombia Friday night.
   In Tokyo on Thursday, the president promised to take swift,
stern action against cocaine cartels and the terrorists.
   U.S. House Speaker Thomas Foley cited the drug violence Thursday
in Washington when he said President Bush ``ought to think
carefully about a visit to Colombia under these circumstances.'' He
commented after meeting with Bush at the White House on the Malta
summit.
   White House advance teams have scouted Colombia's northern
coastal city of Cartagena as a possible site for the upcoming drug
summit Bush has agreed to attend with leaders of Colombia, Bolivia
and Peru.
   Meanwhile a bomb exploded Thursday on a road in Cartagena,
killing two policemen in a car, radio reports said. Pamphlets left
at the site, however, indicated the attack was the work of the
leftist guerrilla National Liberation Army.
   The immediate threat to this South American nation's stability
is traffickers' insistence that the people be allowed to vote on
the administration's extradition policy.
   The Extraditables, a group linked to the Medellin cocaine
cartel, took responsibility for the Wednesday bomb hours after the
devastating explosion. It earlier pledged in a communique to keep
up the terrorist campaign until the extradition referendum is
approved by Congress.
   Colombia's House of Representatives passed a bill Tuesday night
calling for such a referendum and the Senate is to vote on the
measure before its current session ends on Dec. 15.
   Congress has long been the butt of jokes by Colombians as being
corrupt and receiving payments from drug dealers.
   In an editorial headlined ``Faced with Crime, Terror and Moral
Corruption,'' El Espectador said the country's constitutional
system no longer exists because it has been so damaged by
traffickers' influence.
   Traffickers bombed El Espectador on Sept. 2 as part of a terror
campaign to try to pressure the government into ending extradition.
   Barco suggested in his speech that drug barons were intimidating
legislators into following their demands.
   ``It is unacceptable from every point of view that drug
traffickers are trying to subdue our legislators so that they make
a decision that will only bring more death and destruction,'' he
said.
   His administration has sent nine Colombian drug suspects to the
United States under a tough extradition policy, part of an
anti-narcotics war decreed last August after traffickers
assassinated a leading presidential candidate.
</TEXT>
