<FIRST>u a AM-TenureRuling     12-07 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tenure Ruling,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Rules Boston University Must Grant Woman Professor
Tenure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. appeals court has upheld a federal judge's
1987 ruling that Boston University must pay $215,000 in damages and
grant tenure to a female professor who sued the university for sex
discrimination.
   The case was believed to be the first time a woman suing under
the federal anti-discrimination law was reinstated with full tenure
by an appeals court.
   Julia Prewitt Brown, 41, was a member of BU's English Department
from 1974 until she was denied tenure in 1981. At one point,
university president John Silber termed the department ``a damn
matriarchy'' although only only six out of 20 members of the
department at the time were female, according to court testimony.
   In a 68-page decision, the 1st Circuit Court of Appeals
unanimously agreed with a jury verdict and subsequent judgment by
Judge Walter J. Skinner after a three-week trial in July 1987. The
ruling was issued Dec. 1 but Brown's attorney said she chose not to
publicize it until Thursday.
   BU spokesman Thomas Cashman said the university will ask the
court for a rehearing.
   ``Boston University does not discriminate against anyone,''
Cashman said in a prepared statement. ``This case involves issues
of academic freedom. We believe that it is wrong for courts to
substitute their opinions or the opinions of the jury for the
scholarly judgment of the university in determining who shall
teach.''
   BU's official reason for not granting tenure was Brown's alleged
``lack of academic excellence.'' But Brown was unanimously
recommended for tenure by her BU colleagues both inside and outside
the department, according to the appellate decision.
   ``I think it's going to be a real shot in the arm for women as
well as minorities,'' said Barbara Lee, an attorney on the faculty
at Rutgers University and the author of ``Academics in Court.''
   ``It's extremely difficult to win these cases,'' she said.
``Most times the judge accepts the universities' arguments.''
   The decision, written by Chief Judge Levin Campbell, touched on
remarks made by Silber in tenure reviews of other female faculty
members.
   According to the ruling, Silber told one female professor that a
person with her credentials would do well ``and anyway ... your
husband is a parachute, so why are you worried?''
   Campbell wrote that ``(Silber's) comments reflected a
patronizing attitude toward women.''
   Brown, who spent 10 years fighting her case, called the decision
``a victory for all of us.''
   ``I am only one among many women at Boston University and in the
academy at large who have been held to a higher standard than male
colleagues,'' she said in a prepared statement Thursday.
   Ann H. Franke, an attorney with the American Association of
University Professors who filed a friend-of-the-court brief in the
appellate court, said the ruling ``means there's a powerful remedy
through the courts now for sex discrimination.''
   Franke and Lee both said the appeals decision was the first to
their knowledge in which a professor's full tenure was reinstated
under the anti-discrimination law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
