<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;Ls-DebtSales     12-07 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Debt Sales,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixteen S&amp;Ls Allowed to Sell Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen savings and loans were permitted to
sell $3 billion in uninsured debt to their customers, the same
practice that cost many depositors at Lincoln Savings and Loan
Association their life savings, thrift regulators said Thursday.
   Despite the Lincoln debacle, the Office of Thrift Supervision
this year allowed seven S&amp;Ls to begin selling debt to retail
customers and another nine institutions to continue sales approved
earlier, according to a two-page summary released by the office.
   Such sales are attracting heavy scrutiny because some 22,000
investors, many of them elderly pensioners and widows, lost an
estimated $250 million by purchasing subordinated debt in American
Continental Corp., the parent company of the Irvine, Calif.-based
Lincoln, in 1987 and 1988.
   In sometimes tearful testimony, Lincoln customers told the House
Banking Committee last month they were misled into believing the
debt certificates were federally insured.
   The Lincoln debt was sold in the branch offices of the S&amp;L and
offered in amounts as small as $1,000, a feature that appealed to
unsophisticated investors.
   The thrift office said the approved debt sales, in addition to
Lincoln, totaled $3.017 billion. In some instances denominations as
low as $1,000 were offered.
   Thrift office rules required that S&amp;Ls offering debt meet
capital standards at the time of the approval. However, according
to Sheshunoff Information Services of Austin, Texas, two of the 16
S&amp;Ls as of June 30 had no tangible capital. They are Security First
Federal Savings and Loan Assocation of Daytona, Beach, Fla., and
Centrust Savings Bank, Miami.
   Two others fall short of new standards effective Thursday which
require S&amp;Ls to hold capital amounting to 1.5 percent of their
assets, the firm said. They are Cenlar Federal Savings Bank,
Princeton, N.J., and TCF Bank Savings, Minneapolis.
   Centrust was allowed to offer $50 million in notes in minimum
denominations of $2,000, while Cenlar was permitted $20 million in
$1,000 denominations. TCF and Security first sold their debt in
minimums of $10,000.
   However, not all of the debt sales are suspect. Alex Sheshunoff,
the owner of the information firm, said the $1 billion offering in
$100,000 minimums by World Savings and Loan Association, Oakland,
Calif., considered one of the best S&amp;Ls in the nation, is probably
an excellent investment.
   Sheshunoff said S&amp;Ls should be permitted to offer their debt
without going through an underwriter, but he said they should
screen out unsophisticated buyers by offering the debt in large
denominations and should clearly disclose that the debt is
uninsured.
   The release of the information by the thrift office, which
followed a story on the subject in Thursday editions of The
Washington Post, drew criticism of the sales from a House Banking
subcommittee chairman.
   Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the financial
institutions panel, called on Wall in a letter to revoke his
agency's permission for the debt sales.
   ``There is no need for me to recite the damage that this kind of
sale caused to thousands of purchasers in the Lincoln ...
situation,'' Annunzio wrote.
   Wall, in a talk to the Association of Government Accountants,
said his agency was obligated to approve the debt sales under
existing laws and rules.
   ``There was no regulation that had been promulgated to prohibit
it. So we could not have disapproved it other than for good and
other kinds of economic reasons,'' he said.
   The thrift agency is planning within weeks to adopt regulations
sharply limiting future subordinated debt sales by S&amp;Ls because
``we've learned from our experiences,'' Wall said.
   Bills restricting the sale of S&amp;L debt have been introduced in
the House by Reps. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., and Thomas McMillen,
D-Md.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
