<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Bauman     12-07 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bauman,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Karl Bauman, Longtime AP Washington Newsman, Dies at 87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karl R. Bauman, a longtime newsman with The
Associated Press whom President Johnson once said was ``as much a
part of the White House as the press room itself,'' died Thursday
at the age of 87.
   Bauman died of complications from cancer at Holy Cross Hospital,
where he had been hospitalized since Nov. 27, said a nephew, Joseph
J. Madigan of Chicago.
   Bauman, a 38-year AP employee, worked for 32 years in the news
service's Washington, D.C., bureau, covering major federal trials
and the U.S. Supreme Court before moving on to the White House,
where he covered the Kennedy administration and Johnson's 1964
campaign.
   LBJ sent Bauman a letter on his retirement, noting his
three-decade career in the nation's capital.
   ``Since President Roosevelt you have been as much a part of the
White House as the press office itself,'' Johnson wrote on June 27,
1967.
   ``You have outlasted four presidents, and I thought you would
outlast me. The White House seemed a little less colorful today
because of your absence.''
   Bauman's departure from the press corps was marked with ``the
biggest retirement party of anyone in Washington I ever knew in the
news business,'' recalled Frank Cormier, a former AP White House
correspondent who joined Bauman at the White House in 1962.
   Cormier said Bauman ``could be very crusty. He had a
curmudgeonly side on occasion.''
   During a trip with President Kennedy, Cormier recalled, Bauman
found the White House staff had registered him at a hotel as
``Mouk'' Bauman _ Mean Old Uncle Karl.
   ``He was known as Mouk for years,'' Cormier said.
   Bauman was raised in northeastern Kansas and entered the news
business in 1921, when he went to work for The Daily Times of
Leavenworth, Kan., Madigan said.
   In 1923, he moved on to the St. Louis News Press, joining the AP
in St. Louis in 1929. From 1930-35, he worked for the news service
in both St. Louis and the Missouri capital of Jefferson City.
   He was transfered to Washington in May 1935 and worked there
until his retirement, when he and his wife, Frances Lauf of Taos,
Mo., settled in nearby Arlington, Va. Mrs. Bauman died in 1984.
   Bauman moved to a retirement home in Palos Park, Ill., last May
to be near his sister, Elizabeth Ann Bauman, a nun at St. Mary's
College at Notre Dame, Ind., and his nieces and nephews, said
Madigan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
