<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia-Havel     12-07 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Havel,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Havel Says He Would Become President if Crisis Required</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vaclav Havel, who only a month ago
was reviled by the official press, said Thursday he would accept
the presidency if necessary to help resolve the country's crisis.
   Appearing at a crowded news conference in the Laterna Magika
theater, the playwright seemed tired but elated by his speedy
transfer from the dramatic to the political stage.
   Thousands of supporters of Czechoslovakia's Civic Forum
opposition movement, which Havel heads, are now sporting
Hungarian-made buttons declaring ``Havel for President.''
   With characteristic humor, Havel told reporters, ``I don't wear
that badge.'' He said he had nothing to do with its manufacture
because ``my connections do not extend as far as Hungary.''
   A shy man, he has repeatedly declined offers to seek political
office. But, when asked Thursday if he would accept the presidency
if offered, he said he would do so under certain circumstances.
   ``I have repeatedly said that my occupation is a writer and that
I have no political ambitions. I don't feel myself to be a
professional politician but have always put the public interest
ahead of my own.
   ``And, if God help us, the situation should develop in such a
way that the only service I could render my country would be to do
this, then, of course, I would do it,'' Havel said.
   He stressed that there is no organized group promoting his
candidacy.
   ``The more democratic and more normal the condition in our
country, the less my role will be,'' the mustachioed writer said.
   Havel has avoided interviews the past two hectic weeks during a
mass pro-democracy movement that forced the Communists to
relinquish their 41-year monopoly on power, ousted most hard-line
leaders and paved the way for a coalition government that could
restore democracy.
   With characteristic caution Thursday, he ducked a question about
when he began to believe that the opposition could triumph.
   ``We have a saying in Czech, `You should not praise the day
before the evening,''' Havel said, smiling.
   As a founding member of Charter 77, eastern Europe's oldest
human rights movement, Havel has spent most of the last 13 years
under police surveillance and served 4{ years in jail for his
outspoken criticism of what he calls ``totalitarian Communism.''
   Asked what he had learned from those years, Havel echoed the
creed of one of his best-known essays chronicling the moral
deformations of Stalinism, ``Living In Truth.''
   ``I have learned that when a person behaves in accordance with
his conscience, and when he tries to speak the truth, behave as a
citizen even when citizenship as such is degraded. It may not lead
to anything _ but it might,'' he said quietly.
</TEXT>
