<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     12-07 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Oppose Angolan Peace Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebels Thursday objected to a
summit of eight African leaders scheduled to discuss plans for
ending the southwest African nation's 14-year civil war.
   ``The mediation of endless and inconclusive summits by the group
of eight has already proved disastrous to the process of peace in
Angola,'' the rebels said in a statement distributed in Lisbon. It
was signed by rebel leader Jonas Savimbi, leader of the U.S.-backed
UNITA rebels.
   Angola's state news agency, ANGOP, reported Tuesday that the
government would present its latest cease-fire plan to leaders from
Congo, Gabon, Mozambique, Sao Tome e Principe, Zaire, Zambia and
Zimbabwe later this month at their fifth summit on Angolan peace
prospects.
   Angolan government sources said Thursday the summit would be
held in the Angolan capital of Luanda on Dec. 27, the Portuguese
news agency Lusa reported from Luanda.
   Earlier reports said the leaders might meet Dec. 21 in the
Gabonese capital of Libreville.
   Savimbi's statement from the rebels' southeast Angolan bush
stronghold of Jamba called for direct rebel negotations with the
government. It also restated the guerrillas' confidence in Zairean
President Mobutu Sese Seko as the only mediator in the conflict.
   Mobutu mediated a cease-fire agreement between Savimbi and
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos June 22 in Gbadolite,
Zaire, but the truce collapsed soon afterward. Later talks ended in
deadlock with renewed fighting.
   UNITA _ the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
_ has been fighting to share power with the Cuban-supported
government in Luanda since Angola gained independence from Portugal
in 1975.
