<FIRST>r a AM-US-JapanPoll     12-07 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan Poll,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll: Japanese Have Harsh Views of United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half of the Japanese don't have much
or any admiration for the United States, its economic success or
its people, according to a Business Week poll released Thursday.
   A majority of 1,000 Japanese polled last month also said the
United States is unfairly pressuring Japan on trade issues, but
they added that their country should loosen barriers to trade.
   Forty-two percent of those polled said one of America's biggest
economic problems is that the nation has too many minorities, while
35 percent cited a lazy work force.
   The poll was conducted in Japan Nov. 10-14 by Louis Harris &amp;
Associates for Business Week. The magazine said the results should
be accurate to within 4 percentage points.
   Among the findings, 57 percent said America is unfairly trying
to pressure Japan on trade issues, but 62 percent said Japan could
be more flexible on trade.
   A total of 54 percent said they believe the United States has
had trouble selling products in Japan because its products are not
as good as those made in Japan, 55 percent said Japan was imposing
unfair trade barriers and 52 percent said U.S. companies aren't
trying hard enough.
   Forty-three percent of those polled said they believe Japan
eventually will take America's place as the world's leading
economic and political power.
   A total of 54 percent said they have little or no admiration for
America as a nation, 56 percent have little or no admiration for
its economic success and 63 percent for its people.
</TEXT>
