<FIRST>r a AM-TielessTeacher     12-07 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tieless Teacher,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Reinstates Tieless Teacher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POINT PLEASANT, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A math teacher who was fired for
refusing to wear a necktie will return to the classroom next week,
school officials said Thursday.
   ``I'll be wearing a good pair of jeans, a cotton denim shirt and
my boots,'' Bill Webb said Thursday.
   For most of his 20 years in teaching, Webb has worn jeans and a
work shirt. The school board instituted a new dress code during the
1988-89 school year calling for a tie and dress pants.
   Webb refused, saying he had signed his contract before the dress
code was in effect. He also contended that the school board
shouldn't be able to regulate a teacher's choice of clothes.
   Webb was suspended several times and then dismissed in December
of 1988 for refusing to conform.
   The reinstatement came after the state Supreme Court said Webb
had to be given his job back while the Mason County Board of
Education appeals a lower-court decision that overturned the firing.
   Rick Powell, Mason County superintendent of schools, said the
reinstatement won't halt the board's appeal to the state Supreme
Court.
   ``One way or another, whether Mr. Webb prevails or we prevail
... my goal is to get the system back to normalcy,'' Powell said.
``And the system is about educating young people.''
   Webb predicts it will take some time to get back into the swing
of things.
   ``I think it will be a little awkward both for me and the
students,'' he said. ``They've had a different teacher this year.
... It's unfortunate that they've had to go this type of thing for
two years in a row.''
   The board is to meet with Webb on Friday, Powell said. Attorneys
for the board and Webb are to discuss back pay, which Webb contends
he is owed for his time off the job.
   Since his firing, Webb has been farming at his home in
Gallipolis, Ohio, and running an auto body shop. Gallipolis is just
across the Ohio River from Point Pleasant, about 50 miles northwest
of Charleston.
</TEXT>
