<FIRST>u a AM-EarthquakeDinner 1stLd-Writethru a0649 12-07 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earthquake Dinner, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Thanks for Community Aid, Armenians Make Dinner for Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with dinner, quotes. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, `The church ..., ADDS 4 grafs to UPDATE with activities elsewhere.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Armenia Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's Armenian community gave an ancient
tradition a modern twist, laying on a special meal for the homeless
to honor victims of the Soviet republic's killer earthquake one
year ago Thursday.
   ``We wanted to show our gratitude for all those who helped us,''
said Margaret Zahigian, member of St. Gregory of Narek Armenian
Apostolic Church. She referred to those in the community who
contributed time and aid to victims of the Dec. 7, 1988, disaster.
   ``Feeding the poor is a good place to start,'' she said after
helping serve the first of two meals at the City Mission. She
estimated nearly 200 people would sit down to a turkey dinner.
   ``Forty days after a death, we have a requiem service and a
dinner in honor of the deceased,'' said Florence Karoghlanian,
church council president. Although the dinner is not 40 days after
the deaths _ the biblical time period between the Resurrection of
Jesus and the Ascension _ the meal stems from that tradition, she
said.
   The church in suburban Richmond Heights collected $134,000 in
cash for victims of the quake, which killed more than 25,000
people. The donations will be used as seed money to build a city in
Armenia, church treasurer Harold Zahigian said.
   ``The Cleveland community was very generous in making
contributions, not only money but also clothing and medicine,''
said Matthew J. Hatchadorian, local president of the Armenian
General Benevolent Union. He estimated that there are 1,000 people
of Armenian descent in the area.
   ``We wanted to express our appreciation to all the people in
this community for their response to a horrible tragedy,'' he said.
   Church members prepared turkey, candied sweet potatoes,
Armenian-style rice pilaf, green beans and pumpkin pie for
Thursday's meal. A dozen members volunteered to serve the dinners
to 130 men at the City Mission downtown.
   ``They're expressing their appreciation to the community and
we're thankful,'' said Tony Lewis, who supervises the homeless men
who work at the mission and receive shelter in return.
   The church sent 26 teen-agers to Armenia over the summer to
build a prefabricated house, the first new residence in the
quake-damaged community of Stephanovan.
   The church also was host to five children who were treated at
hospitals in Cleveland and Akron for injuries suffered in the
earthquake. All have returned home, Mrs. Karoghlanian said.
   The quake's one-year anniversary was also commemorated in other
regions of the country. In the Los Angeles area, several Armenian
groups Thursday held candlelight vigils, memorial church services
and fund-raising walk-a-thons for the victims of the earthquake.
   The observances will extend through the weekend with a blood
drive and memorial services at the several Armenian Apostolic
churches throughout the Southern California.
   In New York, the Armenian Philharmonic Orchestra closed its
first ever tour of the United States with a special benefit concert
Thursday night at Carnegie Hall in New York City.
   The orchestra, along with American pianist Andre Watts, has
already appeared in Boston and Washington. Proceeds of the tour
will be used for specific projects in the earthquake zones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
