<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Contras     12-07 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Contras,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Assembly Votes 91-2 Against U.S. Funding of Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly voted overwhelmingly
in favor of a resolution Thursday that calls on the United States
to stop financing Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   The assembly passed by a 91-2 margin the Nicaraguan-sponsored
resolution against the U.S-backed Contras, who were to be disbanded
this week under a regional peace plan. It asked Washington to obey
a 1986 judgment by the International Court of Justice ordering it
to halt support for the Contras.
   Only the United States and Israel voted against the measure. The
41 abstentions included most of the U.S. allies in Europe and the
Caribbean. Honduras, where an estimated 11,000 Contra forces are
headquartered in jungle camps along the Nicaraguan border, also
abstained.
   In a separate action, the General Assembly decided by consensus
to approve spending up to $40.8 million over six months to send a
650-member border patrol force to Central America.
   The peacekeeping force is intended to deter cross-border raids
by the Contras or any other insurgents and to cut off
weapons-smuggling.
   The United States accuses Nicaragua and Cuba of shipping weapons
to leftist rebels battling El Salvador's government, and the
Contras have acknowledged they are selling weapons to the
Salvadoran rebels.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering told the assembly that the
World Court's ruling was one-sided, ignoring U.S. support for the
Central American peace process.
   The United States had said it not believe the world court, based
in the Netherlands and serving as the U.N.'s judicial arm, could
rule on national security issues.
   The court's 15 judges ruled Washington had disobeyed
international law by interfering in Nicaragua's internal affairs
with its support for the Contras. The court has no power to enforce
its judgments, however.
   U.S. military aid to the Contras ended two years ago, Pickering
said, and only non-lethal aid is sent to the rebels.
   By contrast, he said, ``Nicaragua's military assistance to the
El Salvador insurgents has again been revealed in the recent plane
crash at El Transito in El Salvador, which revealed weapons
destined for the El Salvador guerrillas.''
   Two dozen Soviet-made SAM-7 anti-aircraft missile launchers were
found in the wreckage of that light plane, which crashed Nov. 25.
   Nicaraguan Ambassador Alejandro Serrano Caldera said U.S.
``aggression'' against Nicaragua continues today. He said U.S.
non-lethal aid to the Contras is actually logistical help in the
war.
   In addition, Serrano Caldera said U.S. meddling in Nicaragua's
internal affairs continued when the U.S. Congress appropriated $9
million for the opposition in national elections set for Feb. 25.
   Under an agreement signed by Central American presidents, the
Contras were to be dismantled voluntarily by last Tuesday. However,
neither the rebels nor the United States were part of that accord.
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua has proposed extending the
deadline to the end of the month. The region's presidents are
meeting again Sunday in Costa Rica to take up the issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
