<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 2138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Congress     12-07 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Congress,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Says Defense Budget Cuts `Inevitable'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The speaker of the House, Thomas S. Foley,
said Thursday that improvements in U.S.-Soviet relations make cuts
in the Pentagon's budget ``inevitable.''
   Foley's comment came as he and other congressional leaders
praised President Bush's actions at last weekend's meeting with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev in Malta.
   Bush briefed lawmakers on his talks with Gorbachev and on events
in Eastern Europe and the Philippines.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., said afterward that Bush ``probably
heard the most praise he'll hear from Democrats in a long time.
We're all proud of the fact he did a very good job in Malta.''
   Foley called Bush's actions at Malta ``wise.''
   As for the defense budget, the speaker said he does not
anticipate a ``huge, immediate ... peace dividend'' from the
lessening of East-West tensions. ``But, undoubtedly, the defense
budget is going to go in a downward course relative to the gross
national product and relative to government expenditure,'' said
Foley.
   Congress expects that and ``I think it's inevitable,'' Foley
said.
   ``The United States for 40 years has faced a strategic situation
in which the Soviet Union ... posed a threat, as we saw it, to the
security of western Europe and to U.S. interests around the
world,'' he said. ``That hasn't totally disappeared, but it has
(been) so largely altered by events of recent months and the last
couple of years that to maintain a defense posture ... based on
that would be foolish.''
   The Associated Press learned Thursday that Bush has decided to
seek a $292 billion defense budget next year. This year's Pentagon
budget is $286 million; a $6 billion increase would not keep pace
with inflation.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said, ``The president did an excellent job in
converting what was just goiing to be a meeting, a rendezvous, into
an actual summit with substantive discussions.''
   Leahy said Bush and Gorbachev should ``meet every year, with or
without an agenda,'' just as the president meets annually in an
economic summit with leaders of the seven major industrialized
democracies.
</TEXT>
