<FIRST>r a AM-ContinentalAd 1stLd-Writethru a0677 12-07 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Continental Ad, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Chief Apologizes To Idaho Governor, Mayor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to CORRECT title of Lorenzo to chairman,
sted president, of Continental Airlines; CLARIFIES total number of passengers
killed; picks up 5th graf: `Mayor Dirk ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Continental Airlines has
written to Gov. Cecil Andrus and Boise's mayor apologizing for an
advertisement run in Great Britain belittling the city.
   The Houston-based airlines also has changed its advertising
policy to prevent a similar incident, Continental officials said
Tuesday.
   Marc Johnson, Andrus' press secretary, said an apology was the
least Continental Chairman Frank Lorenzo could do. Lorenzo also is
chairman of Texas Air Corp., Continental's parent company.
   The governor took exception to a jibe in the ads that asked how
often someone would need to go to Boise. Andrus called it a ``cheap
shot'' in light of the 1987 Denver crash of a Boise-bound
Continental flight that killed 28 people, 14 of them Idahoans.
   Mayor Dirk Kempthorne said he appreciated the apology but still
wanted follow-up advertisements in Great Britain aimed at boosting
Boise's stock as a destination for air travelers.
   The advertisement, since yanked from publication, pitched
2-for-1 tickets from London to Denver and other destinations. The
ad admitted there are a few places in the United States that
Continental does not serve, but asked, ``But be honest, how often
do you really need to go to Boise, Idaho?''
   Continental pulled out of Boise and seven other Western U.S.
cities in September 1988, saying it would focus on more profitable
routes.
   Lorenzo wrote in the letter to Andrus and Kempthorne, sent by
fax machine late Monday, that ``my view of advertising does not
include poking fun at any city.
   ``Furthermore, a copywriter could not have chosen a more
unsuitable target for his weak pun. I was appalled to see the
effect of these coinciding mistakes,'' Lorenzo wrote.
   ``Both Idaho and Continental share many unhappy memories brought
on by the Denver accident. I want to continue to do everything
possible to mend the wounds that resulted from the tragedy,'' he
wrote.
   Continental has maintained that the ad prepared by a British
advertising firm was conceived by people who had no knowledge of
the Denver crash and was not reviewed at corporate headquarters
until after publication.
   Art Kent, Continental vice president of corporate communication,
said a new policy has been adopted.
   ``All advertising done overseas has to be approved and cleared
before publication here at the Houston headquarters,'' Kent said.
</TEXT>
