<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-SantaClaus Adv08   12-07 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Santa Claus, Adv 08,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, Dec. 8, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Yes, Says Jack Perkins, There Is a Santa Claus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is a solemn moment in the show. Hodding
Carter III, a top official during the Carter administration, is
puzzled why the Pentagon, the State Department and the White House
won't comment on Santa Claus.
   When he was in the State Department, he adds, ``not once did I
hear somebody say, or did I read anything, suggesting that Santa
Claus did not exist.''
   But then, the show, anchored and narrated by former NBC
correspondent Jack Perkins, is about Santa Claus, a syndicated
one-hour special called ``There Really Is a Santa Claus.''
   Airing on various nights this month on stations in 123 cities,
it's a light-hearted ``documentary'' about various facets of the
man in the red suit and white whiskers, all of it an effort to
prove he exists.
   Celebrities like Edward James Olmos, Mickey Mantle and Loretta
Lynn are participants, as are men of learning, one of whom believes
in the possibility of flying reindeer.
   Even police in Fairbanks, Alaska, get in the act. One,
responding to a call, asks a homeowner, deadpan: ``He actually was
on your roof? In a sleigh?''
   And, of course, kids periodically get a say in all this.
   The men of learning include a Dartmouth University professor,
John Rassias, a Santa Claus expert, and a Santa's helper, Dr. Carl
Anderson, a psychologist who wrote his University of Texas
dissertation on Santa Claus.
   The reason he did that, Anderson explains, is that ``I was
struck by the intensity of the children's belief and the joy and
excitement that they experienced when they visited Santa.''
   Conceived and produced by David Lowe Jr., a former ``60
Minutes'' staffer, the show examines the matter of Santa from all
angles _ his origins, his flying reindeer, how he knows if you've
been naughty or nice, and so forth.
   In a section dealing with how Christmas toys get to less
fortunate kids, it also slips in a gentle plug for the Marine Corps
Reserve's Toys for Tots campaign, founded 42 years ago by retired
reserve Col. Williams Hendricks.
   The show has its faults, mainly that it gets a bit too cutesy
now and then. But on balance it's a pretty good holiday special,
particularly for tykes, who may find its findings reassuring in a
world that sometimes seems populated by Grinches with souls of
garlic.
   As Anderson, quoting a little boy, puts it: ``That there's
somebody somewhere in this cruel world who loves children and cares
about them _ that's what Santa's all about.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BAH, HUMBUG TO ADS _ Home Box Office subscribers facing a
barrage of Yuletide appeals from urchins to buy those toys the
little ones see advertised on TV might have them watch a half-hour
HBO special, ``Buy Me That!''
   Produced by Consumer Reports, and airing Monday and four other
nights, it takes an on-the-mark look at those deftly edited ads
that exaggerate what you actually get when you buy toys that the
ads suggest fly or talk. It also gives the gimlet eye to ads in
which the announcer furtively mumbles ``parts sold separately,'' or
worse, ``some assembly required.''
   The show does a very mean thing. It gets kids to try some toys
advertised on TV. That some emerge disillusioned is indicated by
one girl who, having grappled with a some-assembly-required toy,
says, ``You have to be some kind of architect or professional
engineer to know how to put these things together ... it's really
confusing.''
   COSBY SALUTES AILEY _ Bill Cosby will headline a Christmas Eve
NBC special saluting dance pioneer Alvin Ailey, who died last
Friday of a blood disorder. The one-hour show will include some of
Ailey's most memorable choreographic creations, performed by the
dance company he founded.

</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday PMs, Dec. 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv08   12-07 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 08,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Dec. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Catch 22' Trap Claimed in School Bible Club Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Some call it a ``Catch-22'' snare, zapped if they do, and zapped
if they don't. That's the predicament claimed for some students at
Westside High School in Omaha, Neb., who want an off-hours Bible
club.
   The problem has surfaced at numerous public schools across the
country.
   Federal courts have issued conflicting opinions about it, and
although Congress has passed a special law allowing for such clubs,
the issue is now before the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Several church groups, supporting student rights to form such
groups, contend Westside put a double-nix on it, barring the club
for lack of school sponsorship, although such sponsorship would
make the club unconstitutional.
   Either way, it's out, according to the school board's position,
amounting to a ``self-imposed Catch-22'' for the students, the
church groups say in a brief supporting the students' appeal to the
Supreme Court.
   Efforts at organizing such clubs, strictly by student initiative
and without official school involvement, has had a rocky and
litigious course in many communities throughout this decade.
   Trying to dispel the confusion, Congress adopted the Equal
Access Act in 1984, guaranteeing student religious groups the same
rights to meet in off-class hours as other non-academic,
extracurricular groups.
   The law was based on rights of free speech _ that schools with a
``limited open forum'' allowing students to organize clubs about
politics, dancing, archery, bridge or whatever also must allow
clubs that talk religion.
   But schools have remained skittish about any religious inklings
on campus ever since the 1962-63 high court decisions banning
sponsored prayer or Bible readings.
   ``Some educators have come to believe that all religious speech
must be extirpated from the schools,'' the churches' brief says,
but such a view fails to distinguish between officially sponsored
speech and individual rights.
   Congress sought to end discrimination against student religious
speech but the brief says ``this case shows that at least some
local school officials fundamentally reject each and every premise
on which Congress acted.''
   On the other hand, the American Jewish Committee, which opposes
the act, has filed a brief contending that to allow a school
religious club would ``open the door to organized religious
activities in public schools.''
   In a dispute at the Wiliamport, Pa., high school, the Supreme
Court in 1986 affirmed the right of students to meet for Bible and
prayer outside classtime, but the case was decided on a technical
point not generally applicable.
   Early this year, a federal appeals court ruled against a student
religious group at a Renton, Wash., high school, giving the school
discretion to allow clubs considered even remotely related to
education, but not if religious.
   In the dispute at Westside high school, a federal district court
upheld the school board's refusal to allow a religious club while
permitting about 30 other other clubs, such as for chess and scuba
diving.
   But a federal appeals court overturned that decision, rejecting
the school's position that the various clubs were
curriculum-related.
   That claim, the court said, would allow a school administration
simply to choose whatever clubs it wished for vague reasons, but
then to ``discriminate against particular student groups'' because
of religious speech.
   ``It would be tragic if the court allows a school board to
eviscerate'' the Equal Acess Act ``by declaring all clubs except
relgious ones to be `curriculum-related','' says Oliver Thomas,
general counsel for the Baptist Joint Committee on Public Affairs.
   Other groups joining in the brief were the Christian Legal
Scoiety, the National Association of Evangelicals, the Presbyterian
Church (USA) and the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
   U.S. Catholic Bishops have filed their own brief, affirming
rights of students to form voluntary Bible clubs.
   The brief says the action of the school officials, instead of
upholding the Constitution, have created a constitutional problem
``by inhibiting religious activity and conveying a message of
disapproval of religious activity to both the students involved and
the community at large.''
   Oral arguments before the Supreme Court are expected to be heard
this month or early next year, with a decision by next summer.
   Meanwhile, Bridget Megens, who with friends initiated attempts
for a Bible club at Westside High School in 1984 and is now married
and the mother of a young daughter, says: ``I was afraid there
might not be anybody to carry the torch.''
   However, she says about 15 students still are pushing the
effort. ``There are even some kids who are not Christians who are
interested,'' she told the monthly Church and State.
   She says she hopes the dispute will be resolved so her daughter
can belong to a Bible study group at her high school when she grows
up.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday AMs, Dec. 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
