<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 08,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Dec. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An informal survey by Americans United for the
Separation of Church and State finds 107 church-state conflicts
smoldering in 38 states, mostly about religion and public schools
or aid to church-run schools.
   A variety of other disputes also are were found, such as over
teaching creationism in science courses, prayers at sports events
and taxing of church property, the report says.
   The Rev. Robert L. Maddox, executive of the group, says recent
opinion polls find a large proportion of people backing religious
elements in public institutions.
   He says that while majorities profess support for a ``high wall
of separation'' between church and state in theory, polls indicate
they have difficulty accepting such a wall in practice.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The eight seminaries of the Evangelical Lutheran
Church in America face a financial crisis, says the Rev. Roger W.
Fjeld, president of Wartburg Theological Seminary in Dubuque, Iowa.
   He told a meeting the seminaries are working as a network to
increase endowments and take other steps to overcome the crisis and
keep the seminaries vital.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many religious leaders have charged persectuion
of churches in El Salvador following the murder of six Jesuit
priests and arrests or expulsion of numerous Lutheran and Episcopal
church workers there
   Some church leaders also called for a halt to U.S. military aid
there. Top officials of nine U.S. religious bodies charged a
``deliberate and calcuated campaigin to intimidate and harass the
churchers.''
   Presiding Bishop Edmond L. Browning of the Episcopal Church
urged a complete reassessment of U.S. policy in Latin America. The
United Methodist Board of Global Ministries asked the U.S.
government to cut off its ``supply of weapons'' that are worsening
a civil war.
   Roman Catholic Archbishop Roger M. Mahony of Los Angeles cited
threats against El Salvador bishops and other church workers on
government-controlled radio and an official's call for removal of
some Catholic bishops. such statements is unworthy of American
support,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children of Christian-Jewish marriages are
psychologically healthier if raised in the religion of one of the
parents rather than in both faiths or none, a panel of experts said.
   The panel on issues of interfaith marriages was held at the
American Psychological Association convention.
   Lydia Kukoff of Los Angeles, a Reform Jewish specialist, said
reluctance of interfaith couples to choose one faith for their
child, or their decision to let the child decide later ``masks a
dangerous ambivalence.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A specialist on asserted apperances and
predictions of the Virgin Mary at Fatima, Portgugal, in 1917 sees
monumental religious implications in last week's meeting between
the Soviet president and the pope.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev ``may have natural reasons for
it, but heaven has supernatural reasons,'' says the Rev. Robert J.
Fox, editor of the quarterly Fatima Family Messenger.
   In the Fatima apperances, Mary predicted Russia's conversion and
a period of world peace, Fox says, and on March 25, 1984, Pope John
Paul II consecrated the world and Russia to Mary's immaculate heart.
   ``Never have we seen such dramatic and rapid changes'' as those
that since have swept Eastern Europe, Fox says, attributing them to
Mary's ``intercecession with her divine son.''
   ``Russia is going to be the leader of spirituality in the third
millenium,'' Fox said.
</TEXT>
