<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1444EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w AM-DismantlingCatastrophic Adv11   12-07 0919</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dismantling Catastrophic, Adv 11,0938</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Dec. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bureaucracy Shifts Into Reverse To Dismantle Catastrophic-Care Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal bureaucrats and private insurers are
scrambling to rework health insurance benefits, adjust premiums and
spread the word that the end is near for Medicare's year-old
catastrophic health care program.
   In addition, millions of senior citizens are refiguring their
expected 1989 tax bills, the Internal Revenue Service is scrapping
Form 8808 before it hits the printing press, and states are trying
to figure out how they will cover an extra $300 million to $400
million in health care expenses for the poor.
   The Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act _ expected to cost $48
billion in its first five years _ was enacted with fanfare in 1988
to protect 33 million elderly and disabled people against financial
ruin from the staggering costs of prolonged illness.
   But even before most of the benefits took effect, Congress voted
last month to dismantle the program because of a firestorm of
protest from senior citizens who complained it cost them too much.
President Bush has promised to sign the repeal measure.
   Under repeal, the Health Care Financing Administration must take
back the extended hospitalization and nursing home coverage it has
offered Medicare beneficiaries for the past year and scrap plans to
provide expanded coverage of drug and doctor bills and other
medical expenses.
   Louis B. Hays, the acting HCFA administrator, said a top
priority for the agency is to get notices out to Medicare
beneficiaries explaining the new limits on their hospital and
nursing home benefits.
   ``We want to make sure that there isn't confusion,'' Hays said.
   The agency also can forget about providing additional medical
benefits that ``we had invested enormous energy and time in
preparing to implement,'' he said.
   The IRS and the Social Security Administration, meanwhile, have
the tasks of rolling back the income tax surcharge on the elderly
and the extra Medicare premium that financed the catastrophic
program. The surtax was canceled completely; the extra premium will
be scrapped at the end of the year.
   IRS spokesman Henry Holmes said taxpayers will be instructed to
ignore two lines on this year's 1040 tax forms _ lines 54 and 55 _
which refer senior citizens to the elusive Form 8808 that never got
beyond the prototype stage.
   Higher-income senior citizens would have used 8808 to calculate
their added income tax liability for the Medicare benefits. Senior
citizens who paid extra amounts in quarterly income tax payments or
through wage withholding to cover the Medicare surtax will get any
overpayments back as part of their income tax refund, Holmes said.
   About 40 percent of the elderly would have paid some surtax _
$22.50 for every $150 of federal income tax liability _ with about
6 percent paying the maximum amount of $800 per person this year.
   Scrapping the tax is the type of last-minute change it is easy
to spring on taxpayers, Holmes said.
   ``Everybody enjoys hearing news that they don't have to pay a
tax that was on the books,'' he said.
   The Social Security Administration, meanwhile, is complaining
that Congress did not give the agency enough lead time to stop
withholding extra Medicare premiums that helped finance the
catastrophic benefits. It may be April or May before extra payments
of about $5.30 a month no longer are deducted from Social Security
checks, with the overpayments to be refunded later. The premiums of
$4 a month during 1989 will not be refunded.
   ``The bottom line is that Social Security will unscramble this
egg, but we did not lay it,'' said Social Security Commissioner
Gwendolyn King.
   The repeal also is causing last-minute maneuvering among private
insurers who will pick up some of the benefits being canned by the
government. About 70 percent of elderly Americans purchase private
``medigap'' insurance to fill the gaps in their Medicare coverage.
   The National Association of Insurance Commissioners has until
Dec. 15 to draft transition regulations for medigap policies, and
private insurers have until Jan. 30 to revise their policies and
premiums and notify policyholders of the changes. Any changes,
however, will be retroactive to Jan. 1, when the government
benefits expire.
   ``Insurance companies are doing their best, they're just
grumbling about how long it took Congress to make up their mind,''
said Alan Richards of the Health Insurance Association of America.
``It's kind of a `We'll muddle through' situation. We just hope
Congress doesn't change their mind again next year.''
   The association has estimated medigap premiums will rise 20
percent to 25 percent next year due to the combined effects of
rising medical costs and the repeal of the catastrophic package.
   Fallout from the repeal also is reaching state governments. The
repeal legislation left in place expanded Medicaid costs for the
states, while scrapping provisions that would have offset some of
the new expenses, said Alicia Pelrine of the National Governors'
Association.
   ``Grumbling is probably a tame word to describe what is going on
out there,'' Ms. Pelrine said. ``States are already so maxed out on
their ability to accommodate various (federal) mandates ... that a
lot are saying, `We don't know how we're going to pay for this.' ''
   Gerald Miller, executive director of the National Association of
State Budget Officers, said the original catastrophic legislation
would have cost states $900 million, but the repeal bill boosts
those costs by an additional $300 million to $400 million.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Dec. 11</NOTE>
