<FIRST>s i BC-Chile-Sketches Adv10   12-07 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chile-Sketches, Adv 10,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 10, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sketches of Chilean Presidential Candidates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Chile Votes, b0517</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of the candidates
in Chile's presidential election:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PATRICIO AYLWIN _ An ex-senador and former president of the
Christian Democratic Party, the country's largest, Aylwin was
nominated by an opposition alliance of 17 leftist and centrist
political groups. Virtually every opinion poll gives him a
commanding lead over his two opponents.
   At 71, he is the oldest candidate and was already a prominent
politician when Gen. Augusto Pinochet seized power in a 1973 coup.
   Considered somewhat right-of-center, Aylwin initially supported
the military takeover, but became disillusioned with Pinochet's
strong-arm tactics and reluctance to hand power back to civilians.
He gradually joined the ranks of the government's outspoken critics.
   He is known as an able negotiator with a low-key, conciliatory
style, and he was the official spokesman for the opposition
alliance when it successfully campaigned for the ``no'' vote in a
referendum in October 1988, on a proposal that Pinochet remain
president until 1997. That defeat forced Pinochet to call elections
to pick a successor.
   In the campaign Aylwin has pledged to re-establish full respect
for human rights and civil liberties and to increase spending on
social programs. He has said he plans no major changes in Chile's
free-market economic program.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HERNAN BUCHI _ Pinochet's finance minister from 1985 until last
May, Buchi is considered the principal architect of a free-market
economy that has produced five years of steady growth and low
inflation.
   Buchi, 40, is an all-around athlete who runs several miles
daily, climbs mountains and jumps horses. With a master's degree
from Columbia University's business school, he joined the Pinochet
adminstration in 1975 as an Economy Ministry aide and rapidly
ascended the bureaucratic ladder.
   He is considered highly intelligent but slightly eccentric. His
trademark is a roughly trimmed page-boy haircut that once prompted
Pinochet to dub him ``my Prince Valiant.'' One of the slogans of
his campaign has been ``Buchi is different.''
   Despite an international reputation as an able technocrat, he
entered the race as a political novice. Indeed, he withdrew for
several weeks in May and June, declaring he was too shy to be a
candidate. He returned, he said, because of a sense of patriotic
duty.
   Backed by conservative businessmen and rightist political
groups, he has campaigned as the ``can-do'' candidate. He has
promised a million new jobs during the next four years and said he
will spend more on health and education.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FRANCISCO ERAZZURIZ _ From a prominent Chilean family that has
produced several presidents, Errazuriz has dedicated most of his
adult life to amassing wealth.
   The 47-year-old entrepreneur has built a commercial empire that
consists of some 30 businesses including mining and fishing
interests, automobile concessions, a fruit exporting company and a
supermarket chain. All told, he employs about 8,000 workers.
   Characterized by his opponents as a populist, he has promised
free health care and education to all Chileans. He is backed by a
few small political groups.
   He describes himself as a ``centrist-centrist'' and says his
candidacy offers Chileans an alternative to the traditional choice
between leftist and rightist candidates.
   His nickname is ``Fra-Fra.'' One of his principal campaign
slogans is ``No more bla-bla. Vote for Fra-Fra.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 10</NOTE>
