<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Cholesterol Adv11   12-07 1295</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Cholesterol, Adv 11,1329</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scientific Camps Still Sorting Out Cholesterol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Americans wend their way through the season of
holiday goodies and then decide what diet to choose for the New
Year, they face a smorgasbord of scientific updates and debate over
cholesterol.
   A 2-year-old government campaign to get people interested in
knowing how much of the fatty substance is in their arteries has
made cholesterol a popular topic from cocktail parties to
medical-screening booths in shopping malls.
   Researchers are releasing new studies detailing how excess
cholesterol _ an essential building block of cell membranes, sex
hormones and Vitamin D _ in the blood clogs vessels and causes
heart attacks.
   Food manufacturers are devising new products to capitalize on
the findings, splashing ``cholesterol-free'' banners across items
ranging from cupcakes to peanut butter, which never contained
cholesterol anyway.
   News media have kept the public's curiosity piqued with the
views of a small but vocal group of critics, including scientists.
They say the public is being frightened needlessly, many people
won't benefit from the low-cholesterol diets, and money is wasted
to try to get America to change the way it eats.
   How bad is cholesterol? How hard should people work to avoid it?
And how much will that help increase their chances of living longer?
   Researchers have spent hundreds of millions of federal dollars
trying to answer those questions; many top scientists are convinced
of the results.
   ``The evidence linking elevated blood cholesterol to coronary
heart disease is overwhelming,'' a group of them said recently in a
statement by the American Heart Association and the National Heart,
Lung and Blood Institute.
   Population studies, clinical trials, genetic tests and animal
experiments show that high levels of blood cholesterol clog
arteries and increase the risk of heart disease, they said, adding
clinical trials show lowering cholesterol levels by diet or drugs
decreases subsequent occurrence of heart disease.
   ``The direct evidence ... is strongest in middle-aged men with
high initial cholesterol levels,'' but also strongly suggests
cutting cholesterol is likely ``to decrease coronary heart disease
incidence in younger and older men, in women, and in persons with
more moderate cholesterol levels,'' they said.
   Two of the largest studies to date suggest that a 1 percent
reduction in blood cholesterol translates into a 2 percent
reduction in the risk of developing coronary heart disease, they
added.
   Those studies _ the Coronary Primary Prevention Trial, involving
more than 3,800 middle-aged men, and the Framingham Heart Study of
over 5,000 women and men _ have been supported by others suggesting
greater benefit, they said.
   However, critics of the anti-cholesterol campaign contend it has
misled people by excluding mention of other major contributors to
heart disease, America's No. 1 killer, which claims more than
500,000 lives a year.
   One critic, Dr. Robert E. Olson, professor of medicine and
pharmacological science at the State University of New York at
Stony Brook, says only about 20 percent of a person's heart-disease
risk is attributable to blood cholesterol.
   An estimated 40 percent is hereditary and the rest is due to
other causes, chiefly smoking and high blood pressure, he said.
``We think there's too much hype in the marketplace and even in
these educational agencies. Everybody's sort of afraid of their
food and afraid of their cholesterol, often without medical
surveillance.''
   Dr. Fredrick J. Stare, Harvard nutrition professor emeritus and
co-author of ``Balanced Nutrition: Beyond the Cholesterol Scare,''
agrees. ``We don't think the National Cholesterol Education Program
gives enough attention to other risk factors that are more
important _ smoking, high blood pressure, obesity, diabetes, lack
of a reasonable amount of activity and stress.''
   Dr. Eliot Corday of Los Angeles, past president of the American
College of Cardiology, said he objects to cholesterol-lowering
efforts for people over 65.
   ``Over 65, there's no proof there's any benefit,'' said Corday,
formerly a member of the advisory council to the National Heart,
Lung and Blood Institute, where he felt ``very, very outnumbered''
by ardent cholesterol opponents.
   Elderly patients ``try very hard not to touch a bit of
cholesterol,'' Corday said, even though ``it's a damn fool thing to
stop eating eggs and meat when they need the nutrition. They get
anemic.''
   The British Royal College of Physicians recommended in February
that checking family histories for heart attacks is more important
than cholesterol testing, said Victor Herbert, professor of
medicine at New York's Mount Sinai Hospital. ``I agree with them.
If a lot of people in the family didn't have heart attacks, you're
not going to have one.''
   Cholesterol testing becomes appropriate if the family history
suggests a genetic tendency to heart attack, he said.
Cholesterol-modifying efforts should begin only if blood levels are
high for so-called ``bad cholesterol'' _ LDL, or low-density
lipoprotein _ and low for so-called ``good cholesterol'' _ HDL, or
high-density lipoprotein.
   Olson, Corday and Herbert were on a panel assembled in September
by the Council on Science and Health, a consumer education group
partly funded by the food industry, to offset what they call the
cholesterol ``scare.''
   Part of their message was that only 15 percent of the population
have blood-cholesterol levels putting them clearly at greater risk
for heart attacks.
   That level is generally agreed to be 240 milligrams per
deciliter of blood, and people testing that high ``should be seeing
a physician... They should not be self-medicating themselves'' with
diet changes, said Elizabeth M. Whelan, the council's president.
Besides, lowering cholesterol dietarily is difficult at best and
impossible for many; not everyone responds the same way.
   Confusion also prevails about what to modify in the diet, with
undue emphasis placed on cholesterol, Herbert said. ``We make three
times as much cholesterol from dietary fat as from dietary
cholesterol. Too much (dietary) cholesterol is not the culprit. Too
much saturated fat is the culprit.''
   Dr. John C. LaRosa, chairman of the task force on cholesterol
issues for the American Heart Association, says critics ``are not
really saying anything different'' from the government scientists.
   Their guidelines are unchanged since being introduced two years
ago as part of the National Cholesterol Education Program, which
recommends that all adults learn their blood-cholesterol level and
aim for a level below 200 milligrams per deciliter of blood. Those
with levels of 200-239 are considered borderline high, not
requiring treatment unless they have two other traits that increase
their risk for heart disease, including hereditary tendency and
being male.
   People who head for shopping malls or other public places to get
their cholesterol checked should be wary, though. The Department of
Health and Human Services said last month that such screenings can
be inaccurate, pose health risks and frequently fail to provide
counseling or physician referral.
   Those with confirmed levels of 240 or above are at high risk and
should get HDL and LDL testing. If warranted, treatment should
begin with diet and exercise, and should proceed to drugs only if
that approach fails.
   The scientific basis for the guidelines ``is probably more solid
than for any public health venture that I know of,'' said Dr.
Daniel Steinberg, a professor of medicine at the University of
California at San Diego.
   Steinberg was chairman of the federal 1984 Concensus Development
Conference panel that gave rise to the assault on cholesterol.
   ``It has been tremendously effective in bringing in people who
have been previously unwilling to listen to lifestyle
modifications,'' said Dr. Nancy Dickey, of Richmond, Texas, an
American Medical Association board member.
   Seventeen European nations in 1987 reached the same conclusions
as the U.S. panel, and the Canadians did so later, Steinberg said.
``This is not sort of an off-the-wall conclusion by Americans who
are gung-ho against cholesterol.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 11</NOTE>
