<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--KillerBees Adv11   12-07 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Killer Bees, Adv 11,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Lab Develops Devices to Track Bees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAK RIDGE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Behind the security gates at Oak Ridge
National Laboratory, researchers are quietly preparing for an
invasion. They've come up with one device to tell friend from foe
and another to track the enemy.
   The invaders began their advance about 40 years ago and now are
massing in Mexico for a final assault expected some time next year.
   No need to hustle down to the gun shop _ these invaders are
aggressive Africanized bees, sometimes known as ``killer bees''
because they have killed animals and people. They've also disrupted
honeybee colonies.
   Researchers at the federal laboratory here have developed a
hand-held sensor that can distinguish between the tamer domestic
honeybees and their more aggressive cousins, and a prototype of a
device to track the Africanized bees using a solar-powered,
infared-pulsating, microchip bee backpack.
   Neither device falls directly into the work done by the nuclear
engineers and electronics specialists at the U.S. Department of
Energy lab. But they were intrigued by parallels with their work in
connection with radiation monitoring.
   The $339 noise sensor, dubbed a ``Buzz Buster,'' is ready for
market, said engineer Howard Kerr, who developed it largely in his
spare time. ``I've been to Venezuela twice and Mexico once with
this thing and it works like a top.''
   Kerr, an amateur beekeeper, got started a few years ago when
told by a federal agricultural official that for some unexplained
reason the Africanized bees that were released from a Brazilian lab
make a louder sound in flight.
   The resulting Buzz Buster allows monitoring of a bee colony from
a distance to determine whether there are any Africanized bees
buzzing inside.
   While working on the Buzz Buster, Ker called in Chip Taylor, a
University of Kansas bee expert, who said what researchers needed
was a way to track bees, particularly during mating. That sparked
the idea for the microchip backpack.
   After a year of research and $100,000 in seed money from the
lab, Gary Alley's team has developed a transmitter about one-fourth
the size of a postage stamp that sends an infrared beam more than a
1 kilometer. An 8-inch telescope with a special sensor detects the
beam, which can't be seen by the naked eye.
   Alley allows that the transmitter, at about 65 milligrams, is
still 15 milligrams too heavy for a bee to carry, and work on a
computerized tracking system hasn't even begun. But ``I think we
have proven the concept,'' he said. ``There are certainly some
refinements that need to be made. But I think the concept is
feasible.
   ``Today, I couldn't give you a field demonstration of putting
one on a bee. But several major hurdles have been crossed.''
   But he said the hardest work has already been done, and the main
job now is to get more funding to carry on.
   ``We've gotten interest from a broad spectrum of agencies, none
of whom are interested in honeybees,'' Kerr lamented. ``There's a
lot of things that people would like to be able to track with a
very inconspicuous transmitter attached to it.''
   NASA thinks the transmitters might be used for equipment
inventories aboard spacecraft, and there have been inquiries from
people who would like to use the microchip to track animals, birds
and insects, Alley said.
   There also has been interest from the Defense Department and
``how would you characterize it? _ the FBI,'' he said.
   Even if the transmitter isn't ready by the time the Africanized
bees reach the United States, Taylor said, it will be developed
eventually because of the number of possible applications. ``This
is a technology that has to come along. If it doesn't come along
right now, it's got to come along in the future.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
