<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-CoalMine Adv11   12-07 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--What's New-Coal Mine, Adv 11,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fishery Officials Hooked on Old Coal Mines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT HARVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Charles Wagner pulled a whopper
rainbow trout from the Elkhorn River last summer, his state-record
catch spawned an idea.
   Officials marveled that the 11-pound, 3-ounce beauty thrived in
springwater fed in part by an abandoned coal mine, and want to make
it a fish hatchery.
   ``Trout are extremely fragile,'' said Ed Hamrick, director of
the state Department of Natural Resources. ``They need so many
factors in order for them to perpetuate themselves naturally.''
   ``Most people, when they think of a coal mine, don't think of a
hatchery,'' said Don Phares, state assistant chief of cold water
fisheries.
   Good sites for trout hatcheries are hard to find because many
count on natural springs for water, Phares said. He and U.S. Rep.
Nick Rahall, D-W.Va., chairman of the House mining and natural
resources subcommittee, insist water conditions at some old coal
mines are just right to produce the big ones.
   Water draining from coal mines is usually very acid because of
the residue of high-sulfur coal. The mine that feeds the Elkhorn
was always low in sulfur.
   Phares and Rahall refused to name the mine or give its location
until it can be purchased. Congress will take up the project next
year; it must approve $2.5 million to buy the mine and build the
hatchery.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and state Department of
Natural Resources would build the hatchery, with a series of
concrete runways eight feet wide by 100 long to produce up to
200,000 fish a year, Phares said. The mine drainage would be
recirculated, with some outside water added for volume.
   The prototype hatchery could spawn new life for many old mines,
said Jim Zoia, staff director of the House subcommittee. ``There's
a lot of potential in the Appalachian area.''
   Ed Hayne Jr. of Charleston, vice president of West Virginia's
southern chapter of Trout Unlimited, said there are high hopes for
the hatchery. ``Being a big trout fisherman, I think it's needed
and it could very well turn out to be a big economic boost to
McDowell County.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
