<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0792</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. economic activity ranged from stable to
expanding modestly last month, although the manufacturing sector
showed signs of weakness, the Federal Reserve Board said.
   In its latest survey of economic conditions, the central bank
said Wednesday only two of its 12 districts showed ``some recent
softening'' in the economy. The districts were not named, but
summaries provided by the Fed indicated they were the ones based in
Richmond, Va., and St. Louis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's unprecedented peacetime economic
expansion, now in its eighth year, will last at least three more
years, the nation's top business economists said.
   The National Association of Business Economists said Wednesday
the latest survey of its members found 62 percent expecting no
recession for the next three years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publishing and information services giant
McGraw-Hill Inc. said it was eliminating more than 1,000 jobs, or 7
percent of its full-time positions, and taking a big charge in a
cost-cutting realignment.
   Investors sent McGraw-Hill's stock down following Wednesday's
announcement, in apparent disappointment at the company's
projection of earnings for 1990 despite the charges being taken
this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States spent nearly $6 billion from
August through October to stem the dollar's rise and keep the
currency in the trading range set with other major industrialized
nations, the Federal Reserve said.
   A quarterly foreign-exchange report Wednesday by the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York showed the Fed and the Treasury sold
$5.871 billion in exchange for West German marks and Japanese yen
during the three months ended Oct. 31.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American workers made modest productivity
gains in the third quarter but the manufacturing sector posted its
lowest output gain in three years and continued to slow the overall
economy, the government said.
   For the first time this year, the quarter-to-quarter hourly wage
gains made by workers outpaced the growth in consumer inflation,
the Labor Department said in Wednesday's report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Third World loan losses at big New York banks
and souring real estate markets in the Northeast and Arizona pushed
commercial banking into the red last summer for the first time in
more than two years, the government said.
   The nation's 12,824 banks lost $744 million in the
July-September quarter, off sharply from $7 billion in profits in
the second quarter and $7.3 billion in the first three months of
the year, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said Wednesday. For
the first nine months, banks earned $13.7 billion, almost $5
billion less than same period of 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said it wants to sell its Chrysler
Technologies Corp. subsidiary, which includes its defense
electronics and Gulfstream Aerospace aircraft businesses, to
concentrate on making cars and trucks.
   The decision disclosed Wednesday to explore the sale comes as
the auto market is softening, foreign competition is increasing,
and Chrysler is attempting to cut costs to remain competitive.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chairman of publishing giant
Macmillan Inc. and two current executives of the company have
settled Securities and Exchange Commission charges alleging they
filed misleading documents.
   The three _ Edward P. Evans, Macmillan's chairman from 1980 to
1988; William F. Reilly, Macmillan's chief operating officer; and
Beverly C. Chell, the publisher's general counsel _ were accused of
filing misleading or incomplete documents concerning the purpose
for buying 1.2 million shares of Macmillan stock in 1987.
   On Wednesday, the three _ without admitting or denying
wrongdoing _ settled and consented to an injunction barring them
from violating securities disclosure rules.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of investors rushed to beat
the deadline for applying to buy shares in Britain's water industry
under the government's $8.2 billion privatization of the business.
   There had been concern the Wednesday's sale would attract little
interest because of the British stock market's recent sluggishness.
The privatization also has been strongly opposed by critics who say
such a vital utility should remain in state hands for security
reasons and to protect consumers from rate hikes.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell in listless trading Wednesday, as the Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials lost 4.91 points to finish at
2,736.77.
   A Federal Reserve Board report that U.S. economic activity
ranged from stable to slightly stronger last month sent bond prices
downward.
   The dollar declined against most major foreign currencies.
   Grain, soybean, sugar and energy futures rose, precious metals
were firm, and livestock and pork futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
