<FIRST>r f PM-Economy-Consumers     12-07 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy-Consumers,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Board: Consumer Confidence Off in November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer confidence in the economy fell in
November but remains relatively strong, the Conference Board said.
   A survey of 5,000 households nationwide showed that buying plans
for houses and cars are soft and that Americans are slightly less
optimistic about their expectations for the economy in the coming
months.
   The Conference Board's consumer confidence index, released
Wednesday, registered 114.4 for November, the lowest since November
1988.
   Twenty-six percent of survey participants said current business
conditions are good, down from 28 percent in October and the lowest
level in more than a year. But the percentage who thought the
economy was bad also fell, to 15.3 percent from 16.9 percent.
   Respondents' outlook for economic conditions six months from now
showed 17.4 percent thought conditions would improve, the lowest
since April.
   In a separate report, the Conference Board said the volume of
help-wanted advertising in 51 major newspapers increased in
October. The group said want-ad volume was rising in 69 percent of
the newspapers, compared with 55 percent in September and 35
percent in August 1988, but down from 84 percent a year ago.
   The board's help-wanted advertising index rose to 150 from 148
in September, but was down sharply from 161 a year ago.
   ``There is no question that labor market activity is slowing
down, as is the economy in general,'' Conference Board economist
Ken Goldstein said. ``The data on want-ad volume suggests that
while the labor market is cooling off we are not on the verge of a
recession.''
   The Conference Board is a non-profit business organization that
conducts economic research and provides forums for businesses to
exchange information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
