<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Fed-Dollar     12-07 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Dollar,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Sold Dollars Heavily In August-October Period</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States spent nearly $6 billion from
August through October to stem the dollar's rise and keep the
currency in the trading range set with other major industrialized
nations, the Federal Reserve reported.
   The quarterly foreign-exchange report released Wednesday by the
Federal Reserve Bank of New York showed the Fed and the Treasury
sold $5.871 billion in exchange for West German marks and Japanese
yen during the three months ended Oct. 31.
   The New York Fed said the government sold a total of $3.289
billion for Japanese yen and $2.582 billion for West German marks.
   The move, the government's second-largest unloading of dollars
ever in a three-month period, comes on the heels of the
record-setting sale of $11.92 billion in the quarter ended July 31.
   The dollar initially got a boost during the August-October
quarter from a spate of favorable economic data. Because of the
figures, which indicated the economy was not as sluggish as
previously believed, the Federal Reserve was not inclined to push
interest rates lower _ which kept returns relatively attractive on
dollar-denominated securities.
   Gains in retail sales and employment and a better-than-expected
trade report helped boost the dollar to its high during the period
of 2.00 West German marks and 148.98 Japanese yen on Sept. 15.
   But a meeting of the Group of Seven industrial nations in
Washington later that month produced a sharply worded statement
criticizing the dollar's rise. The group _ which includes the
United States, Britain, West Germany, Japan, Canada, Italy and
France _ favors a relatively weaker dollar, which is seen as
helping reduce the huge U.S. trade deficit.
   The Group of Seven called the dollar's rise inconsistent with
long-run fundamentals'' and said a further rise could ``adversely
affect prospects for the world economy.''
   The bulk of the Fed's intervention, which was coordinated with
other leading central banks, occurred in the weeks leading up to
the G-7 meeting and in several weeks following the gathering.
   ``Activities after the (G-7 meeting) were forceful,'' said Sam
Y. Cross, a New York Fed executive vice president who presented the
report to reporters. ``We did act quite forcefully to reinforce the
policy statement'' of the group.
   ``Since that time the dollar has trended downward,'' Cross said.
   By early October the dollar had plunged to 1.8650 West German
marks and 138.60 Japanese yen.
   By mid-October, the upward pressure on the dollar had fully
eased. Interest rates in Europe and in Japan _ traditionally far
lower than U.S. rates _ were higher, thereby shrinking the
advantage the United States had in terms of return to investors and
reducing demand for dollars.
   Furthermore, more recent reports indicated sluggishness in the
U.S. economy that raised speculation the Federal Reserve might ease
credit to help prevent a recession.
   The spotlight shifted to foreign currencies, particularly the
mark, which was bolstered by West Germany's bright economic
prospects and the beginnings of a massive reform movement in
Eastern Europe.
   The dollar now is trading at about 1.76-1.77 marks and 143-144
yen.
   Currency traders are often keenly aware of the activities of
central banks in the open markets, but the Fed's policy is to
comment only well after the fact. The Fed does not provide any data
on intervention by foreign central banks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
