<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-McGraw-Hill Bjt   12-07 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McGraw-Hill, Bjt,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plans Restructuring To Eliminate 1,000 Jobs, Take Writedown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publishing and information services giant
McGraw-Hill Inc. is trimming more than 1,000 jobs, or 7 percent of
its full-time positions, and taking a big charge against its
earnings in a cost-cutting realignment.
   But Wall Streeters sent the company's stock lower Wednesday in
what analysts said reflected disappointment with the company's
earnings projections for 1990 despite the cutbacks.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, McGraw-Hill closed down $2 a
share at $61.50.
   Chairman Joseph L. Dionne said next year's earnings, excluding
non-recurring gains, would be within a range of $3.50 to $4 a share
even after the the job eliminations and $152 million in charges
after taxes in the fourth quarter. Last year, McGraw-Hill earned
$3.83 a share.
   Bruce Thorp, a media analyst for Provident National Bank in
Philadelphia, called the cost-cutting move ``one of the more
decisive things'' McGraw-Hill has done. But he said the earnings
projection surprised analysts.
   ``It's a sign that business isn't really good,'' he said.
   Bert Boksen, who follows McGraw-Hill for Raymond James &amp;
Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla., said, ``The outlook was a lot
worse than anybody expected. ``It indicates a softer-than-expected
outlook for the school publishing business and a general slowing of
the economy,'' he said.
   The company did not specify where the job eliminations would be,
but indicated many would be corporate positions rather than in
operating units, which include Business Week magazine and Standard
&amp; Poor's debt rating service.
   ``The effort to improve productivity and make the organization
leaner is a step in the right direction,'' said Peter Appert, a
media analyst for C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc. But he said
the company should do more.
   ``Operating margins in some of their units are low by industry
standards,'' Appert said, citing TV station operations and some
information services units.
   He said the stock market's negative reaction to the announcement
would do nothing to discourage speculation that the company may be
a takeover target.
   McGraw-Hill said it would deduct $220 million from its pre-tax
earnings, or $152 million after taxes, in the fourth quarter for
writing down the value of assets, including those at its
DRI-McGraw-Hill economic forecasting unit. The charge also reflects
the closing of a unit that publishes general-interest books and the
establishment of a reserve for employee severance payments.
   Several publishing companies recently have taken writedowns,
including Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. and Paramount
Communications Inc., which owns Simon &amp; Schuster.
   In addition, Time Warner Inc. recently agreed to sell its Scott
Foresman &amp; Co. textbook division for less than it paid for it three
years ago and expects to take a pretax charge of $175 million on
the deal.
   McGraw-Hill said it would scrap its current internal structure
of three operating companies _ publishing, financial services and
information services _ and have all operations report to two new
corporate executive vice presidents responsible to Dionne.
   One new executive vice president is Harold W. McGraw III,
great-grandson of the company's founder. McGraw is in charge of
overseeing the financial services, Business Week and broadcasting
groups and the aerospace and defense information units. He had been
head of financial services.
   The other, Walter D. Serwatka, will be responsible for divisions
that provide information on the construction industry, education,
law, computers and communications. He also will oversee the
professional publishing group. He had headed information services.
   ``Adopting this streamlined corporate structure eliminates an
entire layer of staffing and related expenses associated with the
three operating companies,'' Dionne said in a statement.
   The rest of the jobs being eliminated will result from
previously disclosed plans to automate delivery of the F.W. Dodge
Group reports on the construction industry and from corporate staff
reductions, spokesman Stewart Trisler said.
   McGraw-Hill employs about 13,700 people, meaning the reductions
would amount to a 7 percent cut in staffing.
   The company earned $54.97 million, or $1.13 a share, on revenue
of $507.4 million in the fourth quarter of 1988. It earned $185.5
million, or $3.83 a share, on revenue of $1.82 billion for all of
1988.
</TEXT>
