<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern     12-07 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Objects to Methods Used in Investigation of Finances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An extensive financial investigation of Eastern
Airlines being made under the supervision of a federal bankruptcy
court has raised objections from the airline.
   David Boies, an attorney for Eastern, told U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Burton R. Lifland at a hearing Wednesday that the investigation's
objectivity has been compromised because a large part of the work
has been delegated to Eastern's unions.
   Attorney David I. Shapiro, the examiner appointed by the
bankruptcy court, has been conducting the inquiry into Eastern,
Continental Airlines and their parent Texas Air Corp. since early
September. Shapiro and more than 20 associates have been
interviewing current and former officers of the companies, union
leaders and others.
   Shapiro told Lifland he has received a list of complaints from
Boies which contend, among other things, that the investigation has
been ``too tough'' and ``too prosecutorial.'' The examiner said the
magnitude of the task has led him to delegate some work, such as
interviews, to union attorneys but that practice hasn't hurt
objectivity.
   Also at the hearing, Lifland postponed for two months
consideration of a union request for a special trustee to be
appointed to run Miami-based Eastern.
   Lifland postponed from Dec. 15 to Feb. 15 a hearing on the
trustee issue, in accordance with a request by Shapiro. He also
gave Shapiro until Feb. 15 to submit a report on his investigation.
   ``It's clear that the underlying examinations are proceeding
with vigor, with a great deal of discomfort,'' Lifland said.
   The unions at Eastern had asked that a trustee be appointed to
run the airline in place of current management soon after they went
on strike on March 4. Lifland has postponed hearings on the
question several times since then.
   Union attorneys objected Wednesday to Shapiro's request that the
trustee issue be put off again, but they agreed that he needed more
time to complete his inquiry. Attorneys for Eastern's major
creditors supported both of Shapiro's requests.
   Eastern filed for bankruptcy protection on March 9 and has been
rebuilding as a smaller airline by hiring workers to replace the
striking Machinists, pilots and flight attendants.
   Contract talks are ongoing between Eastern and its pilots and
flight attendants unions, which decided to end their 8 1@2-month
sympathy strikes shortly before Thanksgiving. The Machinists union
is still on strike against the airline.
   The unions have accused Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo of
stripping assets from Eastern.
   Shapiro is looking into past transactions between Texas Air,
Eastern and sister carrier Continental. They include, for example,
the transfer of the System One computer reservation system from
Eastern to Texas Air in April 1987 for about $100 million.
   The key question is whether Lorenzo has been treating the three
companies as one airline, Shapiro told the court. He and his staff
have interviewed around 70 people and examined more than 200,000
documents, he said.
   In October, Shapiro had said he expected to complete the
investigation by early December, and said his schedule had been
delayed several times by lawyers for the parties involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
