<DOCNO> AP891207-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirFares     12-07 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Fares,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raise MaxSaver Fares; Temporarily Drop Advance-Purchase Requirements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   While they are raising discount MaxSaver fares, the nation's big
airlines are softening the blow by eliminating advance-purchase
requirements for the popular tickets during the holiday period.
   Following a move a week ago by Pan Am Corp., a number of
airlines said Wednesday they plan to raise MaxSavers by $10 per
round trip on flights of less than 1,000 miles and $20 on longer
trips. The new fares take effect Dec. 16.
   Spokesmen for United Airlines, Continental Airlines, Eastern
Airlines, Delta Air Lines and Northwest Airlines said those
carriers had decided after a week of deliberation to match Pan Am's
increases.
   Most of the airlines also are following United's initiative in
temporarily dropping advance-purchase requirements for the
MaxSavers, the most deeply discounted fares popular with
vacationers.
   American Airlines, the nation's largest carrier, moved Tuesday
to match Pan Am's change.
   American's new MaxSaver fares between New York and Los Angeles,
for example, will be $398 to $438 round trip, up from $378 to $418.
Fares between Chicago and New York will go to $258 to $298 from
$248 to $288.
   Continental spokesman Ned Walker, however, emphasized that the
airline was matching the MaxSaver hikes only in selected markets.
   Passenger traffic normally increases this time of year, a peak
travel season. The airlines have been under pressure to hike fares
because their costs, mainly fuel prices, have increased sharply in
recent months.
   ``I don't think it was too much of a surprise, given the way
costs have been escalating,'' said Edward Starkman, an airline
analyst at PaineWebber Inc.
   Two weeks ago, a number of big carriers led by United said they
planned to raise fares on most domestic routes and eliminate
discount fares used mainly by business travelers. The increases
didn't apply to the MaxSavers, however.
   The airlines said Wednesday they are waiving the usual 14-day
advance-purchase requirements for travel between Dec. 20 and Jan. 5
when seats are available. No refunds are allowed, and passengers
must buy tickets within 24 hours of making a reservation and must
stay over a Saturday night.
</TEXT>
