<DOCNO> AP891207-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Sun-IBM Bjt   12-07 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sun-IBM, Bjt,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sun Needles IBM About Cutbacks, Takes Partial Credit for IBM Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scott McNealy, president of Sun
Microsystems Inc., is needling rival International Business
Machines Corp. over its huge job cuts and said his computer company
can take some of the credit for Big Blue's woes.
   McNealy, who introduced two important additions to Sun's SPARC
desktop computer family Wednesday, predicted a bright future for
his $1.8 billion company in the 1990s despite problems elsewhere in
the industry.
   McNealy's uncharacteristic jabs at IBM and Wall Street traders
came in response to questions about the effect on the computer
industry of IBM's announcement Tuesday that it would cut 10,000
jobs in the United States and set aside $2.3 billion from its
pretax profit to pay for the cuts.
   Asked in an interview Wednesday whether Mountain View-based Sun
might make any cutbacks, McNealy quipped, ``Maybe we should and
make the stock go up.''
   IBM's stock rose 37{ cents on Tuesday's announcement, but fell
$1 Wednesday to $98.62{.
   ``Look at what the analysts did,'' McNealy said. ``IBM made a
statement yesterday that something is very wrong. They laid off a
whole Sun Microsystems worth of employees and they wrote off from
profits more than we have in annual revenue. And their stock went
up.
   ``That's a fundamental statement that, `We don't know what to do
with our cash, so we might as well pay it out in dividends.' Which
is what they're doing.
   ``Their stock went up because (analysts) said, `IBM just washed
all their dirty socks, they took huge reserves and they padded
their balance sheet and income statement massively so that they're
probably not going to have a bad quarter the next couple of
quarters. So I'll get in, ride it up ... then get out before they
do the next one.''
   McNealy noted that IBM's moves were typical of many U.S.
companies.
   ``There are lots of (chief financial officers) in industry who
say when you take a bath, take a big bath because that makes your
stock price go up,'' he said. ``But is that any way to run a
company? I don't think so.''
   That type of thinking, and the short-term opportunities it
provides traders on Wall Street, he said, results from the rules
set by Congress.
   ``I'm not blaming the traders. It's the rules,'' he said. The
answer, he claims, would be to impose heavy income taxes on profits
from stock held less than a year or two.
   McNealy said he has long predicted that the type of workstation
computers Sun sells would cut into the sales of mainframe and
minicomputer systems of companies like IBM.
   Workstations are powerful desktop computers that can be used for
various applications, such as spreadsheets, word processing and
database programming. IBM's mainframes and minicomputers are
time-shared systems hooked to a large number of terminals, and all
the applications are handled by the main processor. IBM also makes
personal computers.
   The three fastest-growing computer companies of the 1980s,
McNealy said, were Compaq Computer Corp., Apple Computer Inc. and
Sun, all of which are desktop-oriented.
   That growth came at the expense of the companies that get most
of their profit from the bigger, costlier computers, such as IBM,
Digital Equipment Corp., Unisys Corp. Control Data Corp. and Amdahl
Corp., Wang Laboratories Inc. and Prime Computer Inc.
   Many industry analysts agree with McNealy's views.
   ``It's fair to say that companies like Apple, Compaq, Sun,
Microsoft and others can take appropriate credit for IBM's
decade-long problems,'' said analyst Peter Rogers of the San
Francisco brokerage Robertson, Stephens &amp; Co.
   ``What's basically happened at IBM is their technology is
obsolete,'' he said. ``The model of computing on which they have
built is no longer the preferred model.''
   Sun's latest entries into its SPARC line are the powerful
SPARCserver 490, which is priced at $113,900 with 32 megabytes of
main memory, and an entry-level SPARCserver 1, priced at $18,900
with 8 megabytes of main memory.
   Founded in 1982, Sun has had only one quarter when it didn't
show a profit. Sun lost $20.3 million in the fiscal fourth quarter
ended last June 30, blaming the slip on product transition and
foulups in an internal computer management system. That cut its
fiscal 1989 profit to $60.8 million on $1.8 billion in sales.
   The company recovered quickly, though, earning $5.2 million in
the first quarter of its 1990 fiscal year.
   Rogers expects Sun will post $93 million in profits in fiscal
1990 on $2.5 billion in sales.
</TEXT>
