<HEAD>Dollar Little Changed, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed in light European
trading early today. Gold bullion prices were higher.
   Dealers said the dollar firmed in late-morning trading amid
short-loss buying by investors who had earlier sold borrowed
dollars on expectations of further declines.
   The market also appeared to be squaring positions before
Friday's release of U.S. unemployment rate figures for November.
Analysts predicted the unemployment rate will rise from 5.3 percent
to 5.4 percent.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar edged up 0.38 Japanese yen to a closing 144.13
yen. Later, in London, it eased to 144.04 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
prices, included: 1.7666 West German marks, up from 1.7648; 1.5870
Swiss francs, down from 1.5875; 6.0365 French francs, up from
6.0315; 1.9935 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0010; 1,303.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,301.15; and 1.1617 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1602.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.5765, unchanged
from late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $405.20 a troy ounce, up
from $402.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $405.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $405.30, up from $403.75 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $4.30 to close at a bid $405.01.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.58 a troy
ounce, up from $5.56 bid late Wednesday.
