<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-07 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks At Another Record High, Dollar Edges Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index closed at a
record high for the 11th time in the last 12 trading days today,
and the dollar edged up against the Japanese yen for the fifth
consecutive day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 203.82
points, or 0.54 percent, closing at 37,858.11.
   The index has risen 725.43 points, or 1.95 percent, in the last
four days alone, and 1,964.53 points, or 5.47 percent, since Nov.
20.
   On Wednesday, ``trust fund managers were placing large orders,
which contributed to the Nikkei's advance,'' said a dealer at Nikko
Securities Co., speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Dealers said investors were reassured by an Economic Planning
Agency announcement that Japan's real gross national product grew
2.9 percent in the July-September quarter from the previous quarter.
   The rise in inflation-adjusted GNP was equivalent to a 12.2
percent annual growth rate, the highest since 1973, the agency said.
   Large capital shares and blue-chip electricals remained at the
center of trading activity, but investors also were turning their
interest to sectors that had been lagging in the last few weeks,
such as textiles and food issues, dealers said.
   ``Trading is becoming more active and broader,'' said the Nikko
Securities dealer. ``I expect the bullish trend to continue for
some time.''
   In the currency market, the dollar closed at 144.13 yen, up 0.38
yen from Wednesday's close of 143.75 yen. It opened at 143.95 yen
and ranged between 143.94 yen and 144.33 yen.
   The dollar now has gained 1.23 yen in the last five days.
   Currency dealers said the dollar opened higher in Tokyo after
gains on overseas markets, and continued to rise on buying by
insurance and trust banks.
   Dollar-buying was triggered by warnings by the East German
military that it would not tolerate attempts by citizens to seize
munitions from security installations, the dealers said. They said
fleeting worries that the military might block the country's reform
movement led some to sell West German marks.
   Investors had been buying marks in a belief that West Germany
would benefit from economic and other reforms in the East bloc.
   Takashi Kanagami, manager of foreign exchange dealings at
Mitsubishi Trust and Banking Corp., said the West German mark would
strengthen further if next week's European Economic Community
summit decides to help East European countries.
</TEXT>
