<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SEC-Macmillan     12-07 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Macmillan,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Macmillan Chairman, 2 Execs Settle SEC Disclosure Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chairman of publishing giant
Macmillan Inc. and two current executives of the company have
settled Securities and Exchange Commission charges alleging they
filed misleading documents.
   The three _ Edward P. Evans, Macmillan's chairman from 1980 to
1988; William F. Reilly, Macmillan's chief operating officer; and
Beverly C. Chell, the publisher's general counsel _ were accused of
filing misleading or incomplete documents concerning the purpose
for buying 1.2 million Macmillan shares for a company employee
stock option plan in 1987.
   In a civil complaint filed Wednesday at federal court in
Washington, the SEC sought an injunction to prohibit the trio from
violating federal securities rules.
   But simultaneously with the charges, the three _ without
admitting or denying wrongdoing _ settled and consented to an
injunction barring them from violating securities disclosure rules.
   A spokesman for Macmillan in New York did not have an immediate
comment on the settlement Wednesday evening.
   ``We believe it to be the first action the commission has
brought in a filing by an ESOP, which are increasingly being used
as a takeover defense,'' said Herbert F. Janick III, an SEC
attorney in the case.
   The SEC complaint alleged that beginning in May 1987, Evans,
Reilly and Chell began to develop a plan to recapitalize Macmillan
in anticipation of a possible hostile takeover.
   Evans later headed a Macmillan management group that lost a
takeover battle for Macmillan to British media lord Robert Maxwell.
   In 1988, a Delaware court blocked a restructuring Macmillan
proposed as a defense against an unwanted $1.9 billion bid from the
Robert Bass Group. Bass later dropped his bid after competing
offers were launched by the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
&amp; Co. and Maxwell.
   According to the SEC complaint, as part of the alleged
recapitalization proposal, Evans, Reilly and Chell caused
Macmillan's employee stock ownership plan (ESOP) to buy 1.2 million
Macmillan shares, which was more than 5 percent of the
then-outstanding stock.
   By law, persons or companies acquiring 5 percent or more of a
company must disclose their stake and state their intentions in an
SEC document known as a 13-D.
   But the SEC charged that the 13-D filed by the trio did not
disclose ``that a purpose of the acquisition was to further the
recapitalization.''
   Evans' lawyer, Richard M. Phillips, issued a written statement
concerning the settlement, which said: ``Since the Macmillan ESOP's
purchase of Macmillan shares was extremely profitable to Macmillan
employees, it satisfied the stated purpose of the transaction to
allow `employees to acquire stock ownership interest in the
company.'''
   ``Mr. Evans is pleased that the (SEC)'s action, alleging that a
further statement of purpose was necessary, could be settled
without spending the time and resources that would be required to
litigate the commission's factual allegations and legal theories,''
the statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
