<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0919EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SEC-ShortSellers     12-07 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Short Sellers,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Says It's Ready and Waiting to Catch Illegal Short Sellers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said it
is ready to prosecute market manipulation by the practice of short
selling _ but the evidence isn't always there.
   ``We're committed to identify short selling abuse wherever it
may occur,'' said John Sturc, of the SEC's Enforcement Division
told a House panel Wednesday.
   But he and another SEC official also told a subcommittee of the
House Committee on Governmental Affairs ``short selling also
provides the market with two vital benefits.''
   Richard G. Ketchum, head of the SEC's Division of Market
Regulation, told the panel those benefits are market liquidity and
price efficiency which help prevent volatility _ the steep price
rises and drops that can panic investors and send the market
plunging.
   But Sturc, an associate director of the enforcement division
noted that he and Ketchum were ``not here to defend or attack short
selling.''
   In short-selling, an investor tries to take advantage of an
anticipated drop in the price of a company's stock. The investor
borrows stock from a broker and sells it, hoping to replace it with
stock purchased at a lower price. The investor's profit would come
from the difference between the price obtained for the borrowed
stock and the lower price paid to replace it.
   Short selling is not illegal and stockholders are allowed to
lend or borrow stock they are holding for customers, if the stock
has been purchased on margin _ the buyer did not put up the full
purchase price.
   But in testimony last week before the commerce, consumer and
monetary affairs subcommittee, some witnesses complained some
professional short-sellers often break the rules to get a stock to
drop quickly and spread false rumors about a company, its products
or its management.
   That testimony was about the over-the-counter market, which does
not have the same rules governing short sales as do the stock
exchanges. The National Association of Securities Dealers, a
private, self-regulating group oversees the over-the-counter market.
   Sturc, however, noted that the SEC considers all complaints of
short selling abuses, but often investigations ``do not lead to
sustainable evidence of violations of the antifraud provisions of
the federal securities laws.''
   At the beginning of the hearing the subcommittee chairman, Rep.
Doug Barnard Jr., D-Ga., said he was not sure ``that the SEC is on
the same wavelength as the subcommittee.''
   But Sturc explained that often when companies complain they are
the victims of short sellers spreading false rumors, there is no
proof where the rumors originated or whether it has had an effect
of the company's stock.
   ``We have a strong enforcement interest,'' said Sturc, adding
``I regret to say, Mr. Chairman, we have not received allegations
of misconduct to quite the degree of specificity as has been
presented to the subcommittee by several of the witnesses. We would
be happy to receive them. My job is to try find violators and catch
them and that's what I like to do.''
   After the session, Barnard told reporters that the hearings were
``not a witchhunt as far as the SEC or NASD were concerned. I
thought there was good explanations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-07-89 0923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Germany-Phones     12-07 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Phones,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Mobile Phone License Awarded to International Consortium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany today awarded a
license to build and operate a private mobile telephone system that
analysts estimate could be worth more than $5 billion to a
four-nation consortium.
   Led by Mannesmann AG, the group also includes Pacific Telesis
Group of the United States, Cable and Wireless PLC of Britain,
Lyonnaise des Eaux of France and Deutsche Genossenschaftsbank, a
major West German bank.
   The Post Ministry chose the consortium from a large field of
contending groups, which included several of West Germany's largest
companies and international telecommunications concerns.
   The private network, called D-2, will compete with the Post
Ministry's own D-1 system. It will be the second digital cellular
system in West Germany. The German government now operates an
analog cellular network and plans to build its own digital system.
   Mannesmann Kienzle GmbH, the electronics subsidiary of the West
German engineering concern, will hold a majority stake in the
consortium, called Mannesmann Mobilfunk GmbH.
   Analysts have said that operating a mobile phone network in
densely-populated West Germany will be an extremely profitable
business in the 1990s. The value of the license has been estimated
at 2 billion to 10 billion marks, or the equivalent of about $1.1
billion to $5.6 billion.
   Mannesmann has said construction of the network will require
initial investments of $2.2 billion.
   Rumors that the consortium won the bidding war spurred a rally
in Mannesmann stock in recent days. Since last Thursday, Mannesmann
stock has surged some 25 percent to close at 340.00 marks a share,
or about $192, on Wednesday.
   The decision by Post Minister Christian Schwarz-Schilling was
based on a recommendation of a special advisory panel that ranked
the Mannesmann consortium first among the bidders.
   Pacific Telesis, which holds a 26 percent interest in the
consortium, has not put a dollar value on its share of the license,
but analysts estimate it could increase the per-share value of the
company's stock by $3 or $4 as the financial market reacts to the
announcement, company spokeswoman Amy Damianakes said.
   ``We view the cellular business as an `Alexander Graham Bell'
opportunity,'' Sam Ginn, PacTel's president and chief executive
officer, said in a news release today.
   ``This license expands our reach into the international cellular
market and provides significant potential for increasing shareowner
value during the 1990s,'' Ginn said.
   Pacific Telesis, one of the ``Baby Bells'' created after the
breakup of American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., has a contract with
the consortium to design, engineer and manage the new system's
construction. PacTel's 26 percent interest covers about 16 million
potential cellular subscribers, compared with its nearly 30 million
potential subscribers in the United States, Ginn said.
   Other partners in the consortium are Mannesmann AG, Deutsche
Genossenschaftsbank, Cable and Wireless PLC, Lyonnaise des Eaux and
the National Associations of Electrical and Automobile Trades.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
