<FIRST>u f PM-ChryslerMoves 1stLd-Writethru   12-07 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler Moves, 1st Ld - Writethru,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Selling Subsidiary, Heading Back to Roots</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, Paulson has...with 3 new grafs to UPDATE
with comments. Picks up 8th graf, On Oct. 1...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. says it wants to return to its
roots, and some industry analysts are praising the move.
   The nation's third-largest automaker announced Wednesday that it
has put its Chrysler Technologies Corp. subsidiary on the block,
sharply scaling back the company's diversification drive of earlier
this decade.
   Chrysler said it has hired First Boston Corp. to advise it on
the sale of the aerospace and military technologies division. It
did not disclose what price it might seek.
   Chrysler Technologies is comprised of Gulfstream Aerospace
Corp., a corporate jet maker that was acquired for $637 million in
1985; Electrospace Systems Inc., a maker of defense and electronics
products and systems bought for $367 million in 1987; and Airborne
Systems Inc., formed in January 1989 by combining military
aviation-related functions of Gulfstream and Electrospace.
   The vast majority of Chrysler Technologies' 1988 revenue of $1.3
billion stems from Gulfstream, said John Stellman, a spokesman for
Chrysler Technologies. Total Chrysler Corp. revenues in 1988 were
$35.47 billion.
   Chrysler also said Wednesday that Gulfstream founder and
Chairman Allen Paulson resigned from the Chrysler board of
directors and took a leave of absence from Gulfstream to pursue a
potential purchase of all or some of Chrysler Technologies.
   Paulson, in a meeting Wednesday with Gulfstream employees in
Savannah, Ga., said he mainly was interested in acquiring
Gulfstream but would make a bid for all of Chrysler Technologies if
necessary.
   Paulson told the workers that if he made a successful bid for
Chrysler Technologies, he subsequently would attempt to sell
Electrospace Systems and Airborne Systems.
   He said he believes he will need about a week to prepare his
offer but is working with banks about possible financing.
   Since Oct. 1, Chrysler has been involved in an aggressive
cost-cutting program to slash at least $1 billion from its budget
by the end of next year, including the elimination of about 2,300,
or 8 percent, of its salaried work force.
   In September, Chrysler sold about half of its stake in the
Japanese automaker Mitsubishi Motors Corp., gaining about $310
million after taxes.
   Sales of Chrysler cars and light trucks for the year through
Nov. 30 were 6.4 percent behind last year's pace, reflecting an
industrywide slowdown.
   Chrysler said the Chrysler Technologies sale had been under
consideration for some time.
   ``We've had some informal inquiries,'' said spokesman Steve
Harris. ``But we've never had any firm offers.''
   Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca said the vehicle market is going
to be fiercely competitive in the future.
   ``We intend to go head-to-head with the Toyotas and Hondas of
the world as well as anybody else in the market,'' he said. ``And
this is the right time to take this step.
   ``The only way to succeed in this kind of environment is to
concentrate all our energies and resources on the task of
satisfying our customers and insuring that our dealers have the
best line of cars and trucks we can possibly produce,'' Iacocca
said.
   Chrysler shares rose 12{ cents to close at $19.12{ a share
Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Although Chrysler Technologies accounted for a relatively small
chunk of the parent company's overall earnings, analysts said the
businesses had been acquired as a way of helping diversify from the
cyclical auto industry.
   Harris said Chrysler Technologies had about $149 million in
pre-tax profits last year and the company had projected earnings of
about $121 million this year. Chrysler Corp. had after-tax profits
of $1.05 billion in 1988.
   The company said the hoped-for sale was unrelated to cash needs,
but analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International
Inc. of New York questioned that assertion.
   ``I don't see how they can say this isn't for cash,'' she said.
``It just seems like a big contradiction. They made the
acquisitions so they can be less dependent on the auto industry.''
   When Chrysler announced the Gulfstream acquisition in 1985,
Iacocca called it ``an important step in our long-range plan to
diversify into high-tech industries like aerospace and
electronics.''
   Analyst Mary Anne Sudol of Fitch Investors Service Inc. of New
York said the decision to sell Chrysler Technologies was a sound
one. ``Since they bought it, the world has changed,'' she said.
   ``In the current thawing in the Cold War and the anticipated
cuts in defense budgets, an operation like that, which is small
relative to Chrysler's size, makes less and less sense,'' she added.
   Chrysler Technologies has about 8,300 employees, Harris said.
Gulfstream has about 5,000 workers, Electrospace has about 2,000
and Chrysler Technologies Airborne Systems has about 1,300.
</TEXT>
