<FIRST>r f PM-PhelpsDodge 1stLd-Writethru   12-07 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phelps Dodge, 1st Ld-Writethru,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phelps Dodge Announces $375 Million in Pre-tax Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT day of week.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phelps Dodge Corp. says it will take pre-tax
charges of about $375 million in the fourth quarter to write down
the value of certain assets that have been idle for several years.
   After deferred tax benefits, these charges will reduce net
income in the quarter by about $250 million, or $7 per common
share, the copper company said Wednesday, adding it still expected
to report a profit for the period.
   ``The decision to take these charges at this time is unrelated
to our outlook for copper and other market factors _ we remain
bullish on the future,'' Douglas C. Yearly, chairman and chief
executive officer, said in a statement.
   Yearly noted that the Phoenix-based company ``has achieved
record results for each of 1987, 1988 and the first three quarters
of 1989, and there is a continuing strong market for copper and
most of our other products.''
   Included in the charges are about $145 million for reserve
provisions for the Morenci smelter, about $50 million for the New
Cornelia Mine, Concentrator and Smelter in Ajo, and ``certain other
facilities that have been rendered obsolete by environmental
requirements or other economic considerations.''
   The charges also reflect the reduction of about $115 million in
assets stemming from the company's decision to indefinately defer
any further pre-operating mine development work on the Dos Pobres
underground copper deposit near Safford.
   ``These assets are assets that have been idle since 1984,'' said
Thomas M. Foster, a company vice president. ``Consequently, this is
a non-cash charge to earnings that we feel we are not going to
reactivate in the forseeable future.''
   Richard Moolick, who retired as president of Phelps Dodge in
1984, questioned the move.
   ``The Ajo mine, at the prices we've been experiencing, is a
viable property,'' Moolick said. He closed the mine in 1984 when
faced with plunging copper prices.
   However, Lew Alton, a managing general partner of the investment
banking firm L.H. Alton of San Francisco, praised the action.
   ``You figure they have new people at the helm, earnings are
phenomenal ... and you get the opportunity to clean up the balance
sheet. Why not do it when you have the chance?'' he said.
   Phelps Dodge's net income for the quarter ended Sept. 30 was
$115.4 million, or $3.26 a share, compared with net income of $93.3
million, or $2.53 a share, for the same quarter last year.
   In addition to its copper operations, Phelps Dodge produces
carbon black, fabricates steel wheels and rims for trucks and
manufactures magnet wire.
</TEXT>
