<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybeans Drift Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures were lower and soybeans were mixed
at the opening today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices fell as a result of the release yesterday of the
National Weather Service's six- to 10-day forecast. The outlook
calls for increased chances for rain in the winter wheat region.
   The lack of export business is putting pressure on soybean
futures, although strong demand for soybean oil may be a boost to
prices.
   Corn futures drifted lower on follow-through from the weak
closing yesterday, with little news to stimulate buying, said
analyst Frank Kouba of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   At the open, wheat was 1} cents lower to \ cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.08 a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 1{ cents lower with December at $2.35 cents a bushel; oats
were 1 cent lower to \ cent higher with December at $1.43} a
bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to 3 cents lower with January at
$5.78 a bushel.
   Livestock futures were lower and pork futures mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Pork belly futures drifted lower after opening higher, with
profit-taking wiping out the earlier gains. Movement of bellies
into storage and falling belly prices also put pressure on futures.
   Livestock futures were slightly higher due to concerns over cold
temperatures in the Plains, which could affect feeding.
   Live cattle were .17 cent lower to .10 cent higher with December
at 75.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent lower to .13
cent higher with January at 82.90 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent
lower to .25 cent higher with December at 51.50 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .90 cent lower to .10 cent higher with
February at 55.55 cents a pound.
   Livestock and pork futures settled mixed in Wednesday's trading.
