<FIRST>u f AM-Germany-Phones Bjt   12-07 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Phones, Bjt,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four-Nation Group To Build Mobile Phone Network Worth Billions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-nation consortium Thursday won
the rights to build and run a private mobile telephone network in
West Germany, a license that some analysts say could amount to a $6
billion gold mine in the 1990s.
   The group led by Mannesmann AG also includes Pacific Telesis of
the United States, Cable and Wireless PLC of Britain, Lyonnaise des
Eaux of France and Deutsche Genossenschaftsbank, a major West
German bank.
   West Germany's current mobile phone network, operated by the
government, is suffering from severe capacity restraints.
   A new network in the densely populated, economically strong
country is considered certain to be a highly profitable enterprise
in the next decade. But many analysts warn that implementation
could face unforeseen delays or obstacles dueto changing regulation
and increasing competition.
   ``We view the cellular business as an `Alexander Graham Bell'
opportunity,'' Sam Ginn, chairman and chief executive officer of
Pacific Telesis, said in a news release issued from the company's
San Francisco headquarters.
   ``This license expands our reach into the international cellular
market and provides significant potential for increasing
shareholder value in the 1990s,'' Ginn said.
   The Post Ministry chose the consortium from a large field of
contenders that included several of West Germany's largest
companies and international telecommunications concerns.
   The private network, called D-2, will compete with the Post
Ministry's own D-1 system.
   Plans call for Mannesmann and the Postal Service to start
building separate networks in West Germany in 1991 and complete
them by 1994, Post Minister Christian Schwarz-Schilling told
reporters. The two systems will be integrated into a larger
European network so the same cellular mobile phones can be used all
over Europe.
   That consideration is significant because of plans by the
12-nation European Community, known as the Common Market, to drop
internal trade barriers by 1992 and create a unified market.
   Schwarz-Schilling said the new project will require investments
of $1.1 billion to $2.3 billion.
   The private network should break even by 1995, he said. Analysts
say D-2 could have 500,000 or more users by that time.
   Mannesmann Kienzle GmbH, the electronics subsidiary of the West
German engineering concern, will hold a 51 percent stake in the
consortium, called Mannesmann Mobilfunk GmbH and based in
Duesseldorf, West Germany.
   The final license agreement with Mannesmann will be signed in
January, Schwarz-Schilling said.
   Pacific Telesis will hold 26 percent of the consortium, DG-Bank
10 percent, Cable and Wireless 5 percent, and Lyonnaise des Eaux
2.5 percent. The remaining 5.5 percent will be held by various
smaller shareholders.
   Other bidders for the license included German heavyweights like
Bayerische Motoren Werke AG, the maker of BMW cars; Axel Springer
Verlag AG, a major West German publisher; and several big
industrial firms.
   Under a formula used by U.S. analysts to value mobile phone
licenses, the order could be worth $6 billion. But others said that
amount is too high because it does not consider necessary outlays
and risks.
   George Verghese, electronics analyst at Deutsche Bank AG in
London, cautioned that a Europe-wide network could be delayed by
disagreements within the European Community.
   He also said growing competition in coming years is likely to
put pressure on profit margins.
   ``On paper it all looks wonderful, but the implementation could
be delayed,'' Verghese said.
   Pacific Telesis shares were up by 75 cents at $48.50 a share in
late New York Stock Exchange trading.
   But Mannesmann shares dropped by nearly 2.8 percent in domestic
trading after the announcement, on what traders called
profit-taking following a recent runup in the stock due to
speculation about the phone license.
   ``Everybody got carried away by the idea that Mannesmann got a
license for printing money, but for the next three years we will
see only costs,'' said Beate von der Seipen, a London stock analyst.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
