<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SalmonFishingWoes     12-07 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salmon Fishing Woes,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lake Michigan Fishing Businesses Struggling With Salmon Die-Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the customers on Denny
Grinwald's Lake Michigan charter boat this summer put the hard
times facing the lake's sport fishing businesses into painfully
clear perspective.
   ``He said, `Captain, I understand there's bad news and good news
on the lake. ... The bad news is I can't eat the fish I catch. The
good news is I'm not going to be able to catch one.'''
   Grinwald, president of the Michigan Charter Boat Association,
isn't laughing.
   What was, by U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service estimates, the
cornerstone of a $1.6 billion Great Lakes fishery for Michigan in
1985 has weakened dramatically.
   A bacterial disease seems to be decimating the lake's
bread-and-butter sport fish, chinook salmon. And this summer, the
National Wildlife Federation issued a controversial warning that
chemical contamination was making the fish a risky meal.
   Low catches and fish consumption warnings drove 140 Michigan
charter boats off the lake this year, leaving 876 operators where
two years ago there were more than 1,000, Grinwald said Wednesday.
   More are expected to leave by spring.
   ``I know at least six boats from Ludington that will go to New
York next year,'' Ludington charter captain Jim Lacko said.
``That's bad. When you lose charter boats, you start losing motel
rooms.''
   Lacko estimates he lost half of his business in the past two
years. ``The fishing is just not there,'' he said.
   Wisconsin's creel surveys show a 50 percent drop in the number
of chinook salmon caught, said Mike Hansen, a Wisconsin Department
of Natural Resources fish specialist in Madison.
   Michigan surveys map a drop in the amount of time sport
fishermen spent on the lake _ down from 3.5 million hours spent at
nine ports in the mid-1980s to an estimated 1.8 million hours this
year, said Gerald Rakoczy, Michigan Department of Natural Resources
biologist in Charlevoix.
   The chinook catch alone in the region from Ludington to
Frankfort _ along the middle western coast of Lake Michigan along
Michigan's Lower Peninsula _ dropped from 242,000 fish in May and
August of 1986 to 34,000 chinook the same period this year,
Grinwald said.
   Chinook salmon, introduced into Lake Michigan more than 25 years
ago to control an alien alewife population, are the dominant sport
fish in the lake and make up more than half the catch, according to
Wisconsin record keepers.
   The salmon sport fishing industry supports not only charter
operations but has helped revitalize many coastal towns.
   ``I've always felt the economic clout of the Great Lakes sport
fishery is greatly undervalued,'' said James Kitchell, a University
of Wisconsin-Madison researcher. ``You see potted geraniums on the
pilings in Grand Haven (Mich.) where before that was nothing; you
get boatels in marinas. It is the single most remarkable thing
that's happened in fishery management.''
   Dramatic declines in the salmon population can only be bad for
the coastal economy, Kitchell said.
   Wright said he is unsure the lake again will host the fishery _
created by overstocking of chinook salmon and an abundance of
alewife _ that kept charter boat operators booked solid in the
early 1980s.
   ``Some of the marginal operations obviously are going to drop
out,'' he said. ``The hard core _ 270 to 400 charter operations _
are still going to be there. They'll fish for what is available.''
   Lake Michigan is still a good place to fish, Grinwald said.
``It's just not the fantastic, incredible fishery it was.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-07 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Futures Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower in
sluggish trading Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The slide in wheat prices was due to the release Wednesday of
the National Weather Service's six- to 10-day forecast, which calls
for precipitation in the winter wheat crop areas, said analyst
Susan Leighty of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Wheat futures received little support from news the U.S.
Department of Agriculture has approved an offer by the Soviet Union
for 410,000 metric tons of wheat under the department's Export
Enhancement Program.
   Under the program, private exporters can sell U.S. commodities
at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in some markets and
collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Corn futures traded in a narrow range, finishing lower as
professionals and commission houses liquidated their long positions.
   Soybean prices continue to be weighed down by a lack of export
business and continuing good planting conditions in South America.
   Ms. Leighty said that overall, futures prices may have been held
down by the lack of announcements from the grain talks between the
United States and the Soviet Union. The first round of negotiations
in Moscow to reach a new long-term grain pact ended Thursday. The
two sides plan to meet again in February.
   At the close, wheat prices were { cent to 2{ cents lower with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.08 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 2{ cents lower with December at $2.36 a bushel; oats
were a \ cent to a { cent lower with December at $1.44 a bushel;
soybeans were 2{ cents to 7\ cents lower with January at $5.75{ a
bushel.
</TEXT>
