<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-GrandMet     12-07 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Grand Met,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Met's Profit Up 23 Percent in Fiscal Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC reported Thursday that its
net profit jumped 23 percent during its fiscal year, boosted by
higher revenue from its food, beverage and retailing operations.
   The British conglomerate said its profit for the year ended
Sept. 30 rose to 508 million pounds, or around $823 million, from
412 million pounds, or $667 million, the year before.
   Per-share earnings increased 18.6 percent to 55.6 pence, or 87
cents, from 46.9 pence, or 74 cents.
   Grand Met bought Pillsbury Co. of the United States for $5.75
billion earlier this year.
   Revenue for the year soared 54.2 percent to 9.3 billion pounds,
or $14.6 billion, from 6.03 billion pounds, or $9.5 billion.
   The gains included proceeds from the sale of the company's
Intercontinental Hotels and London Clubs in December 1988 for more
than 500 million pounds, or $810 million.
   The greatest impact on the company's results came from
Pillsbury, which contributed 2.5 billion pounds, or $3.9 billion,
to total revenue.
   Grand Met said intense activity to integrate Pillsbury has
included the sale of non-strategic businesses, such as its Bumble
Bee and Van de Kamp foods operations.
   ``All parts of the business are performing strongly and
management morale is high,'' the company said.
   Burger King, the fast-food chain which was owned by Pillsbury,
contributed 76 million pounds, or $119 million, to Grand Met's
operating profit. The parent company said it will take time for the
benefits of a recent restructuring and quality improvement program
to bear fruit, but ``the fundamentals of this business are very
sound.''
   Grand Met said sales from its food businesses, including those
that were part of Pillsbury, were strong in all divisions and are
expected to climb 5 percent in the current quarter.
   But the slowdown in the British economy has been especially
evident in the company's liquor sales over the last 12 to 15
months, said Grand Met Chairman Allen Sheppard.
   The company likely will make further acquisitions and sales in
the coming year but it is now prepared to consolidate its current
businesses in food, beverages and retailing, Sheppard said.
   Grand Met didn't report quarterly or half-year results. It is
not required to do so under British law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
