<DOCNO> AP891207-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-GTE-TakeoverDefense     12-07 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GTE-Takeover Defense,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>GTE Board Adopts Anti-Takeover Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GTE Corp.'s board of directors adopted a
plan Thursday to protect the company from hostile takeovers.
   The plan will allow shareholders to buy discounted stock in GTE
if anyone buys 20 percent of the Stamford-based telecommunications
company without GTE's permission. Under certain conditions, they
could also buy stock in an acquiring company at a discount if GTE
disapproved of the merger.
   ``The plan is not aimed at preventing a takeover of GTE,'' said
James L. Johnson, chairman and chief executive officer. ``It is
designed to encourage a buyer to negotiate with the board and to
prevent abusive share-accumulation tactics. The rights will help
the board ensure that all GTE shareholders realize the value of
their investment in the company.''
   Johnson said he was not aware of any efforts to take over the
company.
   GTE said similar rights plans have been adopted by other
telecommunications companies, including Americtech, Bell Atlantic
Corp. and Nynex Corp.
   GTE had combined revenues and sales of $16.5 billion and net
income of $1.2 billion last year from its telecommunications,
lighting and precision materials businesses.
</TEXT>
