<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Navistar     12-07 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Navistar,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truck Maker Takes Fourth-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navistar International Corp. on Thursday reported
a $13 million fourth-quarter loss and said reduced industrywide
demand for trucks and higher costs for purchased components
contributed to the decline.
   The truck and diesel engine maker said it lost 8 cents a share
on sales of $1 billion compared with a profit for the year-earlier
period of $82 million or 29 cents a share on sales of $1.2 billion.
   For fiscal 1989, which ended Oct. 31, Navistar earned $87
million or 23 cents a share on sales of $4.2 billion, down from
1988 annual profits of $244 million or 84 cents a share on sales of
$4.3 billion, the company said in a statement.
   Navistar Chairman James C. Cotting blamed the fourth-quarter
performance on reduced demand for medium and heavy trucks, higher
costs for components and lower sales of service parts and diesel
engines to other vehicle makers.
   Annual earnings were lowered by the ``excess costs'' of adding
27 new truck models and of phasing in a new paint system at
Navistar's Springfield, Ohio, plant, the company said. Navistar
spokesman Bill Greenhouse said the company underestimated the cost
of introducing the new models.
   The company also said it expects to post a 1990 first-quarter
loss, because of ``lower truck and engine sales, increased material
and component costs, and continued intense price discounting by
truck manufacturers.''
</TEXT>
