<FIRST>r f AM-Gulfstream-Paulson     12-07 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulfstream-Paulson,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paulson Says Bid for Gulfstream to be Ready Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulfstream Aerospace Corp. Chairman Allen
E. Paulson says he will be ready in about a week to present a bid
to buy back the company he founded.
   Chrysler Corp. announced Wednesday it plans to sell its Chrysler
Technologies Corp. subsidiary, which includes Savannah-based
Gulfstream, acquired by the nation's No. 3 automaker in 1985.
   Paulson immediately resigned from the Chrysler board of
directors and took a leave of absence from Gulfstream to pursue a
potential purchase of all or some of Chrysler Technologies.
   He told a gathering of Gulfstream workers in Savannah Wednesday
that he is mainly interested in acquiring Gulfstream, though he
would try to buy all of Chrysler Technologies if that's what is
necessary to get the corporate aircraft maker he founded.
   Paulson told the workers that if he made a successful bid for
Chrysler Technologies, he would subsequently attempt to sell the
other parts of that company _ Electrospace Systems and Airborne
Systems.
   Paulson said he believes he will need about a week to prepare
his offer, and will then return to work at Gulfstream.
   ``I have a contract (with Chrysler) to fulfill a year at
Gulfstream,'' he said.
   Paulson ruled out the possibility of a management-led buyout of
Gulfstream financed through bonds. ``I am working with banks. I am
interested in bank financing and putting my own assets to work,''
he said.
   Chrysler paid $637 million for Gulfstream in 1985. The vast
majority of Chrysler Technologies' 1988 revenue of $1.3 billion
stems from Gulfstream, said John Stellman, a spokesman for Chrysler
Technologies. Total Chrysler Corp. revenues in 1988 were $35.5
billion.
   Chrysler spokesman Steve Harris said the company would consider
selling all of Chrysler Technologies or just part, depending on the
offers it receives.
   ``Chrysler would look at the best return for Chrysler
shareholders,'' he said.
   Harris said Chrysler already has received several inquiries for
part or all of Chrysler Technologies, but ``at this time we do not
have any firm offers on the table.''
   Chrysler said it has hired First Boston Corp. to advise it on
the sale of the aerospace and military technologies division. It
did not disclose what price it might seek.
   John Zimmerman, president of Aviation Data Service in Wichita,
Kan., an aviation information and consulting service, said
Paulson's chances of acquiring Gulfstream are excellent.
   ``Mr. Paulson is a very brilliant man with insight to the
aviation industry. It is not inconceivable that somebody would work
with Mr. Paulson in financing a deal,'' he said.
   Chrysler Technologies' Electrospace Systems and Airborne Systems
divisions specialize in the production of military reconnaissance
and surveillance equipment.
</TEXT>
