<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-JingleJangle     12-07 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jingle Jangle,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diet Pepsi Jingle Becomes Battle Hymn in Cola Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diet Pepsi's new ``The Right One'' advertising
jingle has become a battle hymn for the cola wars, with the ad
agency for rival Diet Coke disputing who owns the idea for the tune.
   The song was picked up for Diet Pepsi after a similar version
apparently was offered to rival Diet Coke as well as Budweiser beer.
   Coke's ad agency, Lintas:New York, complains that it should have
been given the chance to buy the song before it was offered to
anyone else, while Pepsi is calling the protest a simple publicity
stunt by its rival cola maker.
   Stone Roberts, executive vice president of Lintas:New York, said
the song used in the Diet Pepsi television spot was written last
year for Diet Coke, although it never was used publicly.
   Roberts said he fired off a complaint letter to Sunday
Productions, the New York music house that developed the song,
after hearing the similar song in a Diet Pepsi ad during the
Thanksgiving weekend.
   ``I'd like to believe they (Pepsi) didn't know it was ours and
didn't buy it in a direct attempt to copy the industry leader,''
Roberts said Thursday.
   But Hilary Lipsitz, president of Sunday Productions, said it was
ludicrous for Coke or its ad agency to say they own the song.
   Lipsitz said he offered the song to other companies, including
Budweiser brewer Anheuser-Busch Cos., after Coke rejected it for a
possible ad campaign dubbed ``The Real One.''
   ``There was no interest from Coca-Cola. It was our song,''
Lipsitz said Thursday. ``It's pretty much as if they came to Irving
Berlin and said, `Write me a song' and didn't use it. Whose song
would it be?''
   Lipsitz said the tune was among several he presented to Pepsi.
   Roberts said Diet Coke wanted a song as a back-up to its current
ad campaign ``if and when the day came where we needed a
substitute.''
   ``Sunday Productions brought back some pieces of music developed
from our concept,'' Roberts said, adding that Sunday was paid a
$10,000 ``demo fee.'' A commercial was prepared and then ``put on
the shelf'' for possible use later, he said.
   Roberts said Lintas should have been given the opportunity to
buy the song outright before it was offered to anyone else. The
agency is considering legal action, he said.
   Officials at the ad agency BBDO Worldwide who work on the Diet
Pepsi account, did not immediately return telephone calls Thursday.
   Becky Madeira, a spokeswoman at Pepsi Cola's Purchase, N.Y.,
headquarters called the complaints a publicity stunt by
Atlanta-based rival Coke.
   ``It's hard to find any other reason for all of this,'' she
said. ``I understand the press had copies of the letters of
complaint before the principals.''
   Ms. Madeira said Diet Pepsi has been using the ``Right One''
slogan since August but hadn't heard any complaints until the
television commercial appeared last month. She also said Pepsi's
application for a trademark for ``The Right One'' was made in July
and drew no objection from Coke.
   She said it is not unusual for companies to choose from several
songs when considering an ad campaign.
   Ms. Madeira also said Pepsi looks for music that reflects the
character of its products, so it would be pointless to seek a song
belonging to a competitor.
   ``It's hard to imagine that would make sense for either
company,'' she said. ``Why would you advertise the personality of a
competitor's product?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0243 </DOCNO>
