<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-07 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Higher In Dull Dealings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed marginally higher against most
foreign currencies Thursday, but trading was light and uneventful.
   Gold prices scored large gains in U.S. dealings after finishing
somewhat higher in Europe. Technical factors were cited for driving
prices higher.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
ended at $410 a troy ounce, up $5.10 an ounce from late Wednesday.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a troy ounce of gold
bullion at $409.60 as of 4 p.m. EST, $5 higher than Wednesday's
late bid.
   Traders said the dollar traded within a very narrow range
throughout the session, closing near the highs of the day partly on
technical factors.
   Most dealers were awaiting the Labor Department's release on
Friday of unemployment data for November. The consensus is that the
report will show an increase of roughly 150,000 jobs, lower than
the 233,000 jobs added during the previous month, and an
unemployment rate of 5.4 percent.
   Unfavorable employment data indicate the economy is slowing and
could help encourage the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates.
Lower interest rates are bearish for the dollar because they
decrease the value of dollar-denominated securities.
   ``Everybody is convinced that U.S. (interest) rates will go
down,'' said Stephen Flanagan, a vice president at Manufacturers
Hanover Trust Co.
   Separately, the West German mark continued to flex its muscle.
Traders noted the mark remained extremely strong, particularly
against the Japanese yen.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar edged up 0.38 Japanese yen to a closing 144.13
yen. Later in London, it was quoted at 144.33 yen. In New York, the
dollar closed at 144.31 yen, up from 144.03 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.5750, from $1.5765 late
Wednesday. But in New York it cost $1.5780 to buy one pound, more
expensive than Wednesday's $1.5765.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday included: 1.7725 West German marks, up from 1.7660;
1.5900 Swiss francs, up from 1.5895; 6.0515 French francs, up from
6.0335; 1.1618 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1612, and 1,307.25
Italian lire, up from 1.303.25.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.7720 West German marks, up from 1.7648; 1.5920 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5875; 6.0560 French francs, up from 6.0315;
1.9935 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0010; 1,308.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,301.15, and 1.1625 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1602.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $404.25 a troy ounce
from $402.25 bid late Wednesday. In Zurich, the metal rose to a
closing bid of $404.00, from $403.75 bid late Wednesday. Earlier in
Hong Kong, gold rose $4.30 to close at a bid $405.01.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $5.60 a
troy ounce from $5.56 bid late Wednesday. On New York's Comex,
silver for current delivery closed at $5.623 a troy ounce, up from
Wednesday's $5.555.
</TEXT>
