<FIRST>r f BC-ComputerSlump-Cuts     12-07 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Computer Slump-Cuts,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Computer Companies Cut Jobs in 1989</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Computer Slump, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the computer makers that cut jobs in 1989
through layoffs or voluntary separation incentives:
   International Business Machines Corp.: In September announced
separation incentive program to eliminate 600 to 1,000 jobs. In
December announced new incentive program to eliminate 10,000 more
jobs. No layoffs.
   Unisys Corp.: In August announced plan to cut 6,000 to 7,000
jobs. In October raised number to about 8,000, composed of 6,300
layoffs and 1,700 reductions through voluntary resignations and
early retirement.
   Wang Laboratories Inc.: Laid off 2,200 employees by the end of
September. Last month announced plans for 2,000 more layoffs.
   Amdahl Corp.: In November announced the layoff of 400 workers in
Sunnyvale, Calif., about 5 percent of its work force.
   Digital Equipment Corp.: In September announced elimination of
700 manufacturing jobs in New Hampshire and Massachusetts. Offered
retraining and relocation to all affected workers. Anticipated
about 200 would instead choose a package of separation incentives.
Froze salaries for six months. No layoffs.
   Control Data Corp.: In April announced it would exit the
supercomputer business and take other steps that would cost 3,100
jobs.
   Bull HN Information Systems Inc.: In January the company, then
named Honeywell Bull Inc., announced plans to cut 1,600 jobs
through a combination of layoffs and attrition.
   Data General Corp.: In October it announced it would elminate
2,200 jobs, coming on the heels of a reduction in its work force
from 16,000 to 14,000 over the past two years.
   Prime Computer Inc.: Announced in October it would lay off 2,500
workers, or almost 20 percent of its work force, as part of a
restructuring of the minicomputer maker after its billion-dollar
buyout by J.M. Whitney &amp; Co., an investment firm.
</TEXT>
