<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     12-07 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices ended mixed Thursday as
heating oil staged another weather-related advance.
   The No. 2 heating oil contract for January delivery shot up 1.01
cents to 65.47 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
The contract traded as high as 65.80 cents during the session after
closing up 0.41 cent on Wednesday.
   Contracts for February through April delivery also gained while
longer-term contracts declined.
   Among other refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale
unleaded gasoline for January delivery, which gained 0.33 cent on
Wednesday, fell 0.36 cent to finish at 52.81 cents a gallon. Most
other contracts also declined.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the main grade
of U.S. crude oil, edged up 4 cents to $20.51 per 42-gallon barrel.
The contract traded as high at $20.65 during the session after
Wednesday's gain of 13 cents. Other contracts closed mixed.
   Energy analysts said cold weather as well as strength in
Europe's gasoil market continued to make U.S. heating oil
attractive to buyers. Heating oil's strength gave the overall
market a lift, they said.
   Low water levels in the Rhine River have created problems for
barges transporting gasoil, the European version of U.S. home
heating oil. Bullishness in Europe's gasoil market has trickled
into the U.S. market.
   ``Today saw continued strength in heating oil due to cold
weather here and in Europe and the low River Rhine,'' said Peter
Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders Futures
Inc.
   Richard Redoglio, energy analyst for Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures, said profit-taking helped depress prices in the gasoline
pits.
   ``People were selling gas against heating oil,'' Redoglio said.
</TEXT>
