<FIRST>u f AM-RadioSale     12-07 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radio Sale,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Broadcasting Buys Eight Radio Stations for $360 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Broadcasting Co. said Thursday it
had completed its previously-disclosed plans to buy eight
Metropolitan-Legacy radio stations in a $360 million deal that it
called the biggest ever in radio.
   The purchase gives Westinghouse Broadcasting 21 radio stations
with an average cumulative audience of 14.1 million people a week,
second only to the 15 million-plus commanded by the 21 stations
owned by Capital Cities-ABC Inc.
   Westinghouse Broadcasting, also known as Group W, is buying the
stations from Metropolitan Broadcasting Corp. and Legacy
Broadcasting, which are controlled by broadcaster and financier
Robert F.X. Sillerman.
   Sillerman and his partners will retain a minority interest in
Group W Radio, which a source familiar with the deal said was less
than 10 percent.
   Group W, which is an operating unit of Westinghouse Electric
Corp. of Pittsburgh, announced in April it had agreed to buy 10
Metropolitan-Legacy stations in a deal reportedly valued at about
$385 million.
   But in the meantime, Metropolitan found a local buyer for its
two radio stations in Minneapolis and they were dropped from the
deal with Group W.
   The newly-acquired stations are WNEW-FM in New York; WMMR-FM in
Philadelphia; WCRX-FM and WCPT-AM in Washington, D.C.; WLLZ-FM in
Detroit; KILT-AM and KILT-FM in Houston and KTWV-FM in Los Angeles.
   ``Our acquisition of these extremely successful stations allows
us to compete for radio advertising revenue in nine of the top 10
U.S. markets,'' said Burton B. Staniar, chairman of Group W.
   He said the addition of the youth-oriented FM radio stations in
New York, Los Angeles and Philadelphia to the company's AM
news-format stations in those cities will enable Westinghouse to
offer appealing package deals to advertisers in those markets.
   Staniar said the deal also gives Group W programming diversity
and size ``that makes our entry into the radio network and program
syndication businesses more financially attractive.''
   As it completed its purchase of the eight stations, Westinghouse
relinquished control of KODA-FM, its FM radio station in Houston.
Federal regulations prohibit companies from owning two FM radio
stations in the same market. The station was placed in a trust and
is being sold in a separate transaction to New York-based Command
Communications for $22 million.
   Group W Radio's other stations are: WBZ, Boston; WINS, New York;
KYW, Philadelphia; KDKA, Pittsburgh; WMAQ, Chicago; KQZY, Dallas;
KQXT, San Antonio; KMEO-AM and KMEO-FM, Phoenix; KFWB, Los Angeles;
KFBK-AM and KAER, Sacramento; and KJQY, San Diego.
   Westinghouse Broadcasting's other units are Group W Television,
which owns five network-affiliated television stations; Group W
Productions, a programming and synidication company, and Group W
Satellite Communications, a cable programming, marketing and
distribution business based in Stamford, Conn.
</TEXT>
