<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-07 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Market Plunge Send Precious Metals Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metals futures prices rose sharply Thursday on New
York's Commodity Exchange in reaction to a decline in prices on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   In other markets, grains and soybeans were lower; cotton
plunged; livestock and pork futures were mixed, and energy prices
were mostly lower.
   Gold settled $4.10 to $5.10 higher with the contract for
delivery in December at $410.00 a troy ounce; silver was 6.5 cents
to 7.2 cents higher with December at $5.623 a troy ounce.
   ``The sharp fall in the stock market caused a flight to quality
buying ... in the precious metals market,'' said analyst Jim Steel
of Refco Inc. in New York.
   Steel noted that many things have caused movement in precious
metals prices, including dollar strength or weakness, interest
rates and inflation.
   ``But what has given gold its bold moves (upward) have been the
declines in the stock market,'' he said
   Silver prices followed gold in Thursday's upward surge, helped
along by the perception that the metal has been sharply oversold in
recent sessions, Steel said.
   Cotton futures were sharply lower on the New York Cotton
Exchange as traders had difficulty unloading offerings because of a
lack of buyers.
   At one time, the March contract was down the limit before
recovering some losses, said analyst Ed Whitten of Balfour Maclaine
Corp in New York.
   Whitten noted that commission houses were active sellers as
prices moved below several support levels.
   Cotton was .23 cent to 1.55 cents lower with December at 63.97
cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower in sluggish
trading on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The slide in wheat prices was due to the release Wednesday of
the National Weather Service's six- to 10-day forecast, which calls
for precipitation in the winter wheat crop areas, said analyst
Susan Leighty of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Wheat futures received little support from news the U.S.
Department of Agriculture has approved an offer by the Soviet Union
for 410,000 metric tons of wheat under the department's Export
Enhancement Program.
   Under the program, private exporters can sell U.S. commodities
at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in some markets and
collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Corn futures traded in a narrow range, finishing lower as
professionals and commission houses liquidated their long positions.
   Soybean prices continue to be weighed down by a lack of export
business and continuing good planting conditions in South America.
   Wheat was { cent to 2} cents lower with December at $4.08 a
bushel; corn was 2{ cents lower to a \ cent higher with December at
$2.36\ a bushel; oats were a \ cent lower to a { cent higher with
December at $1.44 a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents to 7\ cents
lower with January at $5.75{ a bushel.
   Energy futures were mixed on the New York Mercantile Exchange as
prices fluctuated widely during moderate trading.
   Heating oil continued to provide strength to the market, as
another blast of cold weather is expected in the Northeast in
coming days, analsyts say.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 3 cents lower to 4 cents
higher with January at $20.51 a barrel; heating oil was .30 cent
lower to 1.01 cents higher with January at 65.47 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .36 cent lower to .07 cent higher with
January at 52.81 cent a gallon.
   Livestock futures were mostly lower and pork futures down
sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Pork belly futures were down the limit in a wave of commission
house selling. The selling was prompted by continued concern over
the large amount of bellies going into storage and accelerated by
the activation of sell-stops.
   Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .20 cent higher with December
at 75.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .03
cent higher with January at 82.95 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent
lower to .72 cent higher with December at 51.22 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were 2 cents lower with February at 54.45 cents
a pound.
</TEXT>
