<FIRST>u b AM-Manville     12-07 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manville,0300</SECOND>
<UNK>Manville Suspends Discussions on Stock Repurchase Offer</UNK>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp. has announced that it has suspended
talks with the Manville Personal Injury Settlement Trust and will
not pursue the company's announced offer to repurchase $500 million
of Manville preferred stock from the trust.
   Manville said talks will continue with the trust on ways to
improve the trust's financial flexibility and increase value for
all shareholders.
   Cathy Fischer, a spokesman for the trust in Washington, D.C.,
said the trust was trying to raise cash to pay claims. She said
Manville has stipulations on how stock can be sold to raise money,
and Manville wanted to buy some of its stock back. However, the two
sides disagreed over how much that stock was worth.
   She said the fund is scheduled to receive profit-sharing funds
in 1991 based on 1990 profits, but in the meantime, the fund is
running short on cash.
   ``We're exploring our options,'' she said.
   Fischer said Manville wanted to help, ``But we're dealing with
reality. We want to do what's right for the trust fund,'' she said.
   Dave Samson, spokesman for the company, said the two sides
disagreed on some of the restrictive covenants but declined to be
specific.
   The trust was created as part of Manville's bankruptcy
reorganization to compensate victims of asbestos, who had filed
suit against the company. The trust was created Nov. 28, 1988, when
Manville emerged from its Chapter 11 reorganization proceedings.
   So far, the trust has paid more than 15,000 personal injury
claims totaling more than $600 million.
   The trust has assets including 50 percent of Manville's new
common stock, convertible preferred stock, a $1.8 billion bond, and
20 percent of net profits, beginning in 1992.
</TEXT>
