<FIRST>u f AM-Shearson 1stLd-Writethru f0181 12-07 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shearson, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0181,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson Stock Falls Amid Reports of Recapitalization</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th pvs to UPDATE with closing stock price; PICKS UP 9th
graf pvs, `Analysts pegged...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. stock fell sharply
Thursday amid reports of a huge recapitalization plan that would
inject up to $1 billion into the ailing brokerage.
   Shearson has been under increasing pressure in recent weeks to
take steps to improve its profitability and avoid a credit
downgrading that would tarnish the firm's reputation and increase
its borrowing costs.
   American Express Co., which owns 61 percent of Shearson,
reportedly is planning a public sale of 10 million to 22 million
shares of Shearson stock and a direct investment of about $300
million to raise new capital.
   In addition, Revlon Inc. Chairman Ronald O. Perelman reportedly
is holding talks about buying a 9.9 percent stake in Shearson for
about $250 million.
   Lawrence A. Armour, an American Express senior vice president,
confirmed his company is ``reviewing a number of options'' in
regard to Shearson. But he said it would be ``inappropriate to
discuss any details.''
   Armour said the review process has been under way for several
weeks.
   Shearson spokesman Michael O'Neill declined comment on the
recapitalization reports.
   Shearson closed down $1.75, or about 10.6 percent, at $14.75 a
share in New York Stock Exchange trading. The stock rose $1.37{
Wednesday on reports that Perelman might buy up to a 20 percent
interest in the company.
   Analysts pegged Thursday's drop to the lower stake Perelman
would have in the latest purported proposal _ reducing the
possibility of a takeover _ and to the potential dilution of shares
under any new stock issue.
   `There's no way the common shareholder comes out well in this,''
said analyst Lawrence Eckenfelder of Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., in San Francisco.
   Shearson stock has slumped for several months because of poor
earnings reports. The company began searching for new capital after
Moody's Investors Service in October said it was considering
downgrading its credit on $4.8 billion in long-term Shearson debt.
   Shearson recently began laying off 800 workers, reducing the
size of the nation's second-largest brokerage to 35,700, reshuffled
its senior management and slashed stockbroker commissions for the
first time in 15 years.
   A downgrading by Moody's would increase Shearson's cost of
borrowing by about $10 million to $15 million a year, Eckenfelder
said. Securities firms borrow heavily to finance finance trading
and other activities.
   More important, analysts said, American Express wants to avoid
any loss of reputation. ``There's a sense that it's important for
the owners to maintain Shearson as a top credit,'' Eckenfelder said.
   Under the reported recapitalization proposal, American Express
would reduce its Shearson holding to under 50 percent through the
new offering and the Perelman deal. That would allow the credit
card, travel and financial service company to remove Shearson from
its financial statements.
   Eckenfelder said selling securities in a brokerage might prove
difficult because of slumping conditions throughout the industry.
   The proposed recapitalization would dilute the holdings of
Shearson's second-largest stockholder, Nippon Life Insurance of
Japan, to about 10 percent from 13 percent.
   The proposal was reported in The New York Times and The Wall
Street Journal, which cited unidentified sources.
   Earlier reports said Perelman would have been able to obtain
about 20 percent of Shearson's stock if he exercised all of his
stock options under the deal as originally proposed. But the Times
said the proposed transaction was altered to make it less complex.
   While any such deal would provide needed capital for Shearson,
some analysts have cautioned that further dividing the ownership of
Shearson among three or more large outsiders could prove to be a
headache for executives under pressure to turn around the firm's
slumping profits.
   Moody's said it was mulling a possible credit rating downgrade
for Shearson's bonds and commercial paper due to the firm's low
level of capital, low profits and exposure in commercial real
estate loans and investments, as well as the general slump in
brokerage activity.
</TEXT>
