<DOCNO> AP891207-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Pennzoil-Chevron 1stLd-Writethru   12-07 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pennzoil-Chevron, 1st Ld-Writethru,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennzoil Uses Texaco Settlement To Buy Chevron Stake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to CORRECT that Pennzoil not considering
buying up to 18 percent of Chevron stock; CORRECT stock price; ADD analyst
comment; picks up 7th graf, However, Ron ...; SUBS last graf to add quarterly
revenue.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   By JOHN A. BOLT=
</TEXT>
<NOTE>AP Business Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennzoil Co., using cash won in a lawsuit against
Texaco Inc., revealed Thursday it had purchased $2.1 billion worth
of stock in Chevron Corp., the nation's fourth largest oil company.
   Pennzoil's purchase amounts to about 8.8 percent of Chevron, and
Pennzoil said it was considering spending another $500 million to
buy more Chevron stock. That would boost its stake to more than 10
percent and use up all the net proceeds of its payment from Texaco.
   The disclosure came in a letter to shareholders and filings with
the federal Security and Exchange Commission.
   ``This position has been acquired as a long-term investment,''
Houston-based Pennzoil told shareholders. ``Pennzoil has no
interest in attempting to take over Chevron.''
   The company said it analyzed the possibility of buying up to 18
percent of Chevron's stock but ``has no current plans or
proposals'' to do so.
   The announcement helped deflate takeover speculation that had
surrounded Chevron. Chevron stock dropped $5.25 to close at $66.75
in composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Pennzoil rose 62{ cents to close at $83.25 as some investors
speculated that Chevron might try to turn the tables and buy
Pennzoil's stake or even buy all of Pennzoil.
   ``The perception by some investors is that Chevron's response
will be to turn around and buy Pennzoil to make the problem go
away. No one believes for a minute that Pennzoil intends to buy
Chevron,'' said analyst Thomas Escott at Rauscher Pierce Refsnes
Inc., a Dallas investment firm.
   ``There isn't any way Pennzoil's going to come in and take
Chevron over,'' agreed another analyst, George Gaspar of Robert W.
Baird &amp; Co. in Milwaukee.
   However, Ron Londe with A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons in St. Louis said
the purchase nevertheless could be a good move. ``Pennzoil's
notorious for being a very astute investor.''
   San Francisco-based Chevron declined to comment on the
announcement.
   Only Wednesday, Chevron announced a $1 billion sale of 14.1
million shares of common stock to an employee stock owner plan that
could make any takeover more difficult. The stock, about 5 percent
of the company's outstanding shares, was added to 11 percent
already held by an employee profit-sharing plan.
   Chevron, which paid $13.3 billion to buy Gulf Oil four years
ago, has seen its stock climb in recent weeks on rumors of a
possible takeover bid, with Pennzoil mentioned as a likely suitor.
   Last year, Pennzoil received $3 billion in an out-of-court
settlement of its lawsuit against Texaco over Getty Oil Co. in 1984
and observers have been watching closely to see what the company
would do with its windfall.
   Pennzoil had sued Texaco claiming Texaco's 1984 acquisition of
Getty Oil Co. interfered with its plans to buy part of Getty. In
1985 a Houston jury awarded Pennzoil $10.3 billion. Texaco appealed
but eventually settled with Pennzoil for the smaller amount.
   ``Over the past several months, your management and board of
directors have reviewed numerous business situations in an effort
to find an investment opportunity similar to Pennzoil's former
stake in Getty Oil Co.,'' said the letter signed by Pennzoil
Chairman J. Hugh Liedtke and President Randal B. McDonald.
   ``After thorough study, we have concluded that Chevron is by far
the most appealing company in the entire spectrum and particularly
in its peer group.''
   Noting Chevron's profitability has not matched its market
position, Pennzoil said, ``Chevron has demonstrated expertise in
dealing with strictly financial affairs. In the past, it has not
seemed to focus that expertise on its operational divisions. If it
now does so, we believe the results could be pleasantly
surprising.''
   Pennzoil spokesman Robert Harper said the company had until the
end of 1990 to reinvest the money from Texaco to avoid tax
liabilities.
   Pennzoil said it believed it could provide ``constructive
support'' to Chevron Chairman Kenneth T. Derr's plans to improve
the company's performance.
   Chevron, rich in oil and gas reserves and a high-performing
chemicals unit, had sales in 1988 of $28.9 billion, down from $29.1
billion in 1987. Earnings last year totaled $1.8 billion, or $5.17
a share, up about 40 percent from $1.3 billion, or $3.65 a share.
   In its latest quarter, Chevron's earnings edged down to $417
million, or $1.22 a share, from $420 million, or $1.23 a share, a
year earlier.
   Pennzoil, whose main business is in motor oil and sulphur,
reported third quarter income of $35.4 million, or 87 cents per
share, compared to $39.3 million, 93 cents, for the same period a
year ago. Revenue rose to $644 million in the third quarter
compared to $617 million in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
