<FIRST>r f BC-FirstInterstate     12-07 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-First Interstate,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Interstate Announces Plan to Dump Problem Assets in Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Interstate Bancorp, hammered by loan
losses at out-of-state subsidiaries, said Thursday it would speed
up its program to sell bad loans in Texas and add $400 million to
its reserves to cover the costs.
   First Interstate, whose Arizona unit lost $174 million last
quarter and whose Texas subsidiary also has shown big losses in the
past, also said it intended to offer 7.5 million shares of new
common stock to raise about $400 million.
   First Interstate, the nation's largest retail banking system
with offices in 21 states, said the program will cut the costs of
carrying the bad loans. That, combined with existing unused tax
benefits, should provide up to $367 million of potential future tax
benefits, the company said.
   Of the $400 million in added reserves, $300 million was to go
toward the program to eliminate the bad loans in Texas, and another
$100 million ``to address the risk inherent in the company's real
estate portfolio.''
   First Interstate showed a loss of $15.5 million last quarter, or
57 cents per share, after its First Interstate Bank of Arizona took
a $350 million provision for loan losses due to plunging real
estate values in the state.
   It was the first quarterly loss for the big holding company
since the third quarter of 1988, when First Interstate posted a
$214 million loss because of loan losses in Texas banking
operations and restructuring.
</TEXT>
