<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 2347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Abbott-FDA     12-07 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Abbott-FDA,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analyst: Government Report Sees `Potential Problems' At Drug Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of Abbott Laboratories stock slipped
Thursday after a brokerage firm said a government report showed one
of the company's drug plants might be ``a little sloppy'' in
adhering to federal standards.
   Abbott stock closed at $67.12{ a share, down $1.25, in New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   ``We didn't tell people to sell, we just said here is some
information about something that is going on,'' said Michael
Harshbarger, vice president and senior health care analyst at
Chicago Corp., a brokerage.
   A day earlier, Harshbarger obtained through the Freedom of
Information Act a copy of a 41-page U.S. Food and Drug
Administration report on an Abbott facility in Lake County that
produces drugs given intravenously.
   ``Our consultants pointed out where it looked like standards had
been becoming a little sloppy _ where it looked like there could be
potential problems,'' Harshbarger said.
   He said 56 citations were listed in the report, written after an
FDA inspection July 5 through Nov. 3 at the plant. He said 80
percent of the issues cited were ``nit-picking, minor problems and
20 percent potentially had some serious implications.''
   He declined to be specific.
   Marie Ekvall, consumer affairs officer at the FDA regional
office, said: ``The only thing we can say at this point is it's an
ongoing investigation. This report is observations, and from it the
regulatory people have to determine what type of regulatory action
has to be taken.''
   Harshbarger said the brokerage firm's sales staff was told in a
meeting Thursday morning to advise clients of the report.
   Abbott spokeswoman Cathy Babington said later Thursday that the
report's observations were technical in nature, but she didn't
elaborate.
   ``The bottom line for customers and patients is that the
products are safe and they are effective for what they are intended
to be used for,'' Babington said.
   She said the plant referred to in the report is ``one small
section of one building on an Abbott campus that has many, many
facilities.''
</TEXT>
