<FIRST>r f BC-CanadianAutoProduction     12-07 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Canadian Auto Production,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford, Chrysler Shutting Canadian Plants Briefly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian subsidiaries of Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp. said Thursday they were temporarily closing some
factories because of slumping U.S. vehicle demand.
   The announcements came a day after General Motors Corp.'s
Canadian subsidiary said it would temporarily stop production at
four of its assembly plants.
   Chrysler of Canada Ltd. spokesman Alan McPhee said the company
was closing its Pillette Road full-size van assembly plant in
Windsor, Ontario, for two weeks beginning Jan. 2, affecting about
2,200 hourly workers.
   Ford of Canada Ltd. spokesman Jim Hartford said his company was
closing three engine plants and an iron casting plant in Windsor
for the week of Dec. 18, affecting about 3,000 workers.
   On Wednesday, General Motors of Canada Ltd. said it was closing
two car assembly plants in Oshawa, Ontario, and a van assembly
plant in Scarborough, Ontario, for the week of Jan. 2. It also said
its car plant in Ste. Therese, Quebec, would be closed for two
weeks beginning Jan. 2.
   This month, GM of Canada will temporarily stop production at two
component plants.
   GM's moves affects about 17,700 workers.
