<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0319 12-07 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0319,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Share Prices Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning figures, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was up against the Japanese yen
Friday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
declined in morning trading.
   The dollar closed the morning session at 144.23 yen, down from
its opening of 144.32 yen but up 0.12 yen from Thursday's close
here of 144.13 yen. It was traded in a narrow range of 144.21 to
144.40 yen.
   The dollar's higher opening in Tokyo followed a similar
overnight upswing in New York, where it ended at 144.30 yen.
   The mark was dropping back against the dollar after sales of the
German currency by Asian speculators in Sydney, said Minori
Takeuchi, a trader at Chemical Bank.
   Some speculators in Tokyo seemed to be waiting until the dollar
rose more before selling to buy yen, Takeuchi said. Japanese
Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto indicated a relative lack of
concern with the dollar's strength above the 144.00 yen level at a
regular press conference Friday morning.
   ``Inside a delicate situation we are taking a delicate look,''
he said. The remark was seen as indicating the ministry is not
alarmed by the dollar's recent rise.
   Most market players were awaiting the release of the U.S.
jobless rate for November due out in Washington later Friday,
traders said.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost
103.09 points, or 0.27 percent, closing the morning session at
37,755.02.
   It had gained 203.82 points to a record-high closing of
37,858.11 Thursday.
   A trader at Kleinwort Benson securities said he didn't believe
the market's recent rally, in which it advanced for all but 2 of 22
days, had ended despite the drop.
   ``There are a lot of people still waiting to put money into the
market,'' said the trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
